<FIRST>r i PM-OlivierAwards     01-30 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Olivier Awards,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Theater Awards Honor International Stars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Shirley Valentine,'' a Broadway-bound comedy, and
Leonard Bernstein's classic 1956 Broadway musical ``Candide'' took
top honors in this year's Laurence Olivier awards.
   The theater awards, presented Sunday, are London's most
prestigious.
   Sir Alec Guinness received a lifetime achievement award during
the nationally televised ceremony, and representatives of two
winning companies from the Soviet Union _ the Kirov Ballet and the
Maly Theater of Leningrad _ delivered acceptance speeches in Russian.
   Guinness, who is playing a Soviet diplomat in the American play
``A Walk in the Woods,'' told the black-tie audience at the Dominion
Theater ``the theater was my first love and it will certainly be my
last'' as he received his award from guest of honor Princess Diana.
   ``Shirley Valentine,'' Willy Russell's one-woman play about an
emotionally unfulfilled Liverpool housewife, was named comedy of the
year. Pauline Collins, its lone performer, was chosen actress of the
year in a new play or comedy.
   ``Hang in there, girls; it may yet happen,'' said an exuberant
Collins, best-known for playing the maid Sarah on the long-running
series ``Upstairs, Downstairs.'' The actress will make her Broadway
debut when the Russell play opens Feb. 16 at New York's Booth
Theater.
   In a noticeably weak year for musicals, a limited-run revival of
``Candide'' won for musical of the year and for actress of the year
in a musical _ Patricia Routledge.
   Mickey Rooney and Ann Miller, both of whom were nominated for the
commercially unsuccessful London run of the broadway ``Sugar
Babies,'' failed to win an award.
   Timberlake Wertenbaker's ``Our Country's Good,'' a play set in a
community of Australian convicts, was named play of the year over
such works as David Hare's ``The Secret Rapture,'' which opens in
New York next fall, and ``A Walk in the Woods'' by Lee Blessing.
   ``Our Country's Good'' netted the actor of the year award for its
star David Haig.
   Unusually, none of the shows to win the top three awards is still
running in London.
   The Royal Shakespeare's Company's ``Titus Andronicus,'' long
considered one of Shakespeare's most difficult plays, won awards for
its director Deborah Warner and its star, Brian Cox, named best
actor in a revival.
   The award for actress of the year in a revival went to Harriet
Walter for three plays at the Royal Shakespeare Company: ``Twelfth
Night,'' ``Three Sisters'' and ``A Question of Geography.''
   The international flavor set by the Soviet awards for ballet and
theater continued with the award for outstanding achievement in
opera, which went to Romanian singer Leontina Vaduva, who starred in
``Manon'' at the Royal Opera House and delivered her acceptance
speech in French.
   The award for outstanding supporting performance _ by a man or
woman _ went to Eileen Atkins for two plays at The National Theater:
Shakespeare's ``Cymbeline'' and Harold Pinter's ``Mountain
Language.''
   The awards are named after the 81-year-old actor celebrated as
Britain's greatest. Olivier gave the world its definitive Hamlet,
Henry V and Richard III.
</TEXT>
