<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-ChinaTechnology     01-30 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China Technology,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Renewal of US-China Technology Agreement Stalled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Renewal of a U.S.-China technology agreement is
being delayed because of Chinese opposition to copyright protection
for computer software and patent protection for drugs, American
officials say.
   The decade-old accord is to expire at the end of this month, but
a State Department official involved with the talks said it is
likely the earlier pact will be extended in hopes of reaching
agreement through additional negotiations.
   This official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified,
said it was ``too strong'' to say the talks were at an impasse.
   ``We've exchanged information and talked a lot, but we've only
had one negotiating session,'' he said. ``We certainly anticipate
that we'll have some additional negotiating sessions, trying to
bring our positions closer together.''
   He said further talks are expected next month in Beijing,
following up on a session held in Washington on Jan. 12-13.
   At that meeting, the delegations were headed by Peter J. de Vos,
deputy assistant secretary of state for science and technology
affairs, and Duan Ruichun, deputy director of China's Department of
Science and Technology.
   President Bush will be traveling to China next month, but there
is no indication whether the science and technology agreement is
among the issues he plans to raise with the Chinese.
   The Chinese have taken the position that there is no provision in
their law for copyright protection of computer software. They made
it clear that ``they would not sign any agreement that said we agree
that software is protected by copyright,'' said Marybeth Peters, an
official with the U.S. Copyright Office.
   ``They told us they will not enact any kind of a law _ at this
point, and maybe in the future _ that says computer software is
protected by copyright, and even in the agreement, it may not say
`copyright,''' Ms. Peters said.
   The Chinese have contended that software exporters should rely on
contracts with buyers to protect their programs.
   That position has drawn sharp criticism from the Computer and
Business Equipment Manufacturers Association, a Washington-based
computer industry trade group, which points to a growing number of
complaints about software piracy in China.
   ``Contracts do nothing to impede third-party infringers,'' said
John L. Pickitt, president of CBEMA. ``The most effective and
internationally accepted protection for software is copyright.''
   Some U.S. software manufacturers have responded to the stalemate
over copyright by deciding to halt further sales in China.
   ``The risks for U.S. software exporters may have risen to a level
where participation in the PRC (People's Republic of China) market
is not justified for them,'' Pickitt said.
   On pharmaceuticals, Chinese patent law will protect the specific
process for manufacturing a drug, but not the drug itself.
   Ms. Peters said that ``since in many cases there are many ways of
processing the same drug, that really is not very effective
protection.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 0124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     01-30 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Likely Enforcement of Erosion Rules Questioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private conservationist says federal programs
are already having an impact on soil erosion but there are some
fears that the Agriculture Department may have trouble enforcing the
rules in the future.
   One other area of concern is the old problem of city sprawl, of
rapidly growing roads, parking lots and housing tracts eating up
millions of acres of some of the nation's best farmland.
   Robert J. Gray, policy director for the non-profit,
Washington-based American Farmland Trust, said ``the jury is still
out'' on how strict USDA will be in enforcing the 1985 farm law's
requirements to protect land and water resources.
   Among others, those require farmers to have conservation plans
completed to help protect and land and water resources, or risk
losing price supports and other federal benefits.
   ``They claim that they are going to have all the plans in place
by 1990,'' Gray said last week.
   Gray's comments followed release of an updated USDA report
outlining goals through 1997. At the top was soil erosion, a
longstanding priority, with water quality given equal ranking.
   The report said the 1985 law's Conservation Reserve Program, or
CRP, which calls for 40 million to 45 million acres of highly
erodible cropland to be planted with protective grass and trees by
the end of 1990, already is saving 530 million tons of soil each
year, thus reducing total erosion by 15 percent.
   By 1995, the report said, CRP could be saving 800 million tons of
soil annually.
   ``It they do that, then we're almost a third reduction in
erosion, which is really significant,'' Gray said.
   The final report didn't make a big point of land loss to urban
development, but neither did it reject some of the assertions made
when a draft of the report was released for public review in 1987.
   In the 1987 document, USDA said city sprawl and other
non-agricultural uses were gobbling up farmland at an annual rate
that could equal the size of Missouri by the year 2030.
   About 1.5 million acres are converted to non-agricultural use
each year, and 64 percent of that is cropland. At that rate, the
1987 report said, the nation's cropland base could be reduced by
nearly 48 million acres, or 12 percent, between 1982 and 2030.
   Gray said the figures in the draft report are still meaningful
and of concern to many professionals. Some authorities have
discounted the creep of roads, housing, parks and other
non-agricultural uses on grounds that the United States has much
land that could be put into food production if needed.
   One of the arguments includes the CRP land itself, millions of
acres that are being taken from production for 10 years. But Gray
said those acres for the most part are marginal to begin with _ land
that is too fragile for crop use.
   Meanwhile, he said, when cities grow or new roads are needed,
those spread across farmland whether it's marginal or prime, and
it's often some of the best, most productive land in the area.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An analysis by the Agriculture Department shows
that the nation's farmer-owned cooperatives still have a long way to
go in recovering from the sharp business declines of recent years.
   In calendar 1987, according to an annual review, co-op business
volume rose slightly to $59.3 billion from $58.4 billion in 1986.
But that was still far below the record high of $73 billion reached
in 1984.
   Randall E. Torgerson, administrator of the department's
Agricultural Cooperative Service, said the 1987 increase was held
down mostly by the reduced number of crop acres in production that
year.
   Overall, prices received by farmers in 1987 were up slightly, but
the number of cooperatives continued a long downward trend.
   Total co-op business volume includes marketing, or the value of
products sold; the sales of farm supplies such as fertilizer,
chemicals, fuels and feed; and receipts from services such as
trucking, storage, grain drying and ginning.
   Torgerson said the drop in the number of farm cooperatives to
5,174 in 1987 from 5,369 in 1986 was due mainly to reorganizations,
including mergers, consolidations and acquisitions, and to some
co-ops going out of business.
   Memberships totaled 4.39 million in 1987, about the same as in
1986. Many farmers belong to more than one co-op.
   The average membership per co-op increased to an average of 848
in 1987 from 820 the previous year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand is a major producer of tobacco in Asia
as well as an established market for the United States, although
there is ``great uncertainty'' about future sales, says an
Agriculture Department report.
   ``Unlike some of its neighbors in Asia where trade liberalization
has already led to widespread structural changes, Thailand's
cigarette industry still enjoys the protection afforded by a virtual
ban on imports,'' the report said. ``As a result, a thriving black
market exists in higher quality foreign cigarettes.''
   The report by the department's Foreign Agricultural Service said
cigarette use is increasing in Thailand and may have accelerated
last year by as much as 10 percent from 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 0132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NumberOne Bjt   01-30 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Number One, Bjt,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush Still Adjusting to Being at the Top</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 12 years, George Bush dreamed and worked to
reach the heights of his chosen profession. Now he is there and,
like many others who go from being No. 2 to being No. 1, he
sometimes finds himself ill at ease.
   Not often, he says.
   ``There's still the wonder of it all,'' Bush said at his first
presidential news conference Friday. ``It still feels different. But
not surprising.''
   ``He's enjoying the job,'' said presidential press secretary
Marlin Fitzwater. ``The only problem is containing his enthusiasm.''
   But sometimes ...
   There are a couple of examples, including one that Bush told on
himself.
   Minutes after he took his oath at the Capitol, Bush told
congressional leaders, he heard the House sergeant at arms call out,
``Mr. President.''
   As he had for eight years as vice president, Bush waited for
President Reagan to respond. But President Reagan was now former
President Reagan. The call was for President Bush.
   A poke in the ribs from first lady Barbara Bush got the point
across.
   Reporters observed the other instance. Reagan had left Bush a
note in the Oval Office, and they asked the new president to read it
to them.
   Before doing so, Bush turned to Fitzwater. ``Am I violating any
rules here, Marlin?'' he asked.
   ``They're your rules, sir,'' said a reporter.
   ``Oh, I set the rules,'' Bush said. Then he went on to read the
note aloud.
   So, does the new president have the willies?
   Not at all, says Fitzwater. ``He's very excited by the whole
situation.''
   On the other hand, says a political scientist who doubles in
psychology, Bush would be an exception to the rule if he didn't
experience some stress in a job he has tried for so long to get.
   ``Psychologically, it is often rather overwhelming, because their
whole life is built around the struggle to get there,'' said Gary
Weaver, a professor of international relations at American
University who has also taught psychology.
   ``Once they get there, it's over with.''
   It doesn't seem to be over with for Bush, who has been setting a
hectic pace since his inauguration.
   But for some, said Weaver, the consequences can be much more
severe than just forgetting who sets the rules or not realizing who
is being addressed.
   ``Even if you look at articles on suicides of famous people _ and
I'm not suggesting that at all _ what we do find is that it very
seldom occurs as they are struggling to get to the top; it occurs
when they get to the top and are overwhelmed.''
   So, although Bush certainly has shown no signs as serious as
that, said Weaver, ``I guess you could say that for him it's
probably pretty overwhelming, because you know he's been struggling
for a long time, and one ought to assume that there would be some
personality change once he gets there. He's not going to be the old
George Bush.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   W. Dale Nelson covered the Reagan-Bush
administration from the White House for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
