<FIRST>r w PM-TeamstersSuit     01-30 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teamsters Suit,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Teamsters Leaders Quit In Exchange For Dismissal From Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Teamsters leaders quit their posts to avoid
trial in a racketeering case alleging close ties between the union
and organized crime, but the Teamsters' governing board rejected a
government proposal to settle the entire case.
   The resignations and rejection of the proposed settlement came on
a weekend that included a hastily arranged Saturday meeting in
Washington between Teamsters President William J. McCarthy and the
vice presidents of the nation's largest union.
   It was at that session that the Teamsters general executive board
voted to reject what two union sources said was a proposed
settlement calling for internal union election reform and the
resignations of a handful of the vice presidents.
   That same day, Ronald Holmes of Detroit and John H. Cleveland of
Washington informed McCarthy they were resigning as vice presidents
of the 1.6-million member union.
   Holmes made a public announcement of his decision; Cleveland's
decision to quit was confirmed privately Sunday by a union official
after a Justice Department spokeswoman said both men quit as part of
agreements with prosecutors.
   The spokeswoman, Deborah Corley of the U.S. attorney's office in
New York, said Holmes and Cleveland reached oral agreements with
prosecutors that they would be dropped as defendants in the suit if
they resigned.
   Prosecutors this week will ask a judge to approve the deals, Ms.
Corley said Sunday. She would neither confirm nor deny the existence
of a government offer to settle the entire case.
   Both Holmes and Cleveland were on the losing side last summer
when McCarthy defeated union Secretary-Treasurer Weldon Mathis in
the race to succeed Jackie Presser as Teamsters president. Presser,
before his death, had designated Mathis as his choice for the job
but McCarthy won on a 9-8 vote.
   McCarthy, of Arlington, Mass., was head of the Teamsters in New
England and one of the union's 16 international vice presidents when
the suit was filed in New York seven months ago.
   It alleges that more than two dozen reputed organized crime
figures have had dealings in Teamsters affairs, including using mob
influence to control union elections.
   The suit is scheduled for trial Feb. 27. It asks that the court
remove the Teamsters leadership, place the union under trusteeship
and prohibit the alleged mob figures from any future dealings with
the union.
   Twenty-six reputed organized crime figures were named in the suit
but 10 were dropped as defendants last year after signing agreements
in which they promised to avoid dealings with the union.
</TEXT>
