<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0773 01-30 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0773,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains, Stock Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar. Pick
up 5th pvs, ``The index's...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained strong ground against the Japanese
yen Monday, while share prices reversed an earlier trend and plunged
in reaction to the falling yen.
   The dollar closed at 129.73 yen, up 1.08 yen from last Friday's
finish of 128.65 yen. The currency opened the week at 129.58 yen and
traded in a range of 129.55-130.03 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues shed 111.57 points, or 0.35 percent, for 31,567.50
by the end of the trading day. The main market barometer had closed
at a record 31,679.07 Saturday after winning 32.94 points during the
half-day session.
   The Nikkei had gained during trading in the morning, but fell as
institutional investors stepped to the sidelines in concern over the
yen's decline on the foreign exchange market, dealers said.
   The index's recent rapid rise also made participants shy away
from major moves, said one trader with a major securities firm in
Tokyo.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's jump at the start of Tokyo
trading followed a similar trend on overseas markets at the close of
trading last week, said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo.
   ``The dollar is still strong although the U.S. GNP figure was not
that good,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The currency's surge on overseas markets has made Japanese
investors realize the dollar's strength despite the
lower-than-expected GNP figure, which prompted their buying Monday,
the dealer added.
   According to the U.S. Commerce Department Friday, the country's
gross national product, the total value of all goods and services
produced, grew by 2 percent in the last quarter of 1988, down from
2.5 percent in the previous three-month period. It grew 3.8 percent
during 1988, up from 3.6 percent in 1987, the department's report
said.
</TEXT>
