<FIRST>b a AM-TransportCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0444 01-30 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transport Crash, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0444,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Alaska Plane Crash Kills At Least Seven</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with seventh death; picks up
5th graf, `It was ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRBANKS, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military transport flying 18 Canadian
special services soldiers to the U.S. military's massive ``Brim
Frost'' exercises crashed late Sunday, killing at least seven
aboard, authorities said.
   The Hercules C-130 carrying eight crewmen and 10 paratroopers
crashed into a snowbank and broke in two just short of the runway at
Fort Wainwright's airfield southeast of Fairbanks, said U.S. Army
Capt. Jim Rodgers.
   The crash killed at least seven, said Rodgers. Army Maj. Sherrell
Mock initially reported nine dead.
   Five were seriously injured and six sustained minor injuries,
said Army Maj. Jim Tillman. They were being treated at Bassett Army
Community Hospital.
   It was to have been the second of three Canadian planes to land
at the airport, authorities said.
   The plane's last contact with the control tower was at 6:47 p.m.
(10:47 p.m. EST). It crashed a few minutes later.
   With temperatures at minus 48 degrees, emergency vehicles
careened through heavy ice fog to reach the crash site.
   There was no evidence of fire.
   The first of the three Canadian planes landed safely at
Wainwright. The third Canadian plane was diverted to Fairbank's
civilian airport.
   Canadian Forces spokesman Maj. Luigi Rossetto in Edmonton,
Alberta, said the plane had left from Edmonton's Namao Base.
   The soldiers belonged to Force Mobile Command and were part of a
500-man paratroop force that was to support the 1st Brigade, 6th
Infantry Division (Light), in a major land battle that is the
centerpiece of the Brim Frost ground exercises near Fairbanks.
   About 26,000 servicemen, 120 aircraft and 1,000 vehicles from the
U.S. Army, Air Force, Marines, Coast Guard, National Guard, reserve
units and Canadian Forces are participating in Brim Frost '89. The
$15 million cold-weather training exercise began Jan. 20, and is
scheduled to continue through Feb. 1.
   The giant C-130s, which have wingspans of more than 130 feet, is
a workhorse of the military fleet and is used to transport troops
and equipment. They were first delivered in 1956 and have been
involved in several crashes in recent years.
   In June, a C-130 plunged into a soybean field and burst into a
fireball about a mile short of the airport in Greenville, Miss.,
killing six Air National Guardsmen aboard as they completed a series
of touch-and-go landings.
   A C-130 practicing touch-and-go landings crashed in September
1986 at Fort Campbell, Ky., killing three of the five National
Guardsmen aboard. A survivor said the plane had lost an engine.
   In March 1985, a C-130 from Little Rock crashed near Fort Hood,
Texas, killing six crewmen.
   Before that, seven airmen were killed when a C-130 exploded and
crashed near Judsonia, Ark., on May 12, 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua     01-30 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega to Announce 1989 Economic Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega can expect
little support from Nicaragua's business community _ support he
sorely needs to salvage an economy in crisis _ as he unveils his
government's economic plan for 1989.
   The austerity package Ortega was to announce today reportedly
includes a three-month wage and price freeze aimed at curbing
inflation, which the president says reached 20,000 percent last year.
   The Sandinista government has desperately sought the support of
capitalists and workers to brake Nicaragua's rapid slide into
economic chaos.
   ``There's a general awareness that the problem belongs to the
whole country,'' and that the government alone cannot rescue the
economy, said Bayardo Arce, a member of the ruling Sandinista
National Directorate.
   ``We must establish a harmony of interests, outlining the
responsibilities of the government, private enterprise and workers,
so we can face the country's problems,'' he said in an interview.
   On Dec. 31, the president announced sweeping budget cuts for the
Defense Ministry and security forces. The government has not said
how many jobs will be eliminated as a result of the cuts.
   Opposition leader Enrique Bolanos, a cotton grower and former
president of the Superior Council of Private Enterprise, said
Nicaraguan business leaders would not support the plan because they
distrust the Sandinistas.
   ``The government is saying to us, `We're drowning, toss us a
lifesaver,''' Bolanos said in an interview. ``But this time all
we're going to throw them is an anvil, so they finish sinking.''
   Ortega has fared little better with labor organizations.
   A meeting Saturday between Ortega and labor groups that was to be
open to the news media suddenly was closed, indicating negotiations
were not going as smoothly as the president had hoped.
   During a similar meeting Jan. 15, which was open to the media,
labor leaders complained about numerous layoffs of government
workers.
   Sharp currency devaluations and official price hikes have cut
Nicaraguans' purchasing power. This month, the official exchange
rate has gone from 920 cordobas to the dollar to 2,300 cordobas per
dollar. The minimum wage is 3,748 cordobas a day, about $1.63.
   The price of a liter of milk rose from about 54 cents at the
beginning of the month to 87 cents. Effective today, a gallon of
gasoline sells for $2.08, up from 87 cents.
   The Sandinistas blame Nicaragua's economic crisis on the war with
U.S.-supported Contra rebels that began in 1981. The two sides
signed a tentative cease-fire in March, but a permanent truce
remains elusive.
   The government also says Nicaragua's economy has suffered from a
U.S. trade embargo imposed in 1985, and Hurricane Joan, which
devastated the country in October.
   Opposition leaders cite poor government management and planning
for the state of the economy.
   Since riding a 1979 revolution to power, the Sandinistas have
seized many private businesses, and foreign and domestic investment
has plummeted. Under U.S. pressure, Western lending agencies have
halted Nicaragua's access to funds because of its ties to the Soviet
Union.
</TEXT>
