<DOCNO> AP890130-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 0253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WiretapCase Bjt   01-30 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wiretap Case, Bjt,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Of Alleged Wiretaps Under Way In Cincinnati</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city and a grand jury are investigating
allegations that the phone company and police illegally wiretapped
hundreds of phones, including those of Black Muslims, a federal
judge and a billionaire.
   The taps, the subject of a U.S. District Court trial that began
last month, allegedly were placed to allow police to monitor
investigations and to eavesdrop on suspected subversives.
   ``There are allegations that these things happened 10 years ago,
but I have a feeling that the evidentiary trail is cold,'' said
Mayor Charles Luken. ``The city doesn't have any records to indicate
that these things happened.''
   Still, the mayor has directed City Manager Scott Johnson to
conduct an internal investigation into charges that a secret
Cincinnati police intelligence unit cooperated with Cincinnati Bell
Telephone Co. on illegal wiretaps. A federal grand jury also is
investigating the allegations.
   Johnson said Friday he planned to hire private investigators to
help with the probe.
   But two of the nine city council members _ Democrat Peter
Strauss, and Republican John Mirlisena _ are calling for a special
prosecutor, contending that the city's plans are inadequate.
   ``To give it credibility it should be totally independent. The
only time our people should be in the room is when they are being
questioned,'' Mirlisena said.
   Cincinnati Bell and its parent company, Cincinnati Bell Inc.,
deny knowledge of such illegal eavesdropping or that they
participated in or authorized any such activity.
   The allegations were raised by two former Cincinnati Bell
employees _ Leonard Gates, a supervisor fired in 1986 for
insubordination, and ex-repairman Robert Draise, who quit as part of
a plea bargain in 1979 after he was charged in connection with an
illegal wiretap.
   Gates and Draise said Cincinnati Bell security officials ordered
them to install more than 1,200 illegal wiretaps between 1972 and
1984. The men said the wiretaps were put in place to help security
supervisors and Cincinnati police.
   Those whose telephones allegedly were tapped include a Black
Muslim organization, U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin of Cincinnati
and billionaire Cincinnati financier Carl Lindner Jr.
   Police officials have denied the wiretapping.
   But former policemen Harold Mills, Gary Simpson and Elmer
Dunaway, and former Hamilton County Commissioner Allen Paul last
year filed a $112 million lawsuit against Cincinnati Bell Inc., its
officers and directors and the phone company, alleging that their
phones were illegally tapped.
   The lawsuit, whose U.S. District Court trial began in December,
was filed as a class action on behalf of everyone whose telephones
might be shown to have been illegally tapped.
   Cincinnati Bell during the past two weeks responded with two
countersuits seeking a total of $4 million countersuit. One of the
countersuits denies any involvement in illegal wiretaps. The other
accuses Gates and Draise of lying and trying to hurt the company.
   Gates and Draise responded that Cincinnati Bell is merely trying
to get back at them for making their allegations public.
   The $112 million lawsuit recently was amended to include the city
as a defendant. The city filed a motion Jan. 26 denying the
allegations and asking that the lawsuit be dismissed.
   In a deposition, police Sgt. Howard Cade _ a former member of the
secret police intelligence unit _ said he participated in four
wiretaps while working for the intelligence unit. Cade, a 23-year
officer now assigned to the police communications section, said he
knew of no court authorizations for the wiretaps.
   Only federal judges may authorize installations of electronic
eavesdropping equipment.
   Cade reportedly received immunity from prosecution in exchange
for testifying before the federal grand jury.
   Some of the revelations in the depositions have been leaked to
Cincinnati news media. Lawyers for Cincinnati Bell and the city have
asked U.S. District Judge David Dowd Jr. to seal the depositions
from public access pending the trial. Lawyers for the news media
oppose those efforts.
</TEXT>
