<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     01-30 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Gains More Than One Yen, Stock Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained more than one yen against the
Japanese currency for the second consecutive trading day today,
while stock prices plunged amid concerns over their recent sharp
uptrend, dealers said.
   The dollar closed at 129.73 yen, up 1.08 yen from Friday's
128.65-yen finish. It opened at 129.58 yen, and ranged between
129.55 yen and 130.03 yen.
   On Friday, the dollar shot up 1.13 yen.
   The dollar's rallies on overseas markets had made Japanese
investors realize its strength despite the lower-than-expected U.S.
gross national product figure released Friday, a dealer with the
Bank of Tokyo said.
   The dollar also gained despite dollar-selling intervention last
week by U.S. and European monetary authorities last week, he said.
   Other dealers said Japanese institutional investors were the main
dollar buyers, while speculative investors were only adjusting
positions.
   A dealer a major securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the majority of market players, not finding
incentives to change the direction of trading, bought dollars in
line with current market sentiment.
   On Friday, the U.S. Commerce Department reported that the
nation's GNP, the total value of all goods and services, grew by 2
percent in the last quarter of 1988, down from 2.5 percent in the
previous three-month period. It grew 3.8 percent for all of 1988, up
from 3.6 percent in 1987, the department reported.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
plunged 111.57 points, or 0.35 percent, to 31,567.50. It had closed
Saturday's half-day session at a record 31,679.07 points.
   ``Investors were cautious over the index's recent sharp increase,
which already has pushed share prices quite high,'' said a Daiwa
Securities dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   While institutional investors remained on the sidelines,
individual investors bought low-priced smaller issues but failed to
reverse the market's decline, the dealer said.
   Investors also were nervous about recent fluctuations in foreign
exchange dealings, he added.
   Trading was moderate, with the first section volume estimated at
800 million shares.
</TEXT>
