<FIRST>r a PM-MinorityContracts     01-30 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minority Contracts,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Councilman Says Supreme Court Ruling A Blow To Black Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Supreme Court ruling that struck down
an ordinance mandating city contracts for minority companies could
boost unemployment and violent crime here, a black business leader
says.
   The Supreme Court last Monday ruled that the ordinance, which
requires that 30 percent of the value of all city contracts be set
aside for minority companies, unconstitutionally discriminated
against whites.
   The ruling ``is going to ruin quite a few businesses and it is
devestating to the economic fiber of the black community,'' said
Gladys Jackson-Weston, executive director of the Metropolitan
Business League, the leading black business association in the
Virginia capital.
   ``There will be an increase in unemployment and welfare ... the
murder rate in the city is now tied to economics and folks who have
lost their dreams, and we'll have more people out there who have
lost their dreams,'' Ms. Jackson-Weston said recently.
   There are nearly 1,000 minority-run contractors and related
businesses in the metropolitan area, Ms. Jackson-Weston said. She
said she believes one-third of that number won't survive without the
ordinance.
   She said her group would step up training of minority contractors
on keeping books, using computers and reducing overhead.
   Former Mayor Henry L. Marsh III, who was instrumental in pushing
the ordinance through in 1983, believes the ruling will prolong
discrimination in the traditionally white-dominated construction
industry.
   ``It's a big blow,'' Marsh said. ``Discrimination against
minority constructors is a serious problem in Richmond as in other
communities.
   Marsh, now a city councilman, and other city officials point to
statistics as proof the ordinance was needed.
   Richmond's population of 632,015 is 52 percent minorities,
according to City Manager Robert C. Bobb. Before the ordinance took
effect, less than 1 percent of the city's construction work was
awardedm to minority companies, Bobb said.
   While the ordinance was in effect, minority companies were
awarded about 40 percent of the city's work. Since its suspension in
July 1987, the percentage has dropped back below 2 percent, Bobb
said.
   ``There has been little or no progress,'' he said. ``I find that
very discouraging. Without the program in place we're furthering a
very closed system. Firms that are historically locked out will
continue to be locked out.''
   ``Obviously people wanted to do the work,'' Marsh said. ``They
did it when the ordinance was in effect. There were no complaints
that the work was not done well or that there was an inordinate
expense.''
   At least one minority contractor believes the ruling will ruin
his business, which employs nine people.
   ``I was expecting it to go the other way,'' said Merlin Hargrove
of United Unlimited Construction Co. ``I guess the only thing you
can do is pray.''
   Marsh said City Council members are discussing possible
affirmative action programs that would conform with the high court's
ruling.
   John Payton, a Washington attorney who represented Richmond
before the Supreme Court, said the city would have to comply with
the court's order that it make detailed findings of specific
discrimination before implementing a program that includes any kind
of racial preference.
   ``You have to make rigorous findings of discrimination,'' he
said. ``We thought we showed it. But the court said the numbers
don't matter. You have to find actual evidence.''
   Payton said he thought the city would be able to prove actual
discrimination to meet the court's standards.
</TEXT>
