<FIRST>r a PM-SharkAttack     01-30 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shark Attack,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Woman Apparently Killed By Shark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXNARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young woman whose battered body was found
floating in the Pacific off Channel Island Harbor probably was
killed by a shark, authorities said.
   The body of the unidentified woman 18 to 26 years old was spotted
Saturday by the crew of a sailboat six miles from the island.
   She apparently had been dead one to two days, said Dr. F. Warren
Lovell, Ventura County coroner.
   A 13-inch piece of flesh was missing from the woman's left thigh,
said Lovell, who described the wound as a ``classic shark bite.''
   ``There were a number of other shark bites. There was a fresh
bruise on the back of her right hand,'' he said Sunday.
   Lovell said the bruise appeared to have been caused when the
woman tried to fight off the attacking shark in the ocean 50 miles
northwest of Los Angeles.
   Lovell said her lungs ``did not show the classic findings
associated with drowning'' but the bites apparently occurred before
the woman died.
   Authorities said the woman may have been windsurfing as Southern
California was having warm and sunny weather.
   A check of law enforcement agencies showed no missing person
report who matched the woman's description, said Lovell.
   The last fatal shark attack off California was in September 1984
when an abalone diver was mauled 40 miles south of San Francisco.
   John McCosker, a shark expert and director of the Steinhart
Aquarium in San Francisco, said the latest attack may have been by a
Great White shark, which have been known to exceed 20 feet and 3{
tons.
   ``If this was in fact a Great White attack, it would be the first
that we know of to have occurred south of Santa Barbara,'' McCosker
said.
</TEXT>
