<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 0720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RacialQuotas     01-30 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Quotas,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Ruling Jeopardizes Some Minority Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Minority Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials in Boston and Atlanta fear some affirmative action
programs may be jeopardized by the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling
against a racial quota system for government contracts, but leaders
elsewhere hope slightly different plans will survive.
   In a 6-3 vote last Monday, the Supreme Court struck down a
program in Richmond, Va., that required white-owned companies
bidding on any city contract to set aside 30 percent of the
contract's value for minority-owned subcontractors.
   The high court said rigid racial quotas must be supported by
evidence; for example, that black-owned enterprises tried to obtain
construction contracts but were denied them. Without such evidence,
the use of racial quotas violates the equal-protection rights of
whites.
   But many state affirmative action programs across the nation are
voluntary or have goals to aim for rather than mandatory targets for
minority participation in government contracts, or they were
instituted on the basis of evidence, said a sampling of officials
contacted by The Associated Press.
   Before Richmond's quota went into effect, less than 1 percent of
the city's construction work was awarded to minority firms,
according to City Manager Robert C. Bobb. Richmond is 52 percent
minority,
   During the life of the ordinance, minority firms were awarded
about 40 percent of the city's work. Since the law's suspension in
July 1987, the percentage has dropped back below 2 percent, Bobb
said.
   The Georgia Supreme Court is considering a challenge to Atlanta's
35 percent minority business enterprise program and officials of the
black-majority city fear the state court might take its cue from the
ruling in the Richmond case.
   ``The Atlanta program has almost exactly the same defects that
Richmond's has,'' said William O. Miller, president of the
Southeastern Legal Foundation, a conservative group challenging
Atlanta's program.
   Last year Atlanta awarded $24.9 million in jobs to minority-owned
businesses, 36.7 percent of all of its contracts. More than $300
million in city business has gone to minority contractors since the
35 percent minority participation goal was set in 1975.
   Boston Mayor Raymond L. Flynn said he feared the ruling could
jeopardize some of his city's affirmative action programs in
development, hiring and contracts.
   An ordinance adopted in December 1987 required Boston to award 15
percent of all its contracts to businesses owned by minorities and 5
percent to businesses owned by women.
   Boston's population is about 35 percent minority. Minorities and
women received $27 million in city contracts in fiscal 1988, about
14 percent of the total eligible dollars, said Sheila Hubbard,
director of the mayor's Minority and Women Business Office. That
compares with $15.2 million in fiscal 1985.
   Michigan authorities, however, are confident the U.S. Supreme
Court will uphold their law, which requires 7 percent of all
purchasing and construction grants to go to minority-owned
businesses and 5 percent to go to businesses owned by women.
   State officials say they believe enough evidence about
discrimination was presented before the law took effect. ``It took
10 years of bill introductions and hearings to get it through the
Legislature,'' said John Roy Castillo, executive director of the
state Civil Rights Commission.
   A California program which took effect this month should survive
an expected challenge because it sets a goal of 15 percent for
minority participation in state business and a 5 percent goal for
women-owned companies, not an absolute quota, said state
Assemblywoman Maxine Waters, the bill's sponsor.
   However, attorney John Findley of the Pacific Legal Foundation
said minority contracting plans in California have one thing in
common with the Richmond measure: ``There's no showing of past
discrimination and a program designed specifically to remedy it.''
   According to the state Department of Finance's population
research unit, California's 27.8 million population is 24 percent
Hispanic, 7 percent black, and 9 percent Asian and others. About 51
percent of the state is female.
   Baltimore requires prime contractors to subcontract 20 percent of
a project's worth to minority contractors and 3 percent to women,
but City Council vice president Jacqueline McLean said the city
addressed the high court's major objections to Richmond's law.
   ``We held lengthy hearings and established a clear and convincing
record of past discrimination against minority contractors,'' Ms.
McLean said. Baltimore is 54 percent black.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
