<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Shooting 1stLd-Writethru a0491 01-30 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0491,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Opens Fire At Beach; Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with one of the dead was killed by soldier, other details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli in a khaki uniform killed another man
and wounded a woman on a beachfront north of Tel Aviv today, then
fired randomly as he was chased by police and soldiers, police said.
A bystander was killed by a soldier giving chase.
   The gunman surrendered after he was shot by police, said Tel Aviv
police spokeswoman Ahuva Ivri.
   ``Police who arrived chased him. He ran away firing in all
directions and at police,'' Ms. Ivri said.
   Police and soldiers pursued the assailant for a few miles before
he was wounded and raised his hands in surrender, Tel Aviv police
commander Eli Yitzhaki told Israel radio.
   An initial report said the attacker killed two people, but Ms.
Ivri said one of the dead was a man accidentally shot by a soldier
during the chase.
   The shooting began just before noon on the beachfront in Tel
Baruch, an area known as a hangout for prostitutes about a mile
north of Tel Aviv's sprawling resort tourist center, Israel radio
said.
   The attacker first opened fire on a prostitute who was with a
man, killing the man and wounding the woman, Ms. Ivri said.
   She did not identify the assailant but said he was born in 1964
and was from Ofakim, a town in the southern Negev Desert.
   The man's motive was not known, said Ms. Ivri. She said it was
believed all the victims were Israelis.
   A man in his 20s, believed to be the assailant, was brought to
Ichilov Hospital with a gunshot wound in the foot, a doctor at the
hospital said.
   An initial report on the radio said the attacker was a
``terrorist,'' meaning a Palestinian assailant. But later reports
and police said he was Jewish.
   Yitzhaki said on the radio that police had an initial report the
man was wearing an ammunition belt, leading them to believe he was a
Palestinian guerrilla.
   ``We got armed forces in the area on alert and got out armed
soliders to deal with it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
