<SECOND>PM-Iran-Briton,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran Expels British Technician</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has deported a British technician for
involvement in illegal activities, an official report said today.
   Samuel Williams was ``arrested recently because of unlawful and
illegal activities and was expelled after being tried,'' said the
Islamic Republic News Agency. It did not elaborate on the alleged
offenses, nor provide dates of Williams' arrest, trial or
deportation.
   IRNA identified the deportee only as a ``technical expert'' who
worked in eastern Khorasan province for ``several years.''
   Williams is barred from returning to Iran for 10 years, when his
case will be reconsiderd, it added.
   Iran's relations with Britain, like those with most Western
countries, have been shaky since Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
Islamic revolution toppled the pro-Western Iranian monarchy in
February 1979.
   Tehran and London restored diplomatic ties last November after a
17-month strain.
   A few weeks later, one of two Britons imprisoned in Iran was
freed. Nicholas Nicola, 23, was arrested in September 1986, near the
border with Pakistan and tried and convicted of illegal possession
of weapons.
   Nicola was sentenced to 3{ years' jail. Iran's official media
said he was released Dec. 7, 1988, for ``good conduct.''
   After his release, he told reporters he traveled to Iran from
Pakistan to join Afghan guerrillas fighting Soviet troops in
Afghanistan.
   Another Briton, Roger Cooper, 52, remains in jail in Iran.
Cooper, who worked in Iran for 20 years, was detained in November
1985 for overstaying his visa. He later was charged with espionage,
but no date has been set for his trial.
</TEXT>
