<FIRST>u a PM-AlaskaCold 1stLd-Writethru a0461 01-30 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alaska Cold, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0461,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaskans Can Look Forward To More Of The Same</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Canadian plane crash, cancellation
of cruise missile test over northern Canada, Coast Guard calling off port
security exercise. CORRECTS spelling of Army major's first name to Sherrel,
sted Sherrill. Picks up in 9th graf, `Gov. Steve ...' Trims from botton.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alaskans struggled with frozen pipes,
shortages of fuel and food and wind chills of minus 125 degrees in a
record cold spell that showed no sign of relaxing its 2-week-old icy
grip.
   A high-pressure system with clear skies, stinging cold and wind
heading southeast from Alaska's interior, and another high-pressure
system moving toward Alaska from Siberia threatened to prolong the
cold snap.
   ``Basically, we can expect the same kind of cold to continue,
with temperatures way below normal,'' National Weather Service
meteorologist Dan Keeton said Sunday night. ``Any increase in
temperature would be slight to moderate by the end of the week.''
   With the temperature hovering around 60 degrees below zero, a
C-130 crashed in a thick, icy fog Sunday night just short of a
runway at Fort Wainwright southeast of Fairbanks, killing eight
Canadian soldiers and critically injuring three others.
   ``The weather was quite bad,'' said U.S. Army Capt. Jim Rodgers.
However, Army Maj. Sherrel Mock said investigators had not
determined whether weather caused the crash.
   After the accident, Canadian military officials recalled defense
forces and aircrft that had been participating in an exercise with
U.S. forces.
   The Coast Guard, citing gusts up to 100 mph, icing and a wind
chill of 70 degrees below zero, canceled a port security exercise
Sunday at Whittier.
   A second, 1,550-mile test of an unarmed U.S. cruise missile over
northern Canada that had been scheduled to begin early today was
delayed because of the extreme cold weather, Canadian officials said.
   The coldest place in the state Sunday was McGrath, 150 miles west
of Mount McKinley, where it was minus 64. It was 61 below zero in
Tanana, 60 below in Fairbanks and minus 45 in Deadhorse. In
Anchorage, the temperature was a ``balmy'' minus 30, the coldest
January day since 1975, the weather service said.
   During the weekend, 17 all-time record lows fell across the
state, Keeton said. ``In Dillingham, they just shattered theirs,''
he said. ``It had been 36 degrees below; now, it's 53 degrees below
zero.''
   The normal temperature for January in Fairbanks is minus 13
degrees, according to the weather service.
   Wind chills down to 125 degrees below zero prompted warnings that
motorists avoid the heavily traveled Parks Highway that connects
Fairbanks and Anchorage.
   Other problems included fuel and food shortages, power outages,
frozen water and sewer lines, congealed fuel oil and grounded planes
in rural areas, state officials said.
   ``There are no immediate life-threatening situations ... but
there are some communities enduring considerable hardship and
inconvenience,'' the state Division of Emergency Services said
Sunday.
   Gov. Steve Cowper signed a declaration of emergency Saturday so
that state assistance funds will be more readily available if
requested.
   At King Cove on the Alaska Peninsula, residents with frozen fuel
lines were using open buckets of fuel with copper tubing to feed
furnaces, officials said Sunday.
   Mankotak officials said they were running out of heating fuel,
and Lower Kalskag on the Kuskokwim River was running out of fuel and
food.
   The cold weather and balky hydraulic systems slowed aircraft
refueling at Anchorage International Airport. Several freight
flights were canceled and 270 passengers aboard a Northwest Airlines
flight from Chicago to Tokyo were stranded; after landing in
Anchorage to refuel, an engine jammed, officials said.
   In Anchorage, firefighters trying to fight fires wrestled with
frozen pumps on their trucks and other cold-related problems.
   The cold spell heated up business for plumbers, who had long
waiting lists of people with frozen water pipes and balky furnaces.
   The Red Cross opened emergency shelters in Anchorage and at Port
Graham on the Kenai Peninsula. Residents of the Kodiak area borrowed
fuel from schools to keep warm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
