<FIRST>r a PM-DeKalbJail     01-30 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DeKalb Jail,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Uprising Quelled At DeKalb County Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than four days after the DeKalb County
sheriff staged a political protest against jail overcrowding, his
inmates staged their own protest, setting fires and smashing
furniture.
   About 240 maximum-security inmates who staged a Saturday night
uprising at the DeKalb County Jail were returned to their cells
after cleaning up the water and fire damage.
   ``Sheriff (Pat) Jarvis ordered them down on their hands and knees
and whatever it took'' to clean up the mess, said Maj. Winston
Pitmann of the DeKalb County Sheriff's Department.
   The rampage _ at least the eighth disturbance in county and state
prisons in Georgia in recent weeks _ was quelled after about four
hours, when police entered the jail in suburban Atlanta and fought
hand-to-hand with prisoners.
   No hostages were taken and only superficial injuries were
reported.
   The jail, with a capacity of 920, was packed with 1,300 inmates
Saturday, about 250 of whom were awaiting transfer to the
overcrowded state prison system.
   ``It's been brewing. The tension's been building,'' Pitmann said.
``We knew something was going to happen. We tried to warn people.''
   Some inmates said the disturbance erupted in protest of their
dinner, chili, rice and green beans. ``We checked. That was just an
excuse,'' Pitmann said.
   On Wednesday, Jarvis took 69 nonviolent prisoners to the state
Capitol to demonstrate to lawmakers the need for new prisons. Gov.
Joe Frank Harris proposed budget includes no money for six new
prisons requested by the state Department of Corrections.
   ``I don't want a running feud with Gov. Joe Frank Harris,''
Jarvis said Sunday. ``The symbolic posture I took last week ... was
strictly business.''
   ``We all need to sit down and really look at a solution'' to the
prison overcrowding situation. ``And a solution has got to come
quickly.''
   Pitmann said no financial estimate of Saturday's damage has been
prepared. Some criminal charges may be filed following
investigations, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
