<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-RembrandtTheft     01-30 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rembrandt Theft,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rembrandt and Other Painting Stolen, Two Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Rembrandt and another
17th-century Dutch painting were stolen from a government art
warehouse, and police today arrested a warehouse employee and her
boyfriend as suspects, officials said.
   The two paintings, ``Man with Beard,'' a 1647 work by Rembrandt
and ``Winter Landscape With Skaters,'' a 1649 painting by Jan van
Goyen, were reported missing from the warehouse in this city on Jan.
20, according to police spokesman Nico Laterveer.
   Rembrandt, whose full name was Rembrandt van Rijn, is the
best-known of all 17th-century Dutch painters.
   The disappearance of the paintings was only made public today
``so as not to jeopardize the investigation'' Laterveer said.
   The two suspects, identified only as a 22-year-old administrative
employee of the warehouse and her boyfriend, remained in custody.
However, a search of their apartment failed to yield the paintings,
which remain missing.
   The incident was the latest in a series of art thefts in the
Netherlands that began last May, when three paintings, including a
work by Vincent van Gogh and one by French impressionist Paul
Cezanne, were stolen from Amsterdam's Stedelijk Museum. Those
paintings were later recovered.
   On Dec. 12, three Van Goghs were stolen from the famed
Kroeller-Mueller Museum in the eastern Netherlands. No trace of
those three paintings has been found.
   Laterveer estimated the value of the latest two missing paintings
at between $474,000 and $711,000.
   They were reported missing from a warehouse vault containing
dozens of art works, according to Culture Ministry spokeswoman
Annemarie Stordiau.
   No traces of a break-in were found at the vault or the downtown
warehouse, which Ms. Stordiau described as ``very secure.''
   ``It all leads to the conclusion that somebody with regular
access to the vault must have taken the paintings,'' Laterveer said.
   He said the Rembrandt measures only about 10-by-9 inches and the
Van Goyen is only about 8{-by-9{ inches.
   ``Somebody could easily have taken the paintings out of the
building hiding them under a coat,'' Laterveer said.
   The warehouse is one of about 12 owned by the Government Art
Agency, which takes care of about 150,000 government-owned art
works. The agency gives the art works on loan to Dutch and foreign
museums, and its collection includes some of the valuable
17th-century Dutch master works on display in Amsterdam's
Rijksmuseum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
