<FIRST>u i PM-Syria-Iran 1stLd-Writethru a0511 01-30 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Syria-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0511,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Factions Sign Peace Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with news agency report on pact.
Picks up 5th graf pvs `Asked if...' DELETES 13th graf pvs ``The inter-Shiite...''
as redundant.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS FARES</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of Shiite Moslem factions in
Lebanon today signed a peace treaty to end nine months of fighting
that have killed more than 500 people.
   The pact says Syrian-backed forces should control security in
south Lebanon and Moslem parts of Beirut, according to the official
Syrian Arab News Agency.
   The agency said the eight-point agreement was signed by Syria's
ally, the Amal militia, and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of
God.
   Fighting between Amal and Hezbollah has aggravated Lebanon's
civil war and strained ties between Syria and Iran. The inter-Shiite
fighting has been halted several times through cease-fires arrange
by Syria and Iran, but the battles have repeatedly broken out again.
   The latest peace accord was completed at a meeting in the Syrian
Foreign Ministry attended by leaders of the rival militias, Foreign
Minister Farouk Sharaa of Syria and Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati of Iran. It followed a week of negotiations during clashes
in Lebanon.
   In what appeared to be a setback for Hezbollah, the Syrian news
agency said the peace agreement gives Amal control of security in
south Lebanon and emphasized that Syria is the sole security power
in Moslem sectors of Beirut.
   The report said the pact provides for an immediate cease-fire,
exchange of prisoners, an end to hostile propaganda, formation of a
joint anti-Israeli operations center in south Lebanon and creation
of a committee to regulate relations between Amal and Hezbollah.
   Asked if a peace agreement might open the door to freeing Western
hostages in Lebanon, Velayati said: ``We hope that all hostages,
whatever their nationalities, will be released very soon on the
basis of humanitarian aspects.''
   He did not elaborate. Most of the 15 foreigners missing in
Lebanon are believed held by Iranian-backed Shiite factions linked
to Hezbollah.
   However, Hezbollah leader Sheik Ibrahim Amin said Sunday that the
hostages are not linked to a peace accord. ``This matter has no
relation to us, nor with the agreement,'' he said.
   Velayati said before today's talks that ``Syria and Iran will
guarantee the implementation and fulfillment of the agreement''
between their Lebanese allies.
   Amal and Hezbollah, which have been battling for control of
Lebanon's 1 million Shiites, agreed late Sunday to end the fighting
after they handed over to Syrian forces alleged assassins of leaders
on both sides.
   Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kenaan, Syria's military intelligence chief in
Lebanon, said Hezbollah delivered gunmen who killed Amal's leader in
south Lebanon, Daoud Daoud, and two of his lieutenants, in a south
Beirut ambush Sept. 22.
   He said an Amal man accused by Hezbollah of the reprisal
assassination of Sheik Ali Krayyem in east Lebanon also was handed
over to the Syrians.
   He did not identify the men or say what will happen to them.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, considers that country
its sphere of influence and vital to its regional ambitions.
   Tehran has long sought to establish an Islamic-style Islamic
republic there through Hezbollah.
   The more secular and nationalist Amal seeks a Lebanese government
that would share power between Moslems and traditionally dominant
Christians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
