<FIRST>u w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0428 01-30 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Predicts Jobs in Abundance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material, editing throughout, with Bush speech at swearing-in.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today predicted ``jobs in
abundance'' in the years ahead and called for a new spirit of
volunteerism in America.
   ``John Kennedy challenged us to ask ourselves what we could do
for our country,'' Bush said at a swearing-in ceremony for Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole. ``And let us each day ask, what can I do
for another person? How can I make someone else's load a little
lighter?''
   Bush said government service ``plays a vital role, but it must
complement individual service.''
   Bush began the second week of his presidency nursing the
persistent cold that had forced him to cancel a Sunday visit to the
presidential retreat at Camp David with House Speaker Jim Wright.
   ``Pardon my voice,'' a hoarse Bush told his audience at the Labor
Department.
   He told the gathering, largely made up of Labor Department
employees, ``You look out for the working people of America.''
   ``I want this adminstration to be about working people,'' he
added. ``Part of that will be excellence and responsiveness in
goverment. Part of that will be holding the line on taxes. And part
of it will be a new volunteerism: people helping people.''
   ``...I think of the secretary who after a day at the office takes
the time to volunteer and help a child in the neighborhood learn how
to read,'' he said.
   With her husband, Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., at her
side, Mrs. Dole picked up on Bush's theme of volunteerism and budget
restraint.
   ``We don't have unlimited funds, which means we must make the
funds we do have work for us,'' said Mrs. Dole, who was
transportation secretary in the Reagan administration.
   Mrs. Dole said she was committed to a goal of moving beyond full
employment to ``fulfilling employment'' for all who seek a job.
   Bush said there was ``a lot to feel good about on the labor
front'' with civilian unemployment currently at its lowest level in
14 years, 5.3 percent in December.
   ``There'll be jobs in abundance but we'll have to make sure our
workers have the skills that they need to fill those jobs with
excellence,'' Bush added.
   With one week as president under his belt, Bush was expected to
get down to serious talks on budget options this week with Budget
Director Richard G. Darman.
   One of those options could be a proposed new fee on deposits to
help come up with some of the estimated $100 billion needed to shore
up the nation's ailing savings and loan industry.
   Chief of Staff John Sununu said in a broadcast interview on
Sunday that the fee remains an option, despite what he called a
firestorm of opposition on Capitol Hill.
   Critics say the proposal for a $2.50 fee on each $1,000 on
deposit in federally insured financial institutions would violate
Bush's no-new-taxes pledge. Bush and other administration officials
said it wouldn't be a tax, with Sununu calling it ``an adjustment
upward of the current premium structure.''
   Sununu, interviewed Sunday on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David
Brinkley,'' suggested that some leading Democrats in Congress are
``positioning (themselves) to deal with eventual failure'' on a
bipartisan budget agreement.
   ``If that's the attitude going in, then none of us will
succeed,'' he said. He said Bush still intends to come up with a
budget plan that meets deficit-reduction targets without raising
taxes.
   The first major test of Bush's leadership could come on Feb. 9,
when Bush will outline his budget plans to a joint session of
Congress.
   The president is expected to propose numerous modifications to
the $1.15 trillion fiscal 1990 budget presented by former President
Reagan.
   The Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law requires a shortfall of no
more than $100 billion in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1.
Failure to reach that target would result in mandatory,
across-the-board spending cuts taken equally from domestic and
military programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
