<FIRST>r i PM-PolandPriest     01-30 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland Priest,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Solidarity Priest Dies in Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-Solidarity priest died today in a
fire that swept his home in the northeastern city of Bialystok, a
human rights activist said.
   The Rev. Stanislaw Suchowolec apparently died of smoke
inhalation, said Zofia Romaszewska of the Solidarity Commission for
Intervention and Law Abidance. The cause of the fire was not known.
   Ms. Romaszewska said Suchowolec had informed the commission that
he had been assaulted and that his car had been tampered with in the
past. The commission keeps a record of human rights violations in
Poland.
   A priest who shared the house in the Immaculate Heart of Mary
parish said he found Suchowolec's body early this morning.
   Authorities had arrived to investigate, the priest said in a
telephone interview on condition of anonymity. He said he believed
an electric spark started the fire.
   ``I got up in the morning, there was no electricity, and I saw
the doors blackened with soot on the outside. I forced the door open
and he was already dead,'' the priest said.
   ``Everything was burned up ... Everything points to the fact that
it was caused by an electric spark, because there was no light,'' he
said. ``The curtains and coverings were all burned, so it seems he
must have inhaled carbon monoxide.''
   Suchowolec was an active supporter of the banned trade union
Solidarity and is the second priest within 10 days to die in unclear
circumstances.
   On Jan. 21, a sacristan found the body of the Rev. Stefan
Niedzielak, 74, a priest who maintained a shrine to Poles killed in
the Soviet Union.
   Officials have not finished their investigation into Niedzielak's
death, but murder has not been ruled out.
   Suchowolec was a priest for six years and had served as vicar in
Sucho Wola, village of the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, the
pro-Solidarity priest murdered by security police in 1984.
   He also organized pilgrimages to Popieluszko's gravesite in
Warsaw.
   No Roman Catholic Church officials were available to comment in
Suchowolec's parish and church officials in Warsaw declined to
comment. Local authorities also could not be reached immediately.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
