<FIRST>u a PM-McNamaraResigns     01-30 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McNamara Resigns,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney for Massachusetts Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank L. McNamara Jr., dogged by investigations
into his actions as U.S. attorney for Massachusetts, resigned today,
just three days after the majority of his assistant prosecutors
demanded his removal.
   ``The work of this office is far too important to be sidetracked
by any controversy,'' McNamara said in a brief statement that didn't
mention his assistants' demand.
   McNamara, who said he intended to return to private law practice,
said he believed President George Bush and Attorney General Richard
Thornburgh ``should be afforded the opportunity to appoint a person
of their own choosing.''
   McNamara, a 41-year-old Republican, has been the target of a
Justice Department investigation since November, when charges that
he saw his predecessor smoke marijuana backfired. Investigators
found no evidence to support his allegations; McNamara admitted to
smoking marijuana himself.
   Additional investigations questioned whether McNamara used his
office as a political tool. Over the weekend, he denied urging
politically motivated investigations of prominent Democrats and
vowed not to resign under pressure.
   On Friday, 28 of the 39 assistant U.S. attorneys under his charge
wrote to Thornburgh urging him to expedite McNamara's departure.
   ``Mr. McNamara's conduct and performance while United States
attorney is resulting in a loss of confidence in the adminstration
of justice,'' the letter said. ``Because Mr. McNamara will neither
resign nor step aside temporarily, the credibility and operations of
this office will continue to be damaged ... unless he is removed.''
   McNamara has been dogged by controversy since he was nominated by
President Reagan to replace William F. Weld in April 1987, when Weld
was promoted to head the Justice Department's criminal division.
   McNamara's confirmation was held up while the FBI investigated
irregularities in his congressional campaign finances and his
failure to pay income tax for 1983 and 1984 until 1986. He ran
unsuccessfully against U.S. Rep. Thomas P. O'Neill Jr., speaker of
the House, in 1982.
   During the confirmation process, McNamara said he believed Weld
was trying to scuttle his nomination and told investigators that he
had seen Weld drunk on several occasions. He also alleged he had
seen Weld smoke a marijuana joint at a 1982 wedding party.
   A Justice Department investigation failed to support McNamara's
charges, and McNamara was forced to admit that he had smoked
marijuana himself at a later date.
   In November, several assistant prosecutors said McNamara pursued
an investigation of a prison land deal by the administration of Gov.
Michael S. Duakakis in an attempt to discredit Dukakis, then the
Democratic nominee for president.
   Over the weekend, McNamara denied allegations that he urged a
federal investigation into marijuana-smoking charges against U.S.
Rep. Joseph Kennedy II and Robert Farmer, the top fundraiser for
Dukakis' presidential campaign.
   McNamara said the allegation stemmed from an unsubstantiated FBI
report that was leaked to reporters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
