<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0476 01-30 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel To Go Ahead With Settlements in Occupied Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New grafs 10-12 ``Also today,...'' to update on circumstances
of killing. Picks up 13th graf pvs ``Army officials...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel will go ahead with plans to build eight
new Jewish settlements in the occupied lands this year despite the
Palestinian uprising and a slashed budget, an adviser to Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir said today.
   Michael Dekel, the prime minister's adviser on settlements, said
there was no shortage of ``idealistic pioneers'' to develop five new
settlements in the West Bank and three in the southern Gaza Strip.
   The coalition agreement signed by the new government of Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc and the center-left Labor Party calls for the
building of five to eight Jewish settlements.
   ``The moment people oppose you, you cannot raise your hands and
surrender _you have to struggle,'' Dekel told The Associated Press,
referring to the 13-month Palestinian revolt against Israeli
occupation in the territories.
   ``The settlement of the state of Israel is very important because
of _ not despite _ the intefadeh,'' he said, using the Arabic word
for uprising.
   Dekel said he hoped the government's economic austerity plan,
which cut more than $600 million from the state budget, would not
take a toll on the settlement movement.
   About 70,000 Jewish settlers already live in the West Bank and
Gaza, which Israel seized during the 1967 Middle East war.
   Many of the 1.7 million Palestinians in the territories fear
Israel wants all their land, and the settlers have become frequent
targets of stonings and firebombings. They have called on the
government to take harsher steps against Arab rioters.
   Although settlers have received government incentives to move to
the occupied lands, many have strong ideological commitments to the
territory, believing it is their God-given birthright.
   Also today, an Arab mukhtar, or traditional village leader, was
stabbed to death in the occupied West Bank village of Beit Lid, a
military spokeswoman said today.
   An Arab reporter said Mahmoud Salem Mahmoud, 65, went to work on
his farm Sunday. Relatives began searching for the mukhtar when he
failed to return home as planned, and found his body, which was
``stabbed in many places,'' he said.
   Although the reason for the killing was unclear, Arab reporters
said Mahmoud may have been slain because he was suspected of working
for the Israelis.
   Army officials say 30 Palestinians have been killed during the
uprising by fellow Arabs because they were suspected collaborators
or informants.
   In addition, underground Palestinian leaders of the uprising have
called for overthrowing traditional village leaders to make way for
younger, more radical ones.
   Including the alleged collaborators, 370 Palestinians have been
killed since the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987. Fifteen Israelis also
have been killed.
   Also today, Israeli news reports said an army officer was
sentenced to three months in prison and six months probation for the
shooting death of a Palestinian protester in the Gaza Strip last
August.
   The officer, a second lieutenant, shot at a fleeing man who had
led a violent protest, Israel army radio said.
   A military court judge said the soldier did not have to shoot at
the Palestinian because the man was not endangering his life or
those of other troops.
   ``We're not talking about a mission that must be carried out at
any cost,'' the judge wrote in his opinion, according to army radio.
   Israeli newspapers also reported that Defense Minister Yitzhak
Rabin would hold a series of meetings with local Palestinian leaders
to push his plan for elections leading to partial autonomy for the
occupied territories. The Palestine Liberation Organization has
rejected the proposal.
</TEXT>
