<FIRST>r a PM-AdulterousPreacher     01-30 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Adulterous Preacher,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Back In Pulpit 3 Years After Leaving In Disgrace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister who left his church after
admitting he committed adultery, leaving a schism in his
congregation that prompted the Rev. Jerry Falwell to step in, now
wants to start a new church in the same city.
   The Rev. Herman ``Buddy'' Frankland returned to preaching Sunday
with a sermon on ``Lessons Learned: Lessons Applied'' to about 50
people in a motel room, and said he was seeking a place to rent for
his new Messiah Temple.
   The fundamentalist minister has avoided the spotlight since
leaving the Bangor Baptist Church in disgrace in 1985.
   ``I have learned a lot of lessons. It's been a tough three
years,'' he told the congregation. ``But I'm back because of your
letters ... I've made mistakes, but I don't want to go into the
valley again.''
   One woman said afterward that Frankland was the most inspiring
preacher she had ever heard. ``Thank God he's back. We need him,''
she said.
   Frankland stepped down from the pulpit of the Bangor Baptist
Church, which he had founded 19 years earlier and built into one of
the largest in New England, after announcing publicly he had
committed adultery.
   Following his fall from grace, a split occurred within the
congregation, prompting Falwell, a fellow fundamentalist known
nationally for his television show and politics, to step in as
acting pastor in an attempt to straighten out what he saw as chaos.
   Asked by reporters after the sermon what prompted his return,
Frankland said he had received an inspiring letter from a former
parishioner and felt guilty for having left his congregation.
   He acknowledged that some people say he does not belong in Bangor
but said, ``A shepherd should not leave his flock. I don't care what
people say.''
</TEXT>
