<FIRST>r a PM-SniperShootings     01-30 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sniper Shootings,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>20-Year-Old Self-Styled `Commando' Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAPHANK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old self-styled commando who
``always wanted to join the army'' has confessed to three murders in
the Midwest and one killing and four other sniper attacks on Long
Island, police said.
   In a two-hour videotaped statement, Yusef Abdullah Rahman
admitted to shootings that killed one man and wounded three others
in December on eastern Long Island, Suffolk County District Attorney
Edward Jablonski said Sunday.
   Rahman, Jablonski said, also claimed to have killed three people
in Kansas City, Mo., although police there said he is wanted for
only one murder.
   Rahman was arrested Saturday afternoon in Wyandanch after a brief
foot chase, Jablonski said. Rahman was linked to the Long Island
shootings after several guns belonging to him were found in a car in
Southampton about a week before his arrest.
   He was held without bail on one count of second-degree murder,
three counts of attempted murder in the second degree and one count
of reckless endangerment in the first degree.
   The Long Island shootings occurred Dec. 5 to 8 within a two-mile
radius in the towns of Southampton and Riverhead. The two towns are
about 75 miles east of New York City and near exclusive beach
communities favored by the city's wealthy.
   Friends and relatives of the victims, all in their 30s, described
them as hard-working family men and couldn't suggest a motive.
   Police Capt. John McElhone said Rahman, a Riverhead resident, was
``playing out his fantasy'' with the random shootings.
   He said Rahman liked to wear commando-style outfits, such as
black clothing and a bullet-proof vest. Jablonski said he rode a
bicycle when he did the sniping, and carried a knife strapped to his
leg.
   ``He always wanted to join the army but his parents wouldn't
allow him,'' said Detective George Horvath.
   Jablonski said Rahman would peer through the windows of homes
before firing. He said Rahman even asked one victim afterward about
the shooting.
   Rahman also was accused of shooting at a police car on Jan. 1
``to renew public interest in his actions,'' McElhone said.
According to Jablonski, Rahman said he aimed at the headlights but
nearly hit an officer in the head.
   In Kansas City, Rahman is wanted for first-degree murder and
armed criminal action in connection with the 1987 slaying of
Frederick Beard, said Sgt. Pete Edlund.
   Beard's body was found slumped over the steering wheel of his car
on Aug. 3, 1987. Edlund said Beard had been shot several times.
</TEXT>
