<FIRST>u a PM-NerveGas-Arrest     01-30 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nerve Gas-Arrest,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused In Nerve Gas Plot Ordered Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today ordered the government to free
on $2 million bail a Korean-born American businessman charged with
attempting to export tons of nerve gas bombs.
   U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin said the government failed to
convince him that Juwhan Yun would flee prosecution if he were
released on bail.
   Yun, 48, has pleaded innocent to charges of conspiring to violate
the Arms Export Control Act by seeking to ship overseas 500
quarter-ton bombs of sarin, a nerve gas. The government says the
bombs may have been intended for Iran.
   ``Nothing is more abhorrent to our free society than the spectre
of persons accused of crimes being confined in prisons before trial
and conviction,'' Sarokin wrote in an opinion ordering Yun's release.
   ``The right to be free on bail before trial is what distinguishes
our democracy from totalitarian governments,'' he added.
   Yun has been in custody since his arrest Jan. 12.
   Under the bail agreement, Yun was ordered to forfeit his passport
and those of his family. He also agreed to be confined to his home
and to have all international telephone calls to his home monitored
by the U.S. attorney's office.
   A magistrate revoked bail for Yun on Jan. 20 after prosecutors
said the classified government documents written in English and
Korean were found on a desk at his import-export business, Komex
International Corp., in Summit.
   Yun's attorney, Stephen Dratch, argued last week that his client
was a victim of entrapment, claiming the government had overstepped
its bounds during the investigation.
   Sarokin made his decision after reading transcripts of taped
conversations and copies of intercepted facsimile messages provided
by the government.
   Yun, Sarokin said, would be unlikely to flee because his wife and
three children and his mother reside with him.
   Bail will be secured by Yun's house in Short Hills, worth
$650,000, and a New York City condominium, worth $250,000, the judge
said.
</TEXT>
