<FIRST>r a AM-StAlbansBodies     01-30 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-St Albans Bodies,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifth Body Found in St. Albans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. ALBANS, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A body found in a junkyard Monday was
the fifth in the area since two brothers were discovered shot to
death earlier this month, police said.
   ``The search is definitely continuing,'' said Kanawha County
Sheriff Art Ashley. ``We specifically want to go through that same
vicinity thoroughly.''
   The unidentified body found Monday, by a specially trained dog,
was about 200 yards east of where three other bodies have been
found. Another victim was found in her home a short distance away,
and police have been searching for two other people missing since
autumn.
   Mark Southern McCallister, 19, is being held in the Kanawha
County Jail without bond on murder charges in two of the deaths. He
is charged with the Jan. 8 shotgun slayings of Billy and Otis
Sanson, who lived in a trailer compound.
   Otis, 25, was shot in the back and left in a camper trailer. The
body had been covered with cushions and the camper door nailed shut,
said assistant Kanawha County Prosecutor Reagan Whitmyer.
   Billy, 27, was shot in face and left in a makeshift dog pen.
   The body of their sister, Bonnie Sanson, was found by search dogs
Jan. 21 buried on the grounds of an abandoned motel. An autopsy
revealed she was killed by a shotgun blast to the back of the head.
   McCallister's grandmother, Charlotte Ruby Ferrell, 69, was found
in the bedroom of her St. Albans home Jan. 13, shot in the head with
a shotgun and wrapped in sheets and a curtain.
   Missing are Bonnie Sanson's boyfriend, Jimmy Price, and Michael
Schillings, a North Carolina man who linked up with the compound's
residents last spring.
   Three other people who lived there _ the Sansons' mother, her
daughter and Bonnie Sanson's daughter _ moved last week to South
Carolina, officials say.
</TEXT>
