<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   01-30 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Explodes in Christian Sector, Killing 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI3,4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded as the motorcade of
Phalange Party leader George Saade passed a cemetery Monday in
Christian east Beirut, killing three people and wounding 17, police
reported. Saade escaped injury.
   The right-wing Christian leader said later he did not believe it
was an assassination attempt because ``the route I took ... is not
the road I usually take to my office. ... I decided only minutes
before leaving my house to take this route.''
   In Damascus, Shiite Moslem militias sponsored by Syria and Iran
signed a peace agreement aimed at ending a 9-month-old war in south
Lebanon and Beirut's Moslem sector in which more than 500 people
have been killed and nearly 2,000 wounded.
   Saade, 57, was riding in a bulletproof blue Alfa Romeo driven by
a chauffeur and escorted by three carloads of bodyguards. Two
bodyguards were among the dead and about 10 cars were destroyed.
   No group claimed responsibility immediately for the third car
bombing in Beirut this month. Eleven people have been killed and 47
wounded.
   A broadcast on Voice of Free Lebanon radio owned by the Lebanese
Forces, the main Christian militia, accused the Syria's intelligence
service. It said the Syrians, ``or their secret hands, are again ...
resorting to the cowardly car bombing method that has filled their
bloody record in Lebanon.''
   There was no response from Syria, which has 40,000 soldiers in
Lebanon and has become its chief power broker during more than 13
years of sectarian civil war.
   More than a dozen car-bomb assassination attempts have been made
on Moslem and Christian government leaders, politicians and militia
commanders since the civil war began.
   A red Renault packed with an estimated 110 pounds of TNT exploded
as Saade's motorcade moved along a boulevard near a cemetery in the
Furn el-Shubback residential distriict, police said.
   Elias Elias, chief of Saade's 12 bodyguards, told reporters they
surrounded the Phalangist leader immediately and ``fired in the air
to prevent anyone from approaching while we helped him out of his
damaged car. We then put him in another car and sped off.''
   Saade, whose party is a traditional force in the Christian
community, said on his party's Voice of Lebanon radio later that he
did not believe the bomb was meant for him.
   He said he thought is was intended to disrupt Arab League efforts
to resolve a political crisis that threatens Lebanon with permanent
partition along sectarian lines.
   ``Some people wanted to scuttle this initiative,'' he said, but
did not elaborate.
   An Arab League committee in Tunis is trying to reconcile
Lebanon's rival Moslem and Christian governments so Parliament can
name a president to replace Amin Gemayel, whose six-year term ended
Sept. 22. Gemayel's father, the late Pierre Gemayel, founded the
Phalange.
   The Voice of Lebanon quoted Gen. Michel Aoun, acting prime
minister of the Christian cabinet, as saying from Tunis the bombing
was directed at the reconciliation meetings and ``legitimate
security'' in Christian east Beirut.
   In Damascus, the mainstream Amal militia and fundamentalist
Hezbollah, or Party of God _ sponsored by Syria and Iran
respectively _ signed an eight-point peace accord at the Foreign
Ministry, Syria's official news agency reported.
   Leaders of the militias and the two foreign ministers worked out
the agreement, which calls for an immediate cease-fire and exchange
of prisoners. It also decrees an end to hostile propaganda and
provides that a joint operations center against Israel be
established in south Lebanon.
   Amal, which means Hope in Arabic, and Hezbollah have been
struggling for supremacy among the 1 million Shiites who make up
Lebanon's largest sect.
   In an apparent setback for Hezbollah, the agreement gives Amal
control of security in south Lebanon and emphasizes that the Syrian
army is responsible for security in Beirut's Moslem areas.
   Hezbollah was seeking to set up an Islamic republic in south
Lebanon along the lines of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomenei's Iran, and
also had been trying to expand into west Beirut from its base in the
south Beirut slums.
   Under the agreement, both sides also agree not to harm U.N.
peacekeeping forces ``or the personnel of international
organizations'' in Lebanon, the Syrian news agency said.
   Fundamentalist Shiites have clashed frequently with U.N.
peacekeepers in south Lebanon and several foreigners working for
humanitarian agencies have been kidnapped.
   Sheik Ibrahim Amin, a Hezbollah leader, said there was no
connection between the peace agreement and Western hostages in
Lebanon. ``This matter has no relation to us or with the
agreement,'' he said.
   Most of the 15 missing Westerners, who include nine Americans,
are believed held by Shiite factions linked to Hezbollah.
</TEXT>
