<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Press     01-30 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Press,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists Call for Legal Underground Publications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official journalists' union called
for legalizing underground publications and invited back members
expelled for independent political views, a news report said Monday.
   The calls come after months of increasing openness in the
domestic press and growing debate among national leaders over social
and economic reform.
   In an unusual admission of a personal change of heart, the
Communist Party's chief ideologist, Janos Berecz, told the
journalists' gathering he realized he must now stand ``on the side
of reform,'' said the Magyar Nemzet daily.
   He has been considered a conservative hardliner, but he has made
recent remarks that were surprisingly pro-reform.
   His statement at the journalists' conference suggested that
reformers have gained the upper hand in the party in the battle over
social and ecnomic changes.
   Over the weekend, Politburo member Imre Pozsgay made the
startling statement that the 1956 uprising that was crushed by
Soviet tanks should be seen as a popular revolt. Officials have
called it a ``counterrevolution'' for 30 years.
   During a weekend conference, the state-run journalists' union
said journalists should be allowed to make their own decisions
without waiting for approval from higher officials. Berecz appeared
to sanction this stand.
   He said the party ``is not quite capable of directing the
processes,'' the newspaper reported. It also quoted him as saying,
``The media are not open enough to give free scope to fresh
initiatives.''
   Hungary's official media has become increasingly open, reporting
on issues once considered taboo. New publications have sprung up
that would not have been permitted a year ago.
   At its weekend meeting, the 6,000-member union also condemned
discriminatory policies toward samizdat, or underground publications.
   ``We recognize the right of the `samizdat' publications to
existence, even if, until recently ... such newssheets were
harassed,'' the newspaper quoted the meeting's final document as
saying.
   The conference also expressed support for a proposal to readmit
union members who were ``unjustly discriminated against'' after the
communists took power in 1948, the 1956 uprising, and Hungary's
participation in the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   Scores of journalists were expelled from the union for their
independent views after those events.
</TEXT>
