<FIRST>r a AM-People     01-30 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black fedora worn by the ``Bad'' boy of pop,
Michael Jackson, sold for $1,400 at an auction held by a former
sister-in-law.
   ``This was my birthday present, my Christmas present and my
anniversary present,'' said Donna Frieden, a voice-over artist who
snapped up the hat at Sunday's auction. ``I'm not going to buy any
clothes for a long time.''
   The fedora was among ``warehouses and warehouses'' of Jackson
clan memorabilia that Enid Jackson said she was awarded in her
recent divorce from Michael Jackson's older brother Jackie. She said
she planned to sell off the items because she didn't want to pay for
their storage and maintenance.
   Eager fans also bought a jumpsuit, a tiger-skin patterned leotard
and several gold and platinum records at the auction at the North
Hollywood warehouse.
   The biggest buyer was Brian Murphy, in charge of buying rock
memorabilia for display at Hard Rock Cafe clubs. Murphy spent about
$12,000 for more than a dozen Jackson items for the cafe's London
restaurant and branches under construction in Washington and Boston.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Kathleen Turner and comedian
Robin Williams have been named 1989 Man and Woman of the Year for
making ``a lasting contribution to the world of entertainment,''
Hasty Pudding Theatricals announced Monday.
   The group of Harvard University students, the nation's oldest
college theatrical organization, bestows the honor each year.
Previous recipients include Elizabeth Taylor, Lucille Ball, James
Stewart and Paul Newman.
   Ms. Turner, currently appearing in ``The Accidental Tourist,''
was called a ``stellar and versatile acress whose combination of
sass and glamour has defined her as a leading actress of our
generation.'' Ms. Turner, also known for such films as ``Body
Heat,'' ``Romancing the Stone'' and ``Peggy Sue Got Married,'' will
be honored Feb. 14 with a parade through Cambridge.
   Williams was cited as ``probably the only actor who can claim to
have portrayed a cartoon character, a real-life character and an
alien.'' His work includes the movies ``Popeye,'' ``The World
According to Garp'' and ``Good Morning, Vietnam.'' He played an
alien in the TV series ``Mork and Mindy.''
   Williams will be honored Feb. 21 at the premiere of ``Whiskey
Business,'' Hasty Pudding Theatricals' 141st annual musical.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Lt. Columbo returns to television after a
10-year hiatus, he'll be older but otherwise unchanged, says the
actor who made the rumpled and rambling investigator famous.
   The same old raincoat, the same old car _ only the dog had to be
changed for the upcoming ABC Mystery Movie, Peter Falk said in an
article he co-wrote for the Feb. 4 issue of TV Guide magazine.
   ``Making sure the show would be exactly the same after a 10-year
absence wasn't easy,'' Falk wrote. ``I must say my mouth fell open
when I heard Universal Studios, which makes the show, sold Columbo's
car.''
   Universal was able to track down the Ohio couple who owned the
Peugot that had been used in the show, and they lent it to the
studio for the new episode.
   The dog will have to be updated, however. The original bassett
hound had died; a much younger replacement was aged with makeup,
Falk wrote.
   Although the world has changed around Columbo in the last decade,
the disheveled detective is not about to alter his style, Falk said.
   ``Columbo in 1989 is not thinking about giving up cigars. He's
just thinking, `Gee, it's getting harder and harder to bum a
match.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>A longer version moved on some sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matt Biondi, holder of five world swimming
records and winner of seven Olympics medals, was used to wearing a
wetsuit, but the cape, crown and trident that went with it were a
bit much.
   Biondi admitted to being a little embarrassed at his King Neptune
regalia as he presided Sunday over a Mississippi River boat parade
that was part of early Mardi Gras festivities.
   ``You've got to realize that the things I've been doing for the
past three months were coat-and-tie. Autograph things,'' he said. ``
... And here I am dressed up like Spider-man.''
   The cloak and crown were picked up at a costume shop, but his
blue-and-gray wetsuit and trident had to be custom-made for his
6-foot-6 frame. Organizers said the tridents from the costume shops
looked like salad forks in his hands.
   Although swimming no longer dominates his life, Biondi has hardly
become a land-lubber. He had plans to take a Caribbean scuba cruise
and start training for the U.S. water polo team for the 1992
Olympics.
</TEXT>
