<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     01-30 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Iraq,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Says Iran, Iraq Foreign Ministers May Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq may meet
in New York next week if the United Nations secretary-general
believes it would be helpful, a senior Iraqi official said Monday.
   The two sides have agreed to hold direct talks on curbing
violations of the Aug. 20 gulf war cease-fire, but no date has been
set for the military committee to meet.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz plans to be in New York next
week when the U.N. Security Council reviews the mandate for its 350
cease-fire observers, Deputy Foreign Minister Nizar Hamdoon told The
Associated Press.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati also is expected
there, he said. He added that U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar would decide on a bilateral meeting.
   Jan Eliasson, the U.N. special envoy, said Sunday the decision
would be made after Perez de Cuellar assesses results of the talks
in Iran and Iraq.
   Eliasson, Sweden's U.N. ambassador, left Baghdad for New York on
Monday.
   His talks were aimed at resuming U.N.-sponsored peace
negotiations that broke down Aug. 25 over troop withdrawals and
ownership of the Shatt al-Arab waterway.
   Before leaving, Eliasson said the two sides agreed to form a
joint military working group to include commanders from Iran and
Iraq as well as U.N. peacekeepers. It would work on military
problems of a technical nature along the 740-mile cease-fire line,
he said.
   Hamdoon said the agreement was a step forward, but others were
needed.
   ``It helps to stabilize the cease-fire, but we don't think it
will be sufficient just to have a committee and sit back without an
(peace) agreement,'' he said.
</TEXT>
