<DOCNO> AP890130-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PolygamistDaughter     01-30 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polygamist Daughter,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daughter of Cult Leader Apparently Kills Self</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are investigating the apparent suicide of
the estranged daughter of the founder of a polygamist cult because
of the cult's reputation for ``blood atonement'' against defectors.
   Lillian Chynoweth, 33, a daughter of the late Ervil LeBaron,
founder of the Church of the Lamb of God, was shot once in the head,
Lt. Richard Holland said.
   Mrs. Chynoweth was found dead in her Houston home Saturday by her
13-year-old daughter, who was awakened by the gunshot. A
.357-caliber pistol was nearby.
   The pistol, Holland said, had been given to Mrs. Chynoweth's
14-year-old son by a family friend _ for protection in light of the
killings last June of Mrs. Chynoweth's husband, her brother-in-law
and a niece.
   There were no signs of forced entry or foul play, Holland said.
In addition, he said, Mrs. Chynoweth had been seeking treatment for
depression and had recently talked of suicide.
   Preliminary evidence points to suicide, ``but the investigation
is ongoing,'' Holland said. ``We are approaching it cautiously
because of the history of the family.''
   Last June 27, Mrs. Chynoweth's 36-year-old husband, Mark, was
found shot dead in his office at his Houston appliance store.
Minutes later, his brother, Duane, 31, and Duane's daughter,
Jennifer, 10, were found shot to death in the driveway of a vacant
home, where they had been called under the guise of delivering a new
washing machine.
   At the same time, Eddie Marston, 32, one of Ervil LeBaron's
stepsons and charged but never convicted as a killer for LeBaron,
was shot in Irving.
   The killings remain unsolved.
   ``It is reasonable to conclude that some of the things that
caused her depression were related to the murder of her husband,''
Holland said.
   Mrs. Chynoweth's brother, Isaac LeBaron, 20, committed suicide in
1983. He had suffered ``massive depression'' and had been released
from a hospital the day before his death.
   Isaac LeBaron was instrumental in the conviction of Ervil
LeBaron, sentenced to life in Utah State Prison in 1979 for ordering
the murder of Utah polygamist Rulon Allred. He later died in prison.
   Ervil's death in 1981 prompted the Chynoweths' defection from the
cult and their move to Houston, Holland said.
   Ervil believed he was ``the one mighty and strong prophet of
God'' and vowed in 1970 after a split with his brother, Joel, that
``blood will run to solve our problems.''
   The LeBaron group is believed responsible for at least 18
killings. The current leaders appear to operate from Mexico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Dogwoods     01-30 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dogwoods,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disease Strikes Dogwood Seedlings at Test Site Near Camp David</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush may not be seeing the dogwoods
bloom this spring at Camp David because of a devastating fungus
disease that could become a national epidemic among the native
trees, the Agriculture Department said Monday.
   USDA plant geneticist Frank S. Santamour said that the disease
has swept through native dogwood seedlings at a test site near the
presidential retreat in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains. The seedlings
were from 17 states and proved highly susceptible to anthracnose
disease.
   ``They all declined in vigor, and after two years 75 percent were
dead,'' Santamour said. He predicted that all of the test seedlings
will be dead by the end of 1989.
   Santamour, who works for the department's Agricultural Research
Service at the National Arboretum in Washington, said no North
American flowering dogwood trees of the species Cornus florida are
known to resist the disease.
   Asiatic or Chinese dogwood, Cornus kousa, which produces flowers
similar to C. florida, showed some leaf spotting from the disease
but otherwise were said to have performed well in Santamour's study.
   The fungus that causes dogwood anthracnose has not been
identified exactly, he said. But there appears to be no insect
carrier of the fungus, as with Dutch elm disease. The dogwood fungus
depends on wind and water to spread from tree to tree.
   Santamour said the origin of the disease outbreak is obscure. It
began in the late 1970s on the West Coast among C. nuttallii
dogwoods and the C. florida on the East Coast, he said.
   ``However, we can probably rule out environmental stress as a
casual factor,'' Santamour said.
   A 1984 survey of nearly 50,000 dogwoods in Catoctin Mountain Park
by the U.S. Park Service and USDA's Forest Service confirmed
scattered reports of the new devastating disease among the native
dogwoods.
   Santamour there is probably little hope for finding native
dogwoods resistant to anthracnose.
   ``If the disease continues to spread, nursery workers should be
cautioned against premature judgments on relative resistance of
plants that may have merely escaped the path of infection,'' he said.
   But Santamour said he found that dogwoods planted on lawns and
parks in the Catoctin area seem to have a better survival rate that
those in the forest.
   Dogwoods in the study were grown from seeds from Alabama,
Arkansas, Connecticut, Florida, Georgia, Kentucky, Louisiana,
Maryland, Michigan, Missouri, Mississippi, New Jersey, North
Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania and Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
