<FIRST>r a AM-InsultingTwins     01-30 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insulting Twins,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Halsted Street Twins Offer Fresh Rolls, Frosted with Insults</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben and Al Kohn serve up a little sass with the
coffee and sweet rolls at the break of dawn, jolting customers awake
before the caffeine can.
   For four years the 70-year-old Kohn twins have opened the doors
of the storefront coffee shop on Halsted Street at 3 a.m. and
dispensed insults and bad jokes along with the java, newspapers,
cigarettes, gum and other small items they sell.
   ``I guess people feel they can face anything the day brings after
facing the twins at 4:30 in the morning,'' said police Lt. Wayne
Wiberg, a longtime patron.
   Another officer on the beat, Sgt. Henry Pate, joked, ``They have
only one driver's license between them. One day we'll have to
fingerprint them to figure them out.''
   Although the store is only a few years old, the twins have lived
on the block all their lives. No one calls them Ben or Al because no
one knows which is which. They are known simply as ``the twins.''
   The two were born in a building across the street from the cafe,
the youngest of 12 children. They ran their father's handrolled
cigar and cigarette business in that building and sold hotdogs and
beer at two ballparks for 22 years.
   When the building burned down four years ago, the Kohns began the
coffee shop. They sleep in back on twin beds. Ben Kohn is divorced,
his brother a widower.
   The place, which has no name out front, is simple _ three
mismatched counters, a big space heater that switches on and off as
people warm their backsides, a dozen bar stools, a cash register and
two worn chairs where the twins sit and look out onto the street
when things are quiet.
   Despite the yelling inside the store, the twins have an
understated tolerance of ethnic differences in the blue-collar
neighborhood. They have learned to yell, curse and say ``Good
Morning'' and ``Get out, ya bum'' in Yiddish, Spanish, Lithuanian,
Polish, Italian and Greek.
   They go to sleep at 10 p.m., wake up about 1 a.m., pick up the
fresh rolls and open by 3 a.m., seven days a week.
   ``Retirement ain't for us,'' Al Kohn said one morning, sitting by
the sink.
   ``Routine. We're master of routine,'' said his brother as the two
lit cigarettes at the same time. ``Everyone knows we're always
here.''
</TEXT>
