<SECOND>AM-US-Auschwitz,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Group Says It Appears Vatican Will Miss Deadline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish organization said Monday it appeared
the Vatican will miss a deadline for removing a convent from the
grounds of the World War II Nazi death camp at Auschwitz.
   ``We are severely dismayed and disappointed because it appears
the convent will not be moved as stipulated'' in a 1987 agreement
between the Roman Catholic Church and Jewish groups, said Elan
Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress.
   Steinberg said a Jewish delegation visited the area of Poland
near the death camp, where the Vatican undertook to build a center
of prayer and education about the Nazi Holocaust, ``and not a spade
has been put in the ground.''
   Under the agreement, the center was also to house nuns from
Auschwitz and would be built within two years.
   A dozen nuns set up a convent in 1984 in what had been a theater
at the camp where millions of Jews were killed during World War II.
   Their move stirred a protest among Jews, who regard the site as a
memorial to the Holocaust and believe it should be left undisturbed.
   The archbishop of the French city of Lyon, Cardinal Albert
Decourtray, said last week that the nuns would move into a new
convent but he did not say where or when the building would go up.
   Steinberg called the cardinal's comments ``an apparent effort to
buy time'' in view of the Feb. 22 deadline.
