<FIRST>u w AM-US-Afghanistan Bjt   01-30 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan, Bjt,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Departing Soviets Said Enforcing `Scorched Earth' Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration accused the Soviet
Union on Monday of pursuing a ``scorched earth'' policy in
Afghanistan as its troops head home from the war-torn country.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said the Soviets
were conducting bombing raids in various areas, using both planes
based in Afghanistan and others flying from Soviet territory, while
also launching Scud missile attacks.
   By contrast, Redman said, U.S.-armed Afghan rebels were showing
restraint toward the departing Red Army, which is committed to
complete the withdrawal by Feb. 15.
   Redman gave no assessment of how fiercely the rebels were
pursuing their war against the forces of the Soviet-backed Kabul
government, nor did he offer assurances the Bush administration
would promote restraint.
   ``We support various efforts by the Afghan resistance to
formulate a political structure to replace the illegitimate regime
in Kabul,'' Redman said. ``But it is their structure. ... We don't
have a particular plan of our own.
   ``We can be helpful, but in the end this is something for the
Afghan people to determine,'' Redman said.
   Some 50,000 Soviet troops are quitting Afghanistan after nine
years of fighting alongside the Kabul government against the rebels,
who have received U.S. weapons through Pakistan.
   Both superpowers are continuing their military support.
   The withdrawal was stalled temporarily late last year by Moscow
in response to intenstified rebel attacks on the Soviet troops. The
Soviets, meanwhile, stepped up their own bombing and missile attacks.
   ``The Soviets continue what might even be called a scorched earth
policy, as they continue very, very intensive air activity,'' Redman
said.
   The attacks, he said, were ``both from aircraft based inside
Afghanistan as well as with aircraft based in the Soviet Union.''
   The U.S. spokesman added, ``We just don't believe that this kind
of a policy is what is called for at the time when Afghanistan ought
to be looking to the future.''
   With tensions rising, the United States decided last week to
temporarily close its embassy in Kabul and remove the staff of 11
American diplomats and security guards. The U.S. flag was hauled
down Monday, but the embassy staff did not leave.
   Redman said that bad weather closed the airport and that the
Americans ``are going to leave whenever weather conditions permit.''
   The embassy is near the presidential palace, the state radio and
secret police headquarters, all of which would be prime guerrilla
targets in a battle for the city.
   President Najib's government accused the United States of closing
the embassy as a means of inciting the guerrillas to more intense
warfare after the Red Army departs.
   But Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y. and the chairman of the House
Foeign Affairs Asian subcommittee, said the pullout was ``entirely
justifiable.''
   The departure of the embassy staff will leave 10 Americans in
Afghanistan, all missionaries.
</TEXT>
