<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-BushReport     01-30 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Bush Report,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>1984 Report May Be Guide to Bush's Thinking on S&amp;L System</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-S&amp;Ls-Bush listed on 1:30 p.m. news advisory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says he's not ready yet to
reveal his views on the best way to reform the savings and loan
system, but the report of a study group he headed in 1984 may be a
guide to his thinking.
   Bush's staff director for the Task Group on Regulation of
Financial Services, Washington attorney Richard Breeden, joined the
Whitst week and is expected to play the key role in
shaping the administration's S&amp;L plan, which the president hopes to
outline in a Feb. 9 speeche House staff la.
   Much has changed since Bush, then vice president, signed the task
group report. The magnitude of S&amp;L insolvencies had not yet come to
light.
   But, if the group's recommendations are any indication, they
suggest the president will take a cautious approach to reform rather
than advocate a wholesale restructuring of the industry.
   The 1984 study recognized what since has been identified as a key
contributor to the problem: permissive laws in some states that
allowed S&amp;Ls to stray into risky areas far removed from their
traditional business of making home mortgage loans.
   But rather than call for new regulation, the group emphasized a
system of incentives _ including risk-based insurance premiums and
hignd keeping
three separate insurance funds: for banks, thrifts and credit unions.
   But, it offered a mechanism for the financial system to evolve.
Thrifts that stuck primarily to mortgage lending would remain part
of a separate system. At a certain point, S&amp;Ls that entered enough
new areas, becoming more like banks, would have to join the bank
regulatory system with its stricter oversight.
