<FIRST>u i AM-Israel Bjt   01-30 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, Bjt,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabin Agrees To Modify Peace Plan To Attract Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, looking for
Palestinian support for a peace plan, said Monday he was willing to
work for elections in the occupied lands even if Arabs did not
immediately halt the uprising.
   An influential Moslem fundamentalist leader in the occupied Gaza
Strip said he supported the proposal.
   In Gaza, meanwhile, soldiers shot and wounded 15 Palestinians in
stone-throwing clashes, including a 16-year-old girl and a
15-year-old boy who were in critical condition, Arab doctors said.
   A 12-year-old boy was taken to a hospital in Israel with a
gunshot wound to the head, the doctors said. The army said it was
checking the reports.
   Rabin, speaking on army radio, said he was willing to drop his
earlier condition that Palestinians halt the violence of the
13-month uprising for several months before Israel would talk about
holding elections.
   Palestinians have rejected attaching preconditions to elections,
which would be the first in the territories since 1976.
   Rabin told legislators of his left-leaning Labor Party he was
willing to hold talks immediately with Palestinians. Only after
agreement was reached would hostilities have to end, he said.
   ``When there's agreement on the process, then a calm period will
have to begin, because to my mind if you want free elections they
cannot take place in an atmosphere of violence,'' Rabin said.
   Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, the leader of Moslem fundamentalists in the
Gaza Strip, said he supported the proposal.
   ``If there will be international supervision, there will be more
freedom for the Palestinians and this is the right way. There is no
other way to elect the representatives of the Palestinian people,''
he said on Israel Television's Arabic-language show.
   Yassin's statement apparently was aimed at the Palestine
Liberation Organization. The Moslem fundamentalist Hamas movement is
competing with the PLO over influence in the occupied lands.
   The latest conflict came Monday when PLO activists persuaded
Palestinians to ignore a Hamas-declared strike.
   Yassin also said he supported meetings between Palestinians and
Israeli officials. ``There is no escape from a dialogue,'' he said.
   The Moslem leader said he would meet with Rabin if he received an
invitation, said TV reporter Yoni Ben-Menachem, who interviewed
Yassin at his Gaza home.
   Israeli leftists have called for talks with the PLO. But the
right-wing Likud bloc and leaders of the mainstream Labor Party have
rejected the group, which most Palestinians say must be their
representative in negotiations.
   Likud legislators Monday criticized Rabin for authorizing a
meeting between pro-PLO leader Faisal Husseini, who has been jailed
for most of the 13-month uprising, and Rabin's top adviser on the
territories, Shmuel Goren.
   ``I think Husseini is not an appropriate route (for talks). I
think if he were, the defense minister wouldn't have had him sitting
in jail for his part in the riots and violence,'' said Likud
legislator Binyamin Begin, son of former Prime Minister Menachem
Begin.
   Husseini said after the meeting he believed the PLO would support
elections in the territories, but that the balloting would have to
be on the question of statehood and not for local representatives as
suggested by Israeli leaders.
   Also Monday, an adviser to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
announced Israel will go ahead with plans to build eight Jewish
settlements in the occupied lands this year despite the Arab
uprising and budget cuts.
   Michael Dekel, Shamir's adviser on settlements, said there was no
shortage of ``idealistic pioneers.''
   ``The moment people oppose you, you cannot raise your hands and
surrender, you have to struggle,'' Dekel said in an interview.
   Now, about 1.7 million Palestinians and 70,000 Jewish settlers
live in the West Bank and Gaza.
   Israel seized the territories in the 1967 Middle East war, and
U.S. officials have criticized the settlements as obstacles to peace.
   The uprising is in protest of Israeli rule of the lands. Since
the revolt began, 370 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have been killed.
   The army said Monday that an Arab mukhtar, or village leader, was
found stabbed to death in the West Bank village of Beit Lid.
   The circumstances of the slaying Sunday were unclear, but Arab
reporters said Mahmoud Salem Mahmoud, 65, may have been killed
because he was suspected of working for Israeli authorities.
   Army officials say more than 30 Palestinians have been killed
during the uprising by Arabs who suspected them of being
collaborators or informants.
</TEXT>
