<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Hawk-Window     01-30 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hawk-Window,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hawk Takes Dive, Gets Surprise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LADY'S ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hawk intent on making a meal of two
tiny finches plunged through a bedroom window, and all three birds
emerged shaken up but unscathed.
   ``There is a hole in the glass where he was diving in. There was
glass all over the bedroom,'' said Amy Perciful.
   Ms. Perciful said she heard the ``enormous crash'' about 5:30
p.m. Sunday.
   Rushing to a bedroom, she and a friend, Terry DeLoach, found her
three-tier, bamboo finch cage swinging wildly and a gray-and-white
hawk struggling to return to freedom.
   ``He wasn't cut, but he was so scared. Terry said the hawk's
heart was beating so fast. The main thing on his (the hawk's) mind
was getting out,'' she said.
   DeLoach threw a towel over the bird, carried him outdoors, and
released him.
   Ms. Perciful cared for her finches. ``My poor little birds. I
don't know why they didn't die of a heart attack.''
   The bird probably was a goshawk, which spend the winter along the
eastern coast, said Charlie Zemp, regional marine biologist for the
state Wildlife and Marine Resources Department.
</TEXT>
