<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Thatcher     01-30 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Thatcher,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Honors Mrs. Gandhi</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher unveiled a bust of
assassinated Indian prime minister Indira Gandhi on Monday and vowed
to keep helping India fight terrorists.
   In a ceremony honoring Mrs. Gandhi, Mrs. Thatcher said, ``I think
we both understood what to some people is a paradox: that one can be
warm, human, loving, knowing all the little things of life _ and at
the same time firm, determined, decisive.''
   The ceremony at the Indian High Commission in London came on
Indian Martyr's Day, the anniversary of the murder of independence
leader Mohandas K. Gandhi in 1948.
   Mrs. Thatcher and Mrs. Gandhi, whose father Jawaharlal Nehru was
also a prime minister, both were students and honorary fellows of
Oxford University's Somerville College.
   Mrs. Gandhi was assassinated by Sikh militants in 1984. Mrs.
Thatcher called her death ``another occasion when terrorism deprived
us of a greatly loved and respected figure.''
   Britain has suffered repeated terrorist attacks mounted by the
Irish Republican Army.
   Mrs. Thatcher pledged to continue helping India, now led by Mrs.
Gandhi's son Rajiv, in fighting extremists.
   ``The close cooperation that we have built up between the Indian
and British governments in the fight against terrorism is a very
significant development. I am determined to see it grow closer
still,'' the prime minister said.
</TEXT>
