<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceAcademy     01-30 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Academy,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Classes Resume At Academy Where Overworked Cadet Was Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Classes resumed Monday at the police academy
where one cadet died and 16 others fell ill following a boot
camp-style workout of pushups and laps last fall.
   The 37 recruits of Class 13 were given haircuts and a lecture on
nutrition Monday, a far cry from the strenuous regimen their
predecessors underwent their first day, according to the new head of
the state Criminal Justice Training Council, which oversees the
training of municipal police officers.
   ``What happened here at Agawam was an extreme and not at all
representative of what the training council intended to go on,''
Patrick M. Hamilton said.
   Class 13 is the first at the academy since the training session
that left 16 cadets hospitalized in September from exhaustion and
dehydration. Cadet Timothy Shepard of Pittsfield collapsed the first
day of class, Sept. 19, and died Nov. 2 from his injuries.
   The other cadets were released and allowed back to class for the
remainder of the 14-week course, but several were barred from
physical training because of the injuries.
   Attorney General James Shannon, who investigated the training,
said he found a ``massive failure'' of the bureaucracy overseeing
it. A legislative investigation into police training is under way,
as is a grand jury investigation into the training council's
financial dealings.
   An inquest into Shepard's death is expected to conclude this week
and District Judge Irving Goldblatt said he plans to issue a report
in a few weeks on whether criminal charges should be brought against
the state troopers who were in charge of training the class of 50
cadets.
   The tragedy, however, has already changed the way municipal
police are trained in Massachusetts.
   The latest class of recruits from 19 police departments in
western Massachusetts opened with four hours of inspections,
instructions on rules and regulations, haircuts and marching drills,
according to David Dacyczyn, who took over as academy director in
the shakeup following the injuries to the cadets.
   On Tuesday, the cadets begin physical training at the Springfield
YMCA, where they will undergo an hour of swimming, aerobic workouts
and other physical training daily, Dacyczyn said.
   Gone are the confusing orders shouted at cadets and hundreds of
pushups meted out as punishment. ``They will be treated as adults
and physical education will not be used as a disciplinary tool,''
Hamilton said.
</TEXT>
