<FIRST>r w AM-US-Iran     01-30 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Iran,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Invites Iran To Open Dialogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department reaffirmed Monday its
willingness to open a dialogue with Iran and took issue with an
Iranian official's contention that Washington is to blame for the
continuing impasse in relations.
   Restating what had been the Reagan administration position,
department spokesman Charles Redman said the United States is
prepared to open an ``authoritative dialogue'' with Iranian
officials on a formal end to Iran's war with Iraq, an end of Iranian
support for terrorism and freedom for American hostages held by
pro-Iranian forces in Lebanon.
   The administration believes that Iran may have some influence
over the groups holding the hostages.
   The advent of the Bush administration in Washington has
heightened speculation about the possibility of an easing of
tensions between the two countries and an Iranian effort to help
secure the release of the nine hostages.
   In his inaugural address, President Bush appealed to Iran for
help in freeing the hostages and promised a reciprocal gesture of
good will if Iran was receptive to the idea.
   Since then, however, the two sides have disagreed on which one
should take the first step.
   Redman's comments Monday were touched off by remarks by Iran's
deputy foreign minister for European and American affairs, Mohammad
Javad Larijani, who called on the United States to show good will by
making some unilateral gestures.
   Specifically, Larijani said the United States should pay at least
token compensation to families of the 290 people, mostly Iranians,
who died when a U.S. Navy vessel shot down an Iranian airliner last
July over the Persian Gulf.
   Redman said that the United States remains committed to
compensation but that Iran has not responded to U.S. requests for
information about the families. He said information is needed to
help U.S. officials decide on compensation levels and methods of
distributing the funds.
   Larijani also said the United States could show good will by
releasing ``undisputed'' funds tied up in litigation in the
U.S.-Iran Claims Tribunal at the Hague. Redman denied that there are
any undisputed funds being discussed in that forum.
   As an example, Redman cited a tribunal decision concerning
military property owned by Iran but held by the United States. He
noted that the tribunal decided that the United States was not
obligated to return the property but to pay its value as of March
1981.
   ``We are currently trying to determine the value for the
thousands of items involved. Iran and the United States will each be
filing its position on value to the tribunal in due course. It's a
complicated matter and it's not undisputed,'' he said.
   The tribunal was set up in 1981 as part of the settlement that
led to the release of the 52 American hostages in Iran. It is
designed to resolve financial and property claims the two countries
have against each other.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
