<FIRST>r i AM-Canada     01-30 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mulroney Announces Cabinet for Second Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said Monday he will
keep his external affairs and international trade ministers for his
second term, which he won in a campaign waged over a historic trade
pact with the United States.
   In announcing his new Cabinet, however, the Progressive
Conservative leader said he would change his defense minister.
   The new 39-member Cabinet retains Joe Clark as external affairs
minister, John Crosbie as international trade minister, and Michael
Wilson as finance minister.
   Defense Minister Perrin Beatty was moved to health, and Bill
McKnight was moved from Indian affairs to defense.
   Reporters asked Mulroney if the shift of defense ministers meant
an upcoming change for the major pending defense program, the plan
to acquire nuclear-powered submarines for Arctic patrol.
   ``The government is committed to the policy ... but that, like
everything else, will be reviewed no doubt by the new Cabinet,'' the
prime minister said.
   Mulroney's party won a second consecutive majority government
Nov. 21 after a campaign bitterly fought over the free-trade
agreement that Mulroney signed in January 1988 with former President
Reagan. Parliament returned in December to complete legislation for
the agreement, which took effect Jan. 1.
   The new Cabinet includes six new ministers, mostly to replace
Conservatives who lost in last fall's elections.
</TEXT>
