<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Priest     01-30 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Priest,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Solidarity Priest Found Dead After Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-Solidarity priest was found dead
Monday morning after fire swept through his home in the northeastern
city of Bialystok, said church officials and the state-run news
agency PAP.
   The Rev. Stanislaw Suchowolec, 31, of the Immaculate Heart of
Mary parish in Bialystok apparently died of smoke inhalation,
according to results of an investigation by the local prosecutor and
church officials, PAP said.
   Investigators had not determined the cause of the fire.
   The Rev. Maciej Pawlik, parish provost, said a neighoring priest
found Suchowolec's body.
   Suchowolec, an active supporter of the banned independent union
movement Solidarity, had reported harassment in the past, union
officials said.
   He was the second priest to die of unnatural causes in the past
10 days.
   On Jan. 21, a church lay worker found the body of the Rev. Stefan
Niedzielak, 74, who maintained a shrine to Poles killed in the
Soviet Union.
   The Warsaw prosecutor said Niedzielak died of a broken neck, but
the circumstances of his death have not been disclosed.
   The priest who found Suchowolec's body said he believed an
electric spark started the fire.
   ``The curtains and coverings were all burned, so it seems he must
have inhaled carbon monoxide,'' the priest said on condition of
anonymity.
   In his early years as a priest, Suchowolec served as vicar in
Sucho Wola, the home village of the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko, the
pro-Solidarity priest who was murdered by security police in 1984.
   Suchowolec organized pilgrimages to Popieluszko's gravesite in
Warsaw, about 119 miles southwest of Bialystok.
   ``He was a wonderful Solidarity priest,'' said Zofia Romaszewka
of the Solidarity Commission on Intervention and Law-Abidance, which
keeps a record of human rights violations in Poland.
   Romaszewska said Suchowolec told the commission in the past that
his car had been tampered with and that he had been assaulted.
   According to Zdzislaw Krol, chancellor of the Warsaw curia,
Niedzielak had received anonymous threats before his death.
   More than 5,000 people attended Niedzielak's funeral in Warsaw.
</TEXT>
