<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     01-30 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Relief Officials to Visit Rebel-held Parts of Sudan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two officials of private U.S. relief groups
will visit southern Sudan this week to advance plans for providing
help to rebel-held areas, a rebel official said Monday.
   That official and a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi
declined to identify the officials or their organizations. However,
the U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, confirmed
the supplies would come from the U.S. Agency for International
Development.
   Richard Mula, secretary general of the rebels' Sudan Relief and
Rehabilitation Association, told The Associated Press the officials
plan to visit the rebel-held southeastern towns of Kapoeta, Ikoto,
Pachala and Pibor.
   ``They want to go and make initial assessment of the needs of the
people,'' Mula said, adding that they plan to leave Wednesday and
are awaiting clearance from the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   The army is the military wing of Sudan People's Liberation
Movement. The rebels have been fighting the government since 1983,
and U.N. officials say the war has caused a famine that killed more
than 5,000 people last year.
   Officials in Washington said last week they were exploring ways
of providing emergency relief to rebel-held parts of southern Sudan.
U.S. officials say they are providing relief to government-held
southern towns.
   Mula said supplies for rebel areas would be distributed by
private groups, ``but if they can't, our field staff will do so.''
   He said about 2 million people in rebel-held areas need at least
20,000 tons of food, as well as clothing and medicine.
   The rebels say they control about 90 percent of the largely
Christian or animist South. They are demanding reforms from the
Moslem-dominated government in Khartoum.
   During the fighting, a third of southern Sudan's 6 million
civilians have fled to the north or to neighboring countries.
</TEXT>
