<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Racism     01-30 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Racism,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Whites Threaten Indian Family That Moved Into Their Neighborhood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Monday told people to
avoid vigilante tactics after whites brandished a noose and sprayed
racist slogans on the walls of a house that an Indian family bought
in their neighborhood.
   The neighborhood, Mayfair, is classified as whites-only, although
many people of Indian descent have moved there in recent years in
violation of the Group Areas Act.
   Police officers came to the area Sunday when several dozen
right-wing whites staged a protest outside a house bought by an
Indian electrical engineer. A noose was draped over a wall near the
house, windows had been broken, and racist slogans had been painted
on the building.
   Police headquarters said charges of malicious damage to property
were being investigated and that anyone with a grievance should file
a complaint with police rather than take the law into their own
hands.
   The South African Press Agency reported Sunday that the Indian
owner, who has a wife and two children, recounted the incident in a
telephone interview on condition he not be identified.
   ``I told them (the white protesters) that I was a non-violent
person who did not want any trouble,'' the man was quoted as saying.
``They continued to use the foulest of language.''
   Residents of the neighborhood told SAPA that furniture was moved
into the house on Sunday morning and was removed several hours later.
   Among those joining the protest was Hendrick Claasan, who who
represents the neighborhood on behalf of the extreme-right
Conservative Party on the Johannesburg City Council.
   He told police that residents were entitled to enforce provisions
of the Group Areas Act, which mandates racial segregation of
residential areas.
   Newspapers reported that several of the whites at the protest
threatened violence if the Indian family moved in.
</TEXT>
