<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Quake     01-30 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Quake,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Say World's Help Not Needed in Tadzhik Quake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No help from abroad is needed for last week's
earthquake in Tadzhikistan, an official said Monday. The Soviet
Union accepted at least $100 million worth of aid after the
disastrous Armenian quake in December.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov said the temblor
Jan. 23 in a rural area of the Central Asian republic had ``limited
consequences.'' It caused a landslide that buried three mountain
villages and killed 274 people.
   Nearly 100 times as many people were killed by the Dec. 7 quake
in Armenia, after which aid arrived from more than 70 countries. It
was the first time World War II the Soviets accepted help from
abroad because of a disaster.
   Gerasimov said offers of aid came after the Tadzhikistan quake
from the United States, the Netherlands, Britain, Italy and many
other countries.
   ``We appreciate this and we are thankful to the countries,
organizations and individuals who have offered their help, but the
nature and the consequences of the earthquake in Tadzhikistan are
limited,'' he told a news conference.
   ``The number of people who need medical aid is not that large, so
there is no special need for equipment or the presence of foreign
experts or specialists in the area,'' he said. Officials said 75
victims of the Tadzhik quake had been hospitalized.
   Sharora village, 18 miles southwest of Dushanbe, capital of the
republic, was dedicated as a common grave for the victims, many of
whom were buried alive by a wall of mud.
   Officials said destroyed villages would be rebuilt elsewhere.
Tass, the official news agency, said homeless people were being
housed in mobile units, shepherds' cottages and tents.
</TEXT>
