<HEAD>France Sends Emergency Aid to Cyclone Victims on Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France is sending food, beds and blankets, water,
and relief specialists to the Indian Ocean island of Reunion, where
a cyclone hit over the weekend and killed at least two people, a
government official said Monday.
   More than 60 people were also injured when Cyclone Firinga with
up to 155 mph winds swept the island off East Africa on Saturday.
The storm knocked down communication lines, cut road and rail links,
and left up to 130,000 homes without electricity or water.
   France is sending 15,000 food ration kits, 1,500 beds and
blankets, 20 cisterns of water and five experts, said Louis
LePensec, French Minister of Overseas Territories.
   About 400 troops and 50 vehicles from a French army base on the
island have been mobilized to help civilians.
   Reunion, which is governed as part of France, has a population of
about 600,000.
