<FIRST>u p AM-Quayle     01-30 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Says God-Hating Communist System Brought Evil into World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle told religious
broadcasters Monday that the Soviet government system, rooted in
``hatred of God,'' has brought much evil into the world.
   He quoted Communist revolution leader Vladimir Lenin as saying
the idea of god is ``unutterable vileness ... of the most dangerous
kind.''
   ``That was Lenin and unfortunately his gospel is still actively
pursued in the Soviet Union,'' Quayle said.
   He also said that if Moscow's planned international human rights
conference occurs, the United States must ensure that it ``is not
just a public relations extravaganza for the Soviet leadership.''
   ``We must insist that all the agreed-upon conditions for such a
conference are met _ conditions such as free contact of Soviet
citizens with delegates and visitors _ and that all scheduled
meetings take place in conditions of unimpeded access and openness.''
   Quayle made his comments in a speech to the annual conference of
the National Religious Broadcasters.
   President Bush has said he would follow through on former
President Reagan's agreement for U.S. participation in the
conference, but also has said that Soviet human rights performance
will be monitored in the meantime.
   Quayle quoted Bush's campaign comment that the Iron Curtain
separating the East and West still exists, but that it is beginning
to rust.
   Then the vice president went on to attack the Soviet system,
saying that Soviet citizens are now speaking out against the
concentration of power by the Communist Party.
   ``How did the Communist Party gain such appalling confidence in
its own wisdom, indeed, its own omniscience. I think the root of the
matter all comes back to a hatred of God, to a rejection of the
entire concept of a religious system,'' Quayle said.
   He contrasted the Soviet and American revolutions, saying that
founders of the United States had a ``belief in the existence of a
creator whose laws have placed irrevocable limits on the power of
the state.''
   ``Look how much good has come into the world as a result of the
first revolution and how much evil has entered the world because of
the second,'' Quayle said.
   His comments, in language and tone, differed from those Bush has
made recently about the Soviets. However, Bush has urged a cautious
approach to U.S.-Soviet relations, which seemed to be rapidly
improving as Reagan's term came to an end.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Quayle's
comments were not inconsistent with administration policy.
   Quayle also mentioned his upcoming three-day trip to Venezuela
and El Salvador.
   ``My message will be democracy, democracy and more democracy,''
he said.
   He will attend Thursday's inauguration of Venezuela's new
president, Carlos Andres Perez, where he will be in the company of
some two-dozen heads of state and will confer with some.
   The El Salvador stop on the way back Friday will be focused on
emphasizing human rights, officials said. Elections are scheduled in
that nation in just over a month.
</TEXT>
