<FIRST>r w AM-DetroitNewspapers     01-30 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coalition Says it Will Seek to Stop Partial Merger of Detroit Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of Michigan advertisers and
newspaper readers said Monday it will ask a federal appeals court to
reconsider a three-judge panel's decision to allow a partial merger
of Detroit's major daily newspapers.
   Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press will ask the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit to block the
merger of The Detroit News and the Detroit Free Press until all 13
judges can rehear the appeal, said attorneys for the organization.
   The three appeals judges, in an opinion issued Friday, said the
newspapers qualified for a partial exemption from federal antitrust
laws and could implement the proposed joint operating agreement.
   William Schultz, one of the coalition's attorneys, said the
500-member organization would argue that ``this is a case of
exceptional importance'' that deserves a hearing by the full appeals
court. He said the panel's decision puts newspaper competition in 26
other cities in jeopardy.
   If the decision is allowed to stand, any corporation ``with a
deep pocket can go in there and cut prices,'' forcing financial
losses and setting up the conditions necessary to apply for a joint
operating agreement, Schultz said.
   The News, owned by Gannett Co. Inc., and the Free Press, owned by
Knight-Ridder Inc., have said they will merge their business and
production operations beginning Feb. 6. Knight-Ridder had said it
would close the Free Press if the partial merger were disapproved.
Both the News and the Free Press have reported heavy losses over the
past few years.
   There was no immediate comment Monday from Gannett, Knight-Ridder
or The News.
   Free Press Publisher David Lawrence said the papers would go
ahead with the JOA unless another stay is issued by the court.
   ``After almost three years, it's time for our lives to go
ahead,'' he said. ``Every issue has been heard. ... Fair is fair,
and we need to proceed.''
   The agreement, approved last year by the Justice Department but
stalled by the appeal, allows the newspapers to combine advertising,
circulation, production and other business operations to cut costs.
Their news and editorial departments would remain separate as
required by the Newspaper Preservation Act, a law intended to
preserve competing editorial voices when one of the newspapers is in
danger of financial failure.
   The newspapers have announced their intent to raise newsstand
prices should the agreement go into affect and also have said they
expect advertising rates would rise under a partial merger.
</TEXT>
