<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Rights     01-30 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Rights,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Calls For International Pressure To Stop Political Executions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amnesty International on Monday called for
international pressure on Iran to halt torture and political
executions, which the human rights group says have totaled more than
1,000 since July.
   The London-based group also expressed concern about Iran's
anti-drug crackdown, in which at least 113 people convicted of
trafficking or possession have been shot or hanged since the first
of the year.
   Amnesty submitted the information in a statement to the U.N.
Human Rights Commission, which began its annual meeting Monday in
Geneva.
   Amnesty International said other human rights violations that
have persisted in Iran include detention without trial and
amputation, usually of the four fingers of the right hand, of which
it said 21 instances ofhad been recorded.
   The organization said the amputations were ``judicial punishment
for repeated theft.''
   The group also said it was concerned about a massive anti-drug
crackdown and said about people were unfairly convicted.
   Tehran radio reported Sunday that 22 more drug smugglers were
hanged publicly in various Iranian cities in the previous three
days, raising the total to 113 in the crackdown launched two weeks
ago.
   ``Amnesty International urges the international community to use
whatever channels are available to persuade the Iranian government
to put an end to the present wave of public executions and to
implement and observe judicial and other procedures to safeguard the
human rights of its citizens,'' the group said in its statement.
   ``Since the end of July 1988, Amnesty International has recorded
over 1,000 names of political prisoners who have reportedly been
executed,'' it said. ``And further reports are still being
received.''
   The group said it expected a prisoner amnesty for the 10th
anniversary of the founding of the Islamic Republic in February but
that any positive impact of such a move would be ``muted because
hundreds, if not thousands of prisoners will be killed before the
amnesty comes into effect.''
   Revolutionary leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini has pardoned
4,500 convicts imprisoned in the northeastern province of Khorasan
and plans to start releasing them Tuesday when celebrations begin,
the official Islamic Republic News Agency has said.
   Amnesty said it appealed to Iran on behalf of hundreds of
prisoners at risk and asked for comment on reported victims, but it
received no responses.
   The wave of executions apparently was sparked by an incursion
into western Iran from Iraq by the National Liberation Army, a group
backed by the opposition group People's Mujahedeen Organization of
Iran, Amnesty said.
   Many victims were from that group and other opposition parties
and groups involved in armed opposition to the government, the
statement said.
   Many were imprisoned for years before they were shot to death or
hanged ``and among them there were a large number of prisoners of
conscience and others serving prison terms imposed after unfair
trials for their non-violent political activity,'' the statement
said.
   It said more people connected with opposition groups were being
reported detained without charge, young people were being singled
out for random searches on the street by Revolutionary Guards and
floggings remain common.
</TEXT>
