<SECOND>AM-Senate-Mosbacher,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Refuses to Postpone Vote on Mosbacher Confirmation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee
on Monday rejected a private group's request to delay the
confirmation vote on Commerce Secretary-designate Robert Mosbacher
until more is known about his campaign fund-raising for George Bush.
   Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., sent a letter to the group,
Common Cause, saying action on Mosbacher's nomination would not be
postponed because it would be wrong to ``raise sand'' over conduct
that was allowed under federal election law.
   The committee is scheduled to vote Tuesday on Mosbacher's
nomination.
   Common Cause said the vote should be postponed because the
Republican National Committee has yet to release a full and accurate
list of the individuals and corporations that donated at least
$100,000 each to the ``Team 100'' fund-raising drive led by
Mosbacher, who was Bush's chief fund-raiser.
   The Republican National Committee released a list of individuals
who had made contributions, but said much of the money was given on
behalf of corporations which were not identified.
   In a letter to Hollings, Common Cause president Fred Wertheimer
said the information about corporate donors was needed ``to allow
the public to be able to identify any possible connections that
might arise between the soft-money contributions and any direct
interest the contributors may end up having in issues before the
Commerce Department under Mr. Mosbacher's leadership.''
   Hollings said that while he would not postpone action on the
nomination, he planned to introduce legislation to limit spending in
federal elections.
   ``The fault here lies with the Congress and not with Mr.
Mosbacher,'' he said.
</TEXT>
