<DOCNO> AP890130-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UN-HumanRights     01-30 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Human Rights,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba, Palestinians Among Topics At Commission's Annual Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Human Rights Commission on Monday opened
an annual session expected to focus attention on alleged violations
in Cuba and the Israeli-occupied territories.
   Opening speakers at the six-week session cited encouraging signs
in regions long subject to the 43-nation panel's scrutiny _ Iran,
Afghanistan and Namibia _ and in U.S.-Soviet relations.
   Jan Martenson of Sweden, U.N. under secretary-general for human
rights, said the 43-nation meeting ``takes place at a time of great
hope and expectation,'' although the world remains ``plagued by
daily violations of human rights.''
   But Amnesty International, in a statement to the commission on
Monday, called for international pressure on Iran to stop a wave of
more than 1,000 political executions since July. The London-based
human rights group also expressed concern about at least 113
executions this month in Iran's crackdown on drugs.
   The commission's 45th session runs through March 10 and will
culminate with the annual passing of a package of resolutions.
   Delegates are to consider its first special report on Cuba, a
result of unprecedented pressure by the Reagan administration at the
last two sessions.
   The traditional debate on the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip is likely to be sharpened by the 15-month Palestinian
uprising. About 370 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have been killed in
the rebellion.
   New reports are also scheduled from special investigators on
Afghanistan, Iran, Chile, Guatemala and El Salvador. Other reports
will deal with torture, summary executions and religious intolerance.
   The panel is to vote on two longstanding projects: a draft
convention on the rights of the child and a proposed amendment to
the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights calling for
abolition of the death penalty.
   Restating Washington's position, Richard Williamson, U.S.
assistant secretary of state for international organization affairs,
recently said a ``crucial test'' for the commission's credibility is
whether it decides this year to continue scrutiny of Cuba.
   He said the Cuba report is expected to show that Fidel Castro's
government ``does indeed deprive its citizens of most of the basic
human rights.''
   But a group of commission envoys who visited Cuba last year to
gather information and testimony from alleged victims of abuse has
failed so far to agree on a final report.
   U.N. officials say the report will be presented by midsession and
is expected to be less critical of Cuba than the United States hoped.
   Armando Valladares, a former Cuban political prisoner, heads the
U.S. delegation for the second straight year.
   Cuba at this session begins a three-year term on the commission
after a five-year absence.
</TEXT>
