<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BridgeSafety     01-30 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Safety,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Review Sought of Bridge-Inspection Rule Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An auto-safety advocacy group and relatives of
people killed in a New York bridge collapse filed a petition Monday
asking the Federal Highway Administration to reconsider a bridge
inspection rule they said showed ``a callous indifference toward
public safety.''
   The rule, passed last August and affecting some 122,000 bridges
nationwide, allows states to inspect bridges every four years
instead of every two years _ as previously required _ and requires
an underwater inspection every five years.
   The federal agency ``has issued the final rule despite the
documented inadequacies of state bridge inspection programs covering
576,000 bridges,'' Clarence M. Ditlow III, executive director of the
Center for Auto Safety, said in a letter accompanying the petition
by the center and relatives of three victims of the 1987 New York
State Thruway bridge collapse.
   ``For example, the National Transportation Safety Board, which
opposed the rule, identified insufficient state inspection practices
as a major contributing factor in the deadly collapse of the
Schoharie Creek bridge,'' he said.
   The span fell into the Schoharie Creek on April 5, 1987, after
days of rain and flooding. Four cars and a tractor-trailer plunged
into the water, killing 10 people. A year later, the chairman of the
National Transportation Safety Board made an urgent call for highway
bridge inspections, noting that 43,000 bridges in the United States
had not been inspected within two years, as was then required by the
Federal Highway Administration.
   Henry Jasney, a spokesman for the Center for Auto Safety, said
Monday that the highway agency had no data or engineering analyses
to support changing its bridge inspection rule.
   ``Essentially what it does is it pinches pennies and saves some
money on inspections, but at the cost of better safety,'' he said.
</TEXT>
