<FIRST>r a AM-HaitianRefugees 1stLd-Writethru a0645 01-30 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haitian Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0645,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Boat People of 1989 Intercepted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT that boat has not reached shore, UPDATING
that officials intend to do interviews in international water.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 180 Haitian refugees crammed aboard a
sailboat were detained Monday after being intercepted eight miles
off Miami, authorities said.
   The group reportedly included two pregnant women and a child,
said spokesman Gary Starks.
   A tugboat spotted the wood-hulled vessel at about 2:30 p.m., and
the Coast Guard immediately dispatched a patrol boat to meet it,
Starks said.
   It was not known how large the sailboat was or the condition of
the Haitians aboard. The boats are usually hand-made and ramshackle.
The vessel was allowed to continue toward shore, and immigration
officials were to interview the people aboard while the board
remained in international water, Starks said.
   ``I think clearly it indicates the terrible conditions that still
exist in Haiti socially, economically and politically,'' said Perry
Rivkind, district director of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
   A boat with 96 Haitians arrived in Marathon about a month ago,
and the Coast Guard has interdicted a ``massive'' number of would-be
Haitian immigrants closer to their homeland, Rivkind said.
   The Coast Guard said it intercepted 4,712 Haitians last year and
has stopped more than 18,000 since the program began in 1981. Almost
all were immediately returned to Haiti.
   Monday's boatload arrived just a day after about 200 Haitians
protested the treatment of their compatriots at the Krome Avenue
Detention Center in southwest Dade County. Nearly 300 Haitians are
being held there pending review of their asylum requests.
   The demonstration was sponsored by the Haitian organization
Veye-Yo. The protesters said black refugees were more likely to be
held for deportation than are white immigrants.
   Immigration officials have maintained that most Haitians entering
the United States are not eligible for asylum because they are
seeking economic refuge and not fleeing political persecution.
   Rivkind said Krome is at capacity and it would be difficult to
place Monday's arrivals there.
   ``We could put people there on an emergency basis and
subsequently move them out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
