<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Solidarity     01-30 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Says Union Can Be Called Solidarity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has decided Solidarity
can be used in a trade union name, which has been forbidden since
the Soviet bloc's first free union was outlawed in 1982, the
official news agency PAP said Monday.
   ``A name of a trade union, apart from a name of an enterprise,
branch, kind of work or profession, may also contain additional
names such as the word `Solidarity,' according to the decision made
by the Supreme Court,'' the agency reported.
   ``It was decided that this decision will have the form of a law,
obligatory for all courts.''
   An appeal of a lower-court decision that a Solidarity committee
could not be registered at an accounting company in Lublin,
southeastern Poland, was the basis of the ruling. The October 1982
law outlawing Solidarity limited the words permissible in a trade
union's name.
   The Supreme Court said the Lublin court based its decision on the
1982 law and a State Council resolution, but the justices declared:
   ``Such limits have no confirmation in the law. The law, according
to the Supreme Court, based on the principle of pluralism, allows
the organization of more than one union at an enterprise.''
   ``If there are several trade union organizations at an
enterprise, each of them should have a name which would identify it,
which would be impossible if a name contained only elments defined
by the State Council resolution,'' the court said, according to the
PAP report.
   Rzeczpospolita, the government daily, said the court made its
ruling on Saturday.
   Lech Walesa founded Solidarity during the strikes of August 1980.
It was suppressed after the martial law was declared in December
1981, then outlawed.
   In a policy reversal Jan. 18, the Communist Party Central
Committee said more than one union would be allowed in an
enterprise, opening the way for Solidarity to be made legal again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
