<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     01-30 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska's Cold Coming Our Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bitterly cold temperatures continued Monday in Alaska, with the
cold air headed toward the northern Rockies and Plains, and rain was
scattered from the Gulf Coast to the Northeast.
   A high pressure area centered over Fairbanks, Alaska, kept
northern and central parts of the state in the deep freeze for the
15th straight day. Low temperatures across the region included 62
degrees below zero at McGrath, 59 below at Fort Yukon and Northway,
51 below at Fairbanks and 44 below at Barrow.
   A cold front curving across south-central and western Canada was
expected to sag across the northern Rockies and northern Plains over
the next few days and guide the arctic air from Alaska southward.
   Strong gusty wind whipped over the eastern slopes of the Rockies
from Montana into Wyoming, caused by a strong pressure changes
between low pressure over southwestern Saskatchewan and high
pressure over northern Utah.
   Gusts in Montana were clocked to 105 mph near Choteau and to 102
mph near Augusta, west of Great Falls. Gusts reached 96 mph at Cut
Bank, 80 mph at Livingston and Browning, and 65 mph at Del Bonita,
north of Cut Bank.
   In Wyoming, wind gusted to 63 mph at Cody.
   A cold front swept into the Atlantic Coast region with numerous
showers ahead of it. New York City got a half-inch of rain in the
morning.
   The cold front extended into the central Gulf Coast and showers
and isolated thundershowers were scattered across Georgia into
southern Alabama. Amounts were less than an inch.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 13
degrees at Gunnison, Colo., to 83 at West Palm Beach, Fla. Monday
morning's low in the 48 contiguous states was 24 degrees below zero
at Jackson, Wyo.
   For Tuesday, showers were forecast across the Pacific Northwest.
Scattered snowshowers were forecast from northern Montana through
North Dakota into Upper Michigan as the leading edge of much colder
air plunges southward. Scattered showers were forecast across
north-central and northeastern New York state into northern Vermont,
with snowshowers scattered over northern Maine.
   Highs in the 20s and 30s were predicted in southern Idaho and
from the northern high Plains through the northern Plains into the
northern Great Lakes, and across northern Maine; in the 40s from the
Pacific Northwest into the central Intermountain region between the
Sierra Nevada and Rockies, and from the upper Mississippi Valley
through the Great Lakes into New England; in the 70s from the
central high Plains into Texas and the western Gulf Coast, over the
Los Angeles basin, and across northern and central Florida; in the
low 80s across southern Florida; and in the 50s and 60s across much
of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
