<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ConvictedDonors     01-30 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Convicted Donors,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Wants Death Row Prisoners To Become Organ Donors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man awaiting execution on Oklahoma's
death row wants to donate his organs, and a physician thinks he and
other condemned criminals should be allowed to do so.
   ``A single condemned criminal can truly recompense society by
saving the lives of at least five other dying persons,'' said Dr.
Jack Kevorkian. ``Every time you execute someone in this country you
lose two kidneys, two lungs and a heart.''
   The Royal Oak doctor has quit pathology to devote time to helping
Richard J. Rojem Jr. and others like him.
   Rojem, 31, is awaiting execution in the Oklahoma State
Penitentiary after his 1985 conviction for the rape and murder of
his 8-year-old stepdaughter the previous year. Rojem said he wants
to be an organ donor, but prison officials have been slow to act on
his request.
   The convict said he has six more legal appeals in Oklahoma before
his death sentence could become final. Jerry Massie, a spokesman for
the Oklahoma Department of Corrections, speculated that the request
would not be granted ``for security reasons.''
   Kevorkian is working to change laws to provide for execution by
``irreversible anesthesia'' _ a condition that would be similar to
so-called brain death. That method would permit surgeons to take
organs while they are healthy and transplantable.
   Organs often are worthless for transplant purposes after death by
electrocution, hanging, firing squad or lethal gas, he said. After
lethal injection, the method of execution in Oklahoma, only corneas
and kidneys can be used _ if they are removed immediately, Kevorkian
said.
   Many doctors say they have reservations about irreversible
anesthesia because it would directly involve them in an execution.
   ``I want nothing to do with it,'' said Dr. Darrell J. Campbell
Jr., a transplant specialist at the University of Michigan Medical
Center in Ann Arbor.
   Rojem's request comes at a time when more than 16,000 Americans
need new organs, according to the United Networks for Organ Sharing
in Richmond, Va.
   ``He (Rojem) has the right to make an organ donation,'' said
Henry Schwarzschild, spokesman for the American Civil Liberties
Union in New York. ``But it is not an absolute right. The state of
Oklahoma's position may be that he is free to do so, but it doesn't
have an obligation to provide facilities.''
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--SmithsonianTV     01-30 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Smithsonian TV,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smithsonian Plans TV Series on Latin America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Smithsonian Institution will mark the 500th
anniversary of Columbus' discovery of America with a $5 million
series of television documentaries on Latin American history and
culture, written and narrated by Mexican author Carlos Fuentes.
   Robert McC. Adams, secretary of the Smithsonian, told a news
briefing Monday that the five one-hour TV programs entitled ``The
Buried Mirror'' are scheduled to premiere in the fall of 1991.
   Adams said the TV series will ``explore Latin America past and
present, focusing on themes, institutions, beliefs and symbols that
have endured or changed.'' He said the programs will ``seek to
capture the many ways in which Latin Americans have seen themselves
in the past and see themselves today.''
   The executive producer of the series will be Michael Gill, whose
previous TV and film credits include Sir Kenneth Clark's
``Civilization,'' ``The Treasure Houses of Britain'' and ``Alistair
Cooke's America.''
   The bulk of the $5 million cost of the documentaries will be
financed by a group of private investors led by Spanish publisher
Jesus de Planco. Adams said the Smithsonian will contribute an
estimated $2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
