<FIRST>r i AM-AfghanGuerrillas     01-30 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan Guerrillas,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Says Guerrillas Will Not Storm Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Najib, one name, cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan insurgent leader was quoted
Monday as saying guerrillas besieging Kabul, Kandahar, and Jalalabad
will ``refrain from storming these cities to save the lives of
innocent people.''
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, leader of the Jamiat-i-Islami insurgent
group based in Pakistan, also was quoted by the Kuwait newspaper
Al-Anbaa as saying the Soviets ``have no alternative but to quit
Afghanistan.''
   Soviet troops have helped Afghanistan's Marxist government fight
Moslem guerrillas for nine years, but are withdrawing from the
country Feb. 15 under a U.N.-mediated agreement.
   Mohammad Karim Khalili, spokesman for a coalition of eight
insurgent groups based in Iran, said any one-sided or unrealistic
plans for Afghanistan's future ``are doomed to failure.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted him as saying
any agreement should include both the coalition in Iran and the
alliance of seven factions based in Pakistan, ``as well as other
independent groups, or else it is sure to fall through.''
   None of the guerrillas were parties to the withdrawal agreement,
signed April 14, 1988, in Geneva. They have rejected offers of a
compromise political solution and predict the government of
President Najib will fall soon after the Red Army is gone.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said Khalili spoke at a news
conference Sunday at Isfahan, Iran.
   Leaders of the two guerrilla alliances now are organizing a
council of several hundred members to choose a government to take
over from the Najib regime. Khalili and Rabbani, whose group belongs
to the coalition in Pakistan, said the council would be named Feb.
10.
</TEXT>
