<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1838EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Steinberg 1stLd-Writethru a0601 01-30 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0601,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deliberations Continue in Steinberg Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs with jury request for definition of reasonable
doubt; picks up 3rd graf, `The testimony...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors considering whether Joel Steinberg killed
his illegally adopted 6-year-old daughter deliberated for an eighth
day Monday, rehearing testimony on his comments about the girl's
fatal injuries.
   The panel in state Supreme Court in Manhattan also sent a note
asking for a definition of reasonable doubt. The judge replied that
reasonable doubt is ``not just guess or surmise'' but a doubt based
on logic and reached after a conscientious review of evidence.
   Earlier, the jury reheard testimony from nine witnesses,
including Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's battered former live-in
companion.
   The testimony, also from police, paramedics and hospital workers,
focused on Steinberg's comments after Lisa was found comatose in his
Manhattan apartment on Nov. 2, 1987. She died three days later.
   Ms. Nussbaum testified that Steinberg told her he hit Lisa. He
could be convicted even if the jury found he did not hit her but
showed ``depraved indifference'' to her life by leaving her
unconscious on the floor overnight.
   Steinberg's lawyers contended during the trial that it was Ms.
Nussbaum who hit the girl, and that Steinberg, 47, did not summon an
ambulance because he did not realize she was injured.
   If it rejects the murder charge, the jury could convict Steinberg
of first-degree manslaughter, meaning he meant to hurt Lisa but not
to kill her; second-degree manslaughter, meaning he did not mean to
hurt her but showed reckless disregard for her life; or criminally
negligent homicide.
   There was speculation over the weekend, when the jury sought
clarification of terms that are elements of manslaughter, that the
panel had determined Steinberg was innocent of the murder charge.
State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax had told jurors not to
consider manslaughter unless they unanimously acquitted Steinberg of
second-degree murder.
</TEXT>
