<FIRST>r a AM-Contras     01-30 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contras,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contras Say Bush Supports Them, Deny CIA Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders insisted Monday that the Bush
administration supports them, and strenuously denied the existence
of a CIA probe into their possible misuse of secret political funds.
   Contra director Adolfo Calero said the Nicaraguan rebels have not
had official contact with the president or his aides since the
inauguration. But he said he talked informally to Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower and Republican Party Chairman Lee
Atwater, and had received assurances that Bush would continue the
Reagan administration's support of the Contras.
   Bush has yet to appoint an assistant secretary of state for Latin
American affairs, and has made no initiatives or policy changes on
aid to the Contras since taking office 11 days ago.
   ``The message ... is that the resistance would not be abandoned,
that the resistance is a reality and is part of any policy that the
United States would develop,'' Calero said.
   He angrily denied a Los Angeles Times story that quoted
unidentified government and Contra sources as saying the CIA has
begun an audit into the possible personal use of money it gave the
anti-Sandinista rebels for political work outside the United States.
The story identified Calero as a main target of the audit.
   ``It is false, it is defamatory and I am going to proceered.''
</TEXT>
