<DOCNO> AP890130-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-S&amp;LCrisis 2ndLd-Writethru a0670 01-30 0816</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-S&amp;L Crisis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0670,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Address S&amp;L Crisis in Feb. 9 Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Brady meeting members of Congress, inserting new
grafs 3-8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush hopes to spell out plans for
dealing with the savings and loan crisis in his Feb. 9 address to
Congress but might not be ready with details by then, his spokesman
said Monday.
   ``He'll address it in his speech. I'm not willing to say how
specific his speech will be,'' said press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   Meanwhile, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady met privately Monday
with House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and other key Democrats
concerning the S&amp;L situation.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, said Brady described alternatives being considered
for coming up with the money _ experts say it may require as much as
$100 billion _ to close insolvent savings institutions while
protecting depositors against losses.
   ``Everybody's looking for the path of least resistence,''
Rostenkowski said, adding that Brady told the group meeting in
Wright's office that Bush has not made up his mind,
   But Rostenkowski said the plan that Brady floated as one option
last week on Capitol Hill _ to levy an insurance fee on depositors _
``is as flat as a pancake.''
   One alternative could be to raise the premiums that banks and
savings and loan associations now pay for federal insurance.
   ``The healthy institutions won't be for increased premiums,''
Rostenkowski said. ``There's no solution that's not going to be
painful.''
   Fitzwater also said Bush would continue to seek advice from
members of Congress despite complaints by Chief of Staff John Sununu
that lawmakers had leaked discussions of a fee on deposits.
   ``Consultations are a very important part of the process,''
Fitzwater said. ``President Bush has been reaching out to Congress
in many forms. We would expect that to continue.''
   Sununu suggested on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley'' on
Sunday that certain members of Congress may have violated the
administration's trust in leaking word that the depositor fee was
being considered.
   That enabled critics of the plan to seize the iniative and ``put
the worst foot forward'' late last week, Sununu said.
   Fitzwater said that Bush was ``very concerned about leaks'' but
didn't have any particular problems in this instance.
   In fact, Sununu himself discussed the proposed fee as an option
at a White House briefing last Wednesday.
   ``It just happened. It was one of the options and so the governor
discussed it because you asked him. I don't blame anybody. It just
happens,'' Fitzwater said.
   Disclosure that the fee was under consideration caused a
firestorm of protest, both on Capitol Hill and in the banking and
savings and loan industry.
   On Monday, Democrats chided Sununu for saying over the weekend
that the fee plan remains a live option.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a member of the House Banking
Committee, said he was ``utterly amazed'' that the administration
was standing by the proposal. Senate Banking Committee member Jim
Sasser, D-Tenn., said the idea ``won't fly,'' but said he was glad
the Bush administration was addressing the nation's savings and loan
problem.
   ``Ronald Reagan, I never heard him utter one word on the crisis
in the savings and loan industry,'' Sasser said.
   Republicans displayed sympathy toward Sununu. Rep. Jim Leach,
R-Iowa, a banking committee member, said that by defending the plan,
Sununu was merely performing his function of presenting the
president with all the options.
   ``There's a big difference between having one's feet in concrete
on a proposal, and assessing the ... options,'' Leach said.
   Another GOP banking panel member, Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida,
also said he expected the plan to not be implemented, but added that
it would be helpful to study all proposals.
   ``The choices are very narrow,'' he said. ``My view is let's look
it over. There might be some constructive way of dealing with it.''
   The plan would call for a fee of about $2.50 for each $1,000 on
deposit in a federally insured institution. The proceeds would go
toward the $100 billion that federal regulators say could be needed
to deal with the nation's insolvent savings and loans.
   Fitzwater said such a fee _ which some critics say would violate
Bush's no-new-taxes pledge _ remains an option under consideration
by the administration.
   However, he added that other options were also being ``worked on
and developed'' and that no specific plan had yet come to the White
House for Bush's review.
   He said the president has been meeting with Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady daily.
   Fitzwater said Bush would talk about the savings and loan
situation in his budget address to a special House-Senate session on
Feb. 9.
   However, because of the complexity of the problem, the complete
administration proposal for dealing with the situation may not be
ready by then, Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
