<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Economy     01-30 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Statistician Says Perestroika Improving Economic Performance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite empty shelves, long lines and grumbling
consumers, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's drive for efficiency is
improving the performance of the Soviet economy, the top government
statistician said Monday.
   Mikhail Korolev, chairman of the State Committee for Statistics,
wrote in Pravda that the gross national product is growing and
production of many food items is increasing.
   He said this is proof that Gorbachev's campaign for
``perestroika,'' or restructuring, is having a positive impact on
the Soviet economy.
   But he said the effectiveness of perestroika is difficult to spot
in the shops because the Soviet consumer's demand for goods and
services has grown even faster than production.
   ``Despite the increase in the output of consumer goods, the
sharply increased demand has not been met to the full,'' Korolev
wrote in the Communist Party daily.
   He said the Soviet gross national product grew 5 percent last
year and was 13.3 percent higher than in 1985. The national income,
a Soviet measurement of economic performance that excludes some
services measured under GNP, increased in 1988 by 4.4 percent over
the 1987 figure, Korolev wrote.
   The government announced this month that Soviet GNP in 1988
totaled 866 billion rubles, or $1.4 trillion. That was less than
half of the 1985 U.S. GNP of $3.8 trillion.
   To show that perestroika has been successful, Korolev compared
the average yearly grain harvest during the ``perestroika'' years of
1986-88, taken as a whole, with the average in 1981-85.
   He said the current annual average was up 14 percent over the
pre-perestroika period.
   Last week, however, a Soviet official estimated the 1988 grain
harvest at 195 million tons, down from 210 million tons in 1986 and
1987.
   Korolev also said average annual meat production in 1986-88 was
16 percent higher than in 1981-85. He said the yearly average
production of eggs for the same periods had increased by 11 percent
and milk by 10 percent.
   The official also cited significant increases over the last three
years in the production of keenly sought consumer goods such as
televisions, radios, tape players, sewing machines, washing
machines, motorcycles and bicycles.
   He also said Soviets are now earning more.
   ``The monetary incomes of the population grew by 8.5 percent in
1988 alone and by 16.7 percent over the three years of the current
five-year plan period as a whole,'' Korolev wrote.
   He did not give figures for current average incomes or say
whether the increases were adjusted to take inflation into account.
In 1988, government figures said the average Soviet factory worker
was earning about 200 rubles a month, or about $333 at the official
exchange rate.
   Korolev also said Soviets were now working more productively.
   ``It is important that the economy has begun to turn toward an
intensive way of development,'' he wrote. ``Higher labor
productivity has been achieved in all key branches of the economy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
