<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-IndianInvestigation 1stld-Writethru a068e</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Investigation, 1st ld-Writethru, a0689,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead and edits throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is rampant corruption in the Bureau of
Indian Affairs and among many tribal leaders, an Indian activist
told Congress on Monday.
   ``Within the past two years, I have personally attempted to
assist seven Indian reservations located in the Southwest, Northwest
and Northern Plains with economic development,'' said Russell Means,
head of the American Indian Movement.
   ``The investors I represented were from various groups interested
in establishing banks, resorts, Indian-owned public relations firms,
factories, fishing ports and international trade.
   ``I know that the tribal governments do not want economic
development unless graft is a major ingredient,'' said Means.
   Means did not volunteer the names of the seven tribes, nor was he
asked. Means group has pushed hard for Indian rights and has long
been critical of the BIA.
   Means said both the poorest and the richest reservations suffer
from ``mismanagement, a bloated patronage system and no checks and
balances.''
   He said many tribal officials are honest men and women, but ``a
vast majority of the tribal officials parasite on the incestuous
world of tribal politics. ... It's embarrassing.''
   He also contended that there is widespread sexual abuse of
children on Indian reservations, but said, ``And all you hear are
whispers.''
   In his testimony before a special investigative committee of the
Senate Select Committee on Indian Affairs, Means called for
abolishment of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and said management of
the tribes should be the sole responsibility of tribal elders as
traditional customs dictate.
   Means was among five Indian leaders to appear before the
committee on its first day of hearings into a wide range of
allegations of corruption on Indian reservations. The subcommittee
will hear later form the BIA.
   Though he was the only one to advocate abolishment of the BIA,
the agency came under heavy fire from the others.
   Wilma Mankiller, chief of the Cherokee Nation of Oklahoma, said
it was an anachronism which has barely changed since its inception,
despite changes among the tribes.
   ``The BIA structure does not support Indian efforts. Funds are
eaten up by the bureaucracy.'' she said. ``It should be radically
streamlined.''
   Twila Martin-Kekahbah, chief of the Turtle Mountain Band of
Chippewa Indians in North Dakota, said tribes throughout the country
are at various levels of development and the BIA, as it now
operates, is not creative enough to help them all.
   The hearings, expected to last several weeks, were prompted by a
series in The Arizona Republic newspaper detailing fraud in
contracting, gaming, law enforcement on reservations and among
tribal leadership.
   The committee also will examine charges of child sex abuse in
Indian schools and poor-quality education on reservations.
   The committee staff conducted more than 1,000 interviews by
telephone and in person and received briefings and documents from
every federal agency that administers Indian programs.
   The committee also examined more than 900,000 pages of documents
and conducted dozens of depositions.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., who chairs the special
investigative committee, said he did not know if the hearings would
result in restructuring of the BIA.
   ``It's too early to tell,'' he said. ``But we will be making
recommendations.''
   A congressional aide who spoke on condition of anonymity said the
material gathered by the committee would be turned over to the
Justice Department and could be use to seek indictments.
   DeConcini said he was most troubled by reports of child sexual
abuse among Indians and the use of Indians as fronts by companies
trying to qualify as minority contractors.
   He said the panel is still pursuing allegations in the newspaper
series that billions of dollars in oil royalties were illegally
diverted.
   But DeConcini said the dollar amount of the possible diversion
appears overstated.
   Later, Leonard Garment, a Washington attorney who served as a
consultant on Indian affairs to President Nixon from 1969 to 1974,
advocated establishment of an Indian Trust Counsel Authority as a
means of assuring adequate legal representation for Indians.
   ``In some matters on which the United States government must go
to court, the position adopted by the Department of Justice does not
take account of the interests and claims of American Indians .... A
trust counsel authority would insure that, in situations of
conflict, the Indians would receive separate U.S. government
representation in the courts,'' he told the panel.
   The establishment of such a position was unsuccessfully advocated
by Nixon while he was in office, and in a letter to the committee,
dated Jan. 26, 1989, the former president expressed hope Congress
will reconsider the idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
