<FIRST>u a AM-Steinberg-Chronology     01-30 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg-Chronology,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Chronology of the Lisa Steinberg Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 2 _ Six-year-old Lisa Steinberg removed unconscious from
apartment of the couple who illegally adopted her, Joel Steinberg
and his companion, Hedda Nussbaum. Police find a boy, 16-month-old
Mitchell, tied to a playpen and remove him to foster care. They also
find heroin, cocaine, marijuana, scales, crack pipes, a revolver and
ammunition. Steinberg and Ms. Nussbaum are arrested.
   Nov. 3 _ Steinberg pleads innocent to charges of attempted
murder, assault, and endangering welfare of the children.
   Nov. 5 _ Lisa dies when she is removed from respirator. Doctors
say death result of brain hemorrhage caused by head injury. Ms.
Nussbaum arraigned on charges in hospital where she is being treated
for broken bones, burns, and gangrenous leg.
   Nov. 6 _ Steinberg indicted by grand jury and charged with
second-degree murder and manslaughter. He pleads innocent.
   Dec. 1 _ Permanent custody of Travis Smigiel, formerly Mitchell
Steinberg, granted to his biological mother, Nicole Smigiel.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   March 21 _ Grand jury adds drug and weapons charges and child
abuse felony charge to indictment against Steinberg.
   Oct. 25 _ Trial begins before State Supreme Court Justice Harold
Rothwax.
   Oct. 26 _ Murder charges dropped against Ms. Nussbaum after
prosecutors say she was ``so physically and mentally incapacitated
on the night of the murder that she was not criminally responsible
for Lisa's death.''
   Dec. 1-13 _ Ms. Nussbaum testifies for prosecution, directly
implicating Steinberg in Lisa's death. Her testimony of life with
Steinberg describes 11-year relationship that deteriorated with
beatings, brainwashing, food deprivation, bizarre punishments and
drug use. Defense hints toward insanity defense during
cross-examination by stressing Steinberg's odd behavior.
   Dec. 20 _ Defense opens its case, attacking testimony and
credibility of Ms. Nussbaum.
   Dec. 21 _ Dr. Peter Sarosi pleads guilty to ``unlawfully placing
out a child for adoption'' for giving the boy to Steinberg and Ms.
Nussbaum. He is sentenced to 100 hours of community service, fined
$1,000 and put on probation for three years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 13 _ Defense rests without Steinberg taking stand. Trial 12
weeks long, heard 52 witnesses.
   Jan. 19-20 _ Closing arguments. Defense argues Ms. Nussbaum
fatally beat Lisa in jealous rage. Prosecution says Ms. Nussbaum was
too physically and emotionally disabled to have harmed Lisa and that
Steinberg, drugged with cocaine and vexed with child's
rebelliousness, fatally beat her.
   Jan. 23 _ Judge charges jury, instructing that they must
unanimously acquit Steinberg of top homicide count, second-degree
murder, before moving to first-degree manslaughter, second-degree
manslaughter, and criminally negligent homicide. Also instructs that
Nussbaum was accomplice and her testimony must be supported by other
testimony or evidence. Jury begins deliberations.
   Jan. 30 _ A state jury convicts Steinberg of manslaughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
