<FIRST>r w AM-AntarcticRescue     01-30 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antarctic Rescue,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tourists Rescued From Ship Grounded In Antarctica, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists and crew members were rescued Sunday
after an Argentine tour ship ran aground off the Antarctic Peninsula
some two miles from a U.S. research station in Antarctica, the
National Science Foundation announced late Monday.
   The NSF statement said 81 tourists, including 46 Americans, were
flown from Antarctica bases Sunday to Chile and then on to Buenos
Aires in Argentina.
   Officials identified the ship as the Bahia Paraiso, a 400-foot,
double-hulled vessel that doubles as a supply and tour ship. It ran
aground Saturday two miles from the U.S. research outpost, Palmer
Station, just after it had made a stop there. The site is about 600
miles south of Cape Horn, the tip of South America.
   The NSF announcement said there were only a few minor injuries to
crew members and none to the passengers.
   ``Most of 316 passengers and crew were flown to South America on
Sunday, after spending Saturday night aboard cruise ships which
transported them to an Antarctic airfield at a Chilean base,'' the
announcement said.
   About 104 Bahia Paraiso crew members remained at Palmer Station
on Monday, the statement said, to assist in efforts to salvage the
ship.
   The ship was said to be leaking diesel fuel which is killing some
krill, a shrimp-like crustacean that lives in the Antarctic waters.
The fuel also is affecting sea birds, the announcement said.
   In addition to the tourists, the ship carried jet fuel, gasoline
and other supplies bound for the Argentine Esperanza station near
the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula.
   The statement said the passengers and crew were rescued by
motorized lifeboats from nearby cruise ships and from Palmer
Station. From there, the passengers and some of the crew were taken
by two other cruise ships to the Chilean base Teniente Marsh on King
George Island. From there, they were flown by Chilean military
aircraft to Punta Arenas, Chile, on Sunday, and then on to Buenos
Aires by Argentine military aircraft, the announcement said.
   Many of the crew members are using makeshift housing at Palmer
Station, a NSF-supported research center designed to accommodate
only 40. Temperatures, in the region's, were said to be 30 to 40
degrees Fahrenheit. Because of the large numbers of people at the
U.S. station, officials said food was being rationed.
   An Argentine naval ship is expected to arrive at the stranded
ship by Friday to rescue the rest of the tour ship crew and to pump
the fuel oil from the vessel, the NSF announcement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
