<FIRST>r a AM-RiversidePastor     01-30 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riverside Pastor,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Preacher Tapped To Lead Riverside Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. James Alexander Forbes Jr., a black
clergyman known for his preaching skill, has been named to lead
famed Riverside Church and its vigorous social-justice ministry.
   The interdenominational church announced the choice Monday after
a year-long search for a successor to the Rev. William Sloane
Coffin, a civil rights and anti-war activist.
   The 2,200-member church, built by the late John D. Rockefeller in
1930, has had a line of noted pastors, beginning with the late Harry
Emerson Fosdick.
   Forbes, 53, professor of preaching at New York's Union
Theological Seminary where he has taught for 12 years, was described
as being a theologian of eloquence and keen social concern.
   ``He is an eminent preacher, committed to pluralism, inclusivity
and social justice,'' the ``key characteristics for our senior
minister,'' said the head of the search committee, J. Richard Butler.
   He told the congregation Sunday that the committee had concluded
that Forbes was the man ``to lead this congregation through the next
decade and into the 21st century.''
   The selection, already approved by the church's board of deacons,
remains subject to affirmation by members, but that is expected to
be a formality next Sunday when they vote to discharge the search
committee.
   The church, with a $6 million annual budget, has become an
increasingly ethnically mixed congregation, with a diversified
program of help to the poor and homeless and working for racial
justice and disarmament.
   Although jointly affiliated with the American Baptist Churches
and the United Church of Christ, the congregation is a composite of
denominational backgrounds.
   Coffin stepped down a year ago, after a decade of leading the
church, to become president of a disarmament group, Sane-Freeze,
based in Washington, D.C.
   For the last year, an acting senior minister, the Rev. George
Hill, drawn out of retirement in Claremont, Calif., had filled the
pulpit until a successor to Coffin was chosen.
   Forbes, prior to joining the seminary faculty, had led an
innovative pastoral training program in Washington, and previously
led congregations in Richmond, Va., and Roxboro, N.C.
   In Washington, he had been director of Interfaith Metropolitan
Theological Education Inc., a seminary-without-walls for ministry in
Protestant, Catholic and Jewish traditions.
   Last year he joined in protests in Washington and New York
against South African apartheid and was among several seminary
professors arrested.
   Born in Burgow, N.C., Forbes holds theological degrees from
Colgate-Rochester Divinity School in Rochester, N.Y., and New York's
Union Seminary and had clinical pastoral training at the Medical
College of Virginia.
   He was ordained both in the American Baptist Churches and the
Original United Holy Church, International, a black Pentecostalist
body.
   Forbes says religion has a key role to play in national life.
   ``No government can function without a living vision of what it
means to be human'' and religion should keep that vision alive, he
said in a recent interview with The Washington Post.
   He said religion should provide a ``prophetic critique'' of
government and also provide ``guidelines and principles by which we
assess the kind of character that leaders ought to have.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0697 01-30 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Announces Severe Austerity Measures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS final graf `Attempts to...' with 3 grafs to add La Prensa
report on sugar mill deal. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega on Monday
announced a severe austerity plan for 1989 that nearly cuts the
federal budget in half, restricts credit and slashes capital
investment in a bid to curb hyperinflation and increase productivity.
   ``I appeal to the sensibility and honesty of all Nicaraguans so
this proposal doesn't turn into a political confrontation,'' Ortega
said at the end of a two-hour, 40-minute speech before the National
Assembly.
   ``Otherwise, we'll be paying with the blood and the future of our
people.''
   Ortega said that if inflation, which reached 20,000 percent last
year, is not brought under control and production not increased, the
government might implement a ``war economy'' policy.
   He did not elaborate.
   Ortega said the budget will be cut by 461 billion cordobas, or
about 44 percent, including deep cuts in capital investment and
government credits to the agricultural and business sector.
   Consequently, state-run banks will provide new loans ``only to
those who can pay,'' Ortega said. He acknowledged that tighter
credit could prompt dissent from business leaders, but he said the
government has ``been stimulating private producers, regardless of
their political positions.''
   The president did not say how many government workers would be
laid off because of the budget cuts. But in a telephone interview
with the newspaper El Nacional in Caracas, Venezuela, Ortega said
35,000 public employees would be laid off, of which 23,000 beloing
to the Sandinista army and the Interior Ministry and 12,000 to other
public institutions.
   Those laid off will be given monetary help for two months and
offered agricultural work, he said. About 10,000 workers are needed
for the coffee harvest, he noted.
   Ortega said the government plans cuts in subsidies for basic
goods, but did not provide details. He said urban areas would be hit
hardest by the cuts and suggested Nicaraguan laborers consider
moving to rural areas to find employment.
   Ortega also announced that the official and parallel rates of
currency exchange will be merged into one rate per dollar in an
effort to eliminate black market demand for dollars. He did not say
what the rate would be.
   Currently, the official rate, 2,300 cordobas per dollar, is used
to calculate payment for exports, and the parallel rate, at 4,400
cordobas, is used for those selling dollars. The dollar now fetches
about 5,500 cordobas on the black market.
   The president blamed Nicaragua's runaway inflation on the war
with the U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras. He said
the government had to finance its military operations while the
United States pressured multilateral lending institutions to cut off
financing to Nicaragua.
   The United States imposed a trade embargo against Nicaragua in
1985.
   Ortega told Nicaraguans to expect continued hard times and called
for the cooperation of workers and private business. He assured
landholders that government confiscations of property were a thing
of the past.
   ``The (confiscated) land already distributed to the peasants will
not be returned,'' Ortega said. ``On the other hand, there's no
(longer) reason to take away an inch of land from anybody,'' he said.
   About 85 percent of farmland in Nicaragua is in private hands,
and only 15 percent is owned by the state, he said.
   Also Monday, the official Sandinista newspaper Barricada reported
that the government and a private sugar company reached a tentative
agreement to solve a dispute over the confiscation of the company's
sugar mill last July.
   In its lead article, Barricada cited unidentified government
sources in reporting that the deal with Nicaragua Sugar and the
State Sugar Corp. was worked out over the weekend and included
``realistic compensation'' to the firm.
   The general manager of Nicaragua Sugar, Carlos Pellas, confirmed
that a tentative agreement was reached with the government, the
opposition newspaper La Prensa reported Monday.
   La Prensa reported that Pellas declined to reveal details of the
agreement. He did say that returning the sugar mill to its owners
``was not a viable option'' and that longtime workers would not be
fired, the report said
   Repeated attempts by The Associated Press to reach officials of
Nicaragua Sugar by telephone were not successful.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
