<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru a0705 01-30 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Chief Says `Popular Uprising' Not Final Word On 1956</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to CORRECT spelling of Imre Nagy, sted Jagy.
Pickup 3rd graf `Imre Pozsgay...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz said
Monday the leadership has not yet decided that the revolt of 1956
was a popular uprising, despite a Politburo member's weekend
declaration.
   Soviet troops put down the revolt. Its leaders, including Imre
Nagy, premier of the short-lived government, were executed in 1958.
   Imre Pozsgay, a Politburo member and leading reformer, said in a
startling announcement after a weekend meeting of a party committee
that the events were a popular uprising and not, as officially
termed, ``counterrevolution.''
   Pozsgay said his comments reflected the work of the committee,
which he heads. It is reviewing the past 40 years.
   The official news agency MTI quoted Grosz as saying Monday: ``I
do not know what motive led Mr. Pozsgay to formulate this single
element of the four decades of analysis.''
   When chosen to head the committee last year, Pozsgay said it
should review 40 years, thus indicating he favored a review of the
1956 events. Grosz appeared to want a shorter period covered.
   Grosz, returning from a trip to Switzerland, said Monday a
re-evaluation of the political consequences of 1956 was the job of
the party Central Committee, not of one person or a temporary
committee.
   ``This debate is still to be held,'' he said. ``I believe that
perhaps Mr. Pozsgay and the committee have documents on which they
base this statement. I have not come across such documents so far.''
   He said he did not exclude ``in principle'' the formulation of
``a new political qualification'' about 1956, MTI reported.
   Premier Miklos Nemeth noted in an address Monday to the Chamber
of Commerce that Pozsgay's committee had made ``a partial study.''
   ``If there is something that we have to learn from the past it is
that if we use one-word terms to qualify the always extremely
complex occurrences or processes of history, it is a grave error
which can lead to more serious ones,'' MTI quoted him as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
