<FIRST>u a AM-Steinberg-Reax     01-30 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg-Reax,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child Advocate Says Concern Over Child Abuse Won't Last</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Steinberg</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg's manslaughter conviction Monday
in the death of his illegally adopted daughter won't have any
positive, lasting effect in preventing such cases, a leading
advocate against child abuse said Monday.
   ``Now that Lisa's case is over with, it will all be business as
usual,'' said Dr. Vincent Fontana. ``Children will continue to die
at the rate of two or three a week (in New York City) and in another
10 years we'll have another milestone case.''
   Steinberg was convicted of first-degree manslaughter in the death
of 6-year-old Lisa. Fontana, chairman of the Mayor's Task Force on
Child Abuse for more than 20 years, said he should have been
convicted of the more serious charge of second-degree murder.
   ``It's a sad day for the kids who are being abused in this
country,'' said Fontana after learning of the verdict. ``I just feel
sorry for the kids, because all those people who are batterers and
child murderers will feel this is a signal, that because the legal
system is such, you might get away with it.
   ``The child protective system failed her, the schools system
failed her and now the judicial system has failed her,'' he added,
referring to Lisa.
   Fontana said he thought Steinberg's longtime live-in companion,
Hedda Nussbaum, also should have been prosecuted for Lisa's death.
Charges against Ms. Nussbaum were dropped because the prosecution
concluded that she was too emotionally and physically battered
herself, allegedly by Steinberg, to have harmed or helped Lisa.
   ``I believe if there are two parents involved, they're both
guilty _ one is the passive abuser and one is the active abuser,''
he said.
   Dr. Samuel Klagsbrun, Ms. Nussbaum's psychiatrist at Four Winds
Hospital in Katonah, N.Y., said Ms. Nussbaum was a victim, not a
criminal.
   ``There is a double human tragedy in this story. One is the death
of a child and other is an almost longtime death of a woman,''
Klagsbrun said.
   A week before the verdict was issued, Klagsbrun had said Nussbaum
would interpret ``any verdict except murder as `they didn't believe
me.' ''
   Ms. Nussbaum testified that she was severely beaten by Steinberg
and said that he told her he hit Lisa. Prosecutors said she was not
responsible for Lisa's death, but defense lawyers alleged that she
had attacked Lisa in a jealous rage over Steinberg's attention for
the child.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch, who once said that boiling child abusers in
oil was not punishment enough, said of the verdict Monday: ``This
jury has done a remarkable job in sorting out the evidence. They
took a long time but they took whatever time was necessary to do a
good job, to evaluate the evidence against the charges. Hats off to
this jury.''
</TEXT>
