<FIRST>u a AM-Steinberg-Jurors     01-30 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg-Jurors,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Foreman: From Outset, Some Jurors Strongly Opposed Murder Conviction</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Steinberg</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the jurors who convicted Joel Steinberg
of manslaughter Monday made it clear from the start of deliberations
they would never convict him of murder, the panel's foreman said.
   Steinberg faces from 8 1-3 to 25 years in prison on the
first-degree manslaughter charge, but was found innocent of
second-degree murder, a charge that carries a maximum of 25 years to
life.
   Jury foreman Jeremiah Cole said some of the jurors ``made it
clear at the outset that they would never vote for the second-degree
murder count.''
   At a news conference after the verdict was announced, Cole said
the jurors often found themselves in heated argument during the
eight days of deliberations.
   The jurors had become so angry at one another that by the time
they settled on the manslaughter conviction minutes before the
verdict was announced, they asked the court for a few minutes to
``kiss and make up,'' Cole said.
   The deliberations, he said, took such a toll on him that ``it's
impossible for me to remember when anything happened (during
deliberations).''
   ``The past week is a blur for me,'' he said.
   He said he was among the jurors who did not want to convict
Steinberg of murder.
   But he said the three-month trial had given him ``a clear picture
of what happened in that apartment that night and I have that
picture beyond a reasonable doubt.''
   Six-year-old Lisa Steinberg, the disbarred lawyer's illegally
adopted daughter, was found comatose in his Manhattan apartment on
Nov. 2, 1987. She died three days later.
   Steinberg and Hedda Nussbaum, his longtime live-in companion,
were charged in the girl's death. Charges against Ms. Nussbaum were
dropped after prosecutors determined she was too physically and
mentally incapacitated to be responsible.
   She testified against Steinberg for seven days but Cole said, ``I
think it's safe to say we put Hedda's testimony aside.''
   Another juror, Helena Barthell, 36, said the jury had ``virtually
ignored'' Ms. Nussbaum's testimony. Mrs. Barthell said she wanted
Steinberg convicted of murder.
   ``Certainly a murder two verdict would have sent a stronger
message,'' she said.
   State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax instructed the six men
and six women of the jury that they must consider Ms. Nussbaum an
accomplice in Lisa's death. As such, her testimony had to be
supported by other evidence in order to secure a murder conviction.
   ``I felt sorry for her but to some extent as an adult, as a
woman, she accepted these conditions,'' Mrs. Barthell said.
   The juror said she understood the effects of mind-control and
brainwashing on a person but ``you always kind of hope that some
spark of instinct would prevail to protect a child.''
   Cole added, ``It was a key question whether Hedda deserved
blame.''
</TEXT>
