<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-SovietSubs     01-30 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Soviet Subs,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Says Soviet Subs Keep Intruding, Says `May Be Action'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The navy commander charged Monday that
Soviet submarines from secret Baltic bases continue to violate
Swedish waters, national television reported.
   ``We are approaching situations where there may be action,'' Vice
Admiral Bengt Schuback said in a television interview.
   He said experience from several sub-hunt incidents had improved
the navy's chances of catching intruders and that a trapped
submarine may try to shoot its way out.
   ``We are prepared for the risk,'' Schuback said.
   Sweden has not officially accused any nation of violations since
1983, when the government protested Soviet sub incursions to Moscow.
Two years earlier a Soviet submarine ran aground outside a naval
base in southern Sweden.
   The TV said a report about foreign underwater intrusions in 1988,
due to be presented in two weeks, showed that violations continued
at about the same rate as earlier this decade.
   A week ago, the navy said it had ``indications'' that a submarine
had penetrated waters outside Stockholm.
   Schuback said there was no firm evidence, but that ``the vessels
must come from Soviet areas of the Baltic.''
   ``These underwater vessels come from secret bases. ... There is
no possibility that western countries have such hidden
bases,''Schuback said.
   The Swedish defense gradually has reinforced its submarine
defense since the incident in 1981. But stepped-up efforts to catch
intruders, including the use of depth charges and mines, so far have
failed to produce results.
   The military has said new weapons, experience and adjustment of
rules to allow for quicker decision-making is bringing them closer
to catching intruders.
</TEXT>
