<HEAD>Gunmen Kill 12 in Peru</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with guerrillas killing seven in
southern town. Pick up 8th pvs, `Farfan was...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of suspected leftist guerrillas
rounded up residents of a southern Andean town and gunned down seven
people, including three officials, police said Monday. Five people
were reported killed elsewhere.
   An estimated 300 guerrillas believed to belong to the Maoist
movement Shining Path rounded up the residents of San Jose de
Azangaro in the department of Puno on Sunday and killed a police
chief, a mayor, a city councilman and four other people, police said.
   Before leaving, the guerrillas set fire to public buildings and
looted shops in the town 600 miles south of Lima, the nation's
capital, the police said. The names of the victims were not
available.
   In Ayacucho, 200 miles southeast of Lima, six masked men broke
into a home on Monday and fatally shot a couple and two of their
children, said police, who said they had no clues to the motive in
the highland city or the identity of the attackers.
   Police said the attackers killed the father, son and daughter as
they slept in upstairs bedrooms and then shot to death the mother in
the kitchen, where she was making breakfast.
   The killers dragged away a 9-year-old boy who was not related to
family but was in the home at the time, witnesses said.
   The father taught at a high school and the mother worked at an
elementary school. The children went to the state university in
Ayacucho.
   Police identified the victims as Juvenal Farfan, 56; his wife
Eldeliza Gonzales, 46; a son, Juvenal, 23; and a daughter, Julia,
18, police said.
   Farfan was not known to support any particular party. However,
his brother is an Ayacucho correspondent for a small leftist paper
in Lima.
   Ayacucho is the birthplace and stronghold of the Shining Path, a
Maoist political movement whose nine-year guerrilla war has taken
more than 12,000 lives.
   Since July, an anti-communist death squad called the Rodrigo
Franco Command also has emerged and threatened city journalists and
public figures viewed as leftists.
   Police blamed the Shining Path for the murder Sunday night of
19-year-old Alipio Velarde, who was shot to death by two masked men
who forced their way into a house in a shantytown outside Ayacucho.
   The gunmen said they were looking for his brother, Eugenio, mayor
of a small village 20 miles east and a member of the governing
center-left Aprista Party.
</TEXT>
