<HEAD>Man Accused In Nerve Gas Plot Ordered Released; Government May Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with bail order stayed; picks up
3rd graf: ``Nothing is more ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Monday temporarily stayed
his $2 million bail for a Korean-American businessman charged in an
alleged international conspiracy to illegally export nerve gas.
   U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin said the government failed to
offer convincing evidence that Juhwan Yun, 48, of Short Hills would
flee prosecution, but was persuaded to stay his order until noon
Tuesday, said one of Yun's attorneys, Jeremy Littman.
   The delay gives government prosecutors time to consider appealing
the release order to an appeals court.
   ``Nothing is more abhorrent to our free society than the spectre
of persons accused of crimes being confined in prisons before trial
and conviction,'' Sarokin wrote in an opinion ordering Yun's
release. ``The right to be free on bail before trial is what
distinguishes our Democracy from totalitarian governments.''
   Yun has pleaded innocent to charges of conspiring to violate the
Arms Export Control Act and attempting to ship 500 quarter-ton bombs
of sarin, a nerve gas. The destination may have been Iran, the
government said in court papers.
   Yun has been in custody since his arrest Jan. 12.
   Under the bail agreement, Yun forfeited his passport and those of
his wife and three children. He also must remain in his home and all
international telephone calls will be monitored by the U.S.
attorney's office.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Anne Singer, who is handling the case for
the government, declined to comment.
   U.S. Magistrate Ronald J. Hedges revoked bail for Yun on Jan. 20
after prosecutors said classified government documents written in
English and Korean were found on his desk at Komex International
Corp., his import-export business.
   Dratch has argued that his client is a victim of entrapment and
that the government overstepped its bounds during the investigation.
   In his opinion, Sarokin said tape recordings submitted as
evidence by the government ``appear to be incriminating,'' but that
he could not tell from the transcripts how strong the prosecutor's
case would be.
   He said that in a Jan. 4 conversation between Yun and
co-defendant Charles Caplan of London, ``both parties seem to be
abandoning the sarin transaction, because they appear to realize
that export from the United States may be prohibited.''
   Prosecutors contend that Yun was trying to obtain a bogus license
to export the bombs and other military equipment, including missiles
and radar tubes.
</TEXT>
