<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday, Feb. 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Shrove Tuesday, Feb. 7, the 38th day of 1989. There are
327 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Twenty-five years ago, on Feb. 7, 1964, the Beatles' ``invasion''
of the United States began as thousands of screaming fans welcomed
John Lennon, Paul McCartney, George Harrison and Ringo Starr at New
York's John F. Kennedy International Airport.
   On this date:
   In 1812, author Charles Dickens was born in Portsmouth, England.
   In 1827, the first ballet performed in the United States, ``The
Deserter,'' was presented at the Bowery Theater in New York.
   In 1885, author Sinclair Lewis was born in Sauk Center, Minn.
   In 1904, a fire began in Baltimore that raged for about 30 hours
and destroyed more than 1,500 buildings.
   In 1931, aviator Amelia Earhart married publisher George P.
Putnam in Noank, Conn.
   In 1936, President Franklin D. Roosevelt authorized a flag for
the office of the vice president.
   In 1944, during World War II, the Germans launched a
counteroffensive at Anzio, Italy.
   In 1948, General Dwight D. Eisenhower resigned as Army chief of
staff and was succeeded by General Omar Bradley.
   In 1971, women in Switzerland won the right to vote.
   In 1974, the island nation of Grenada won independence from
Britain.
   In 1983, President Ronald Reagan fired Environmental Protection
Agency official Rita M. Lavelle after she refused a request from EPA
administrator Anne M. Gorsuch that she resign.
   In 1983, Elizabeth H. Dole was sworn in as the first female
Secretary of Transportation by the first woman to sit on the U.S.
Supreme Court, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor.
   In 1986, Filipinos went to the polls in elections that would
result in a disputed victory for incumbent President Ferdinand
Marcos over challenger Corazon Aquino.
   In 1986, Haiti's President-for-Life, Jean-Claude Duvalier, fled
his country, ending 28 years of his family's rule.
   Ten years ago: The State Department said an accumulation of
reports from the Israeli-occupied territories made it appear that
some Arab security suspects had been mistreated by Israeli
authorities.
   Five years ago: President Ronald Reagan announced he had ordered
U.S. Marines in Lebanon to move to ships offshore. Space shuttle
astronauts Bruce McCandless II and Robert L. Stewart went on the
first untethered space walk. David, a 12-year-old boy born without
immunity to disease, touched his mother for the first time after he
was removed from a germ-free ``bubble'' at Texas Children's Hospital
in Houston.
   One year ago: Leslie Manigat was sworn in as Haiti's president
(however, he was removed from power the following June).
   Today's birthdays: Actor Eddie Bracken is 69. Author Gay Talese
is 57. Football player-turned-game show host Rolf Benirschke is 34.
   Thought for today: ``Human beings are the only creatures who are
able to behave irrationally in the name of reason.'' _ Ashley
Montagu, English anthropologist.
</TEXT>
