<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday, Feb. 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Feb. 9, the 40th day of 1989. There are 325
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, on Feb. 9, 1889, an act of Congress
elevated the Department of Agriculture to Cabinet-level status.
   On this date:
   In 1773, the ninth president of the United States, William Henry
Harrison, was born in Charles City County, Va.
   In 1825, the House of Representatives elected John Quincy Adams
president after no candidate received a majority of electoral votes.
   In 1870, the U.S. Weather Bureau was established.
   In 1933, the Oxford Union Society at Oxford University debated,
then approved by a vote of 275-to-153, a motion stating ``That this
House will in no circumstances fight for its King and Country.''
   In 1943, the World War II battle of Guadalcanal in the southwest
Pacific ended with a U.S. victory over Japanese forces, who were
forced to evacuate.
   In 1950, in a speech in Wheeling, W.V., Sen. Joseph McCarthy,
R-Wis., charged the State Department was riddled with Communists.
   In 1962, an agreement was signed to make Jamaica an independent
nation within the British Commonwealth later in the year.
   In an estimated 73 million viewers tuned in as the Beatles made
their first live American television appearance, on ``The Ed
Sullivan Show.''
   In 1971, the ``Apollo 14'' spacecraft returned to Earth after
man's third landing on the moon.
   In 1977, Queen Alia of Jordan _ the third wife of King Hussein,
and the first to be named queen _ was killed in the crash of a
military helicopter.
   In 1983, in a dramatic reversal from 50 years earlier, the Oxford
Union Society rejected by a vote of 416-to-187 a motion ``That this
House would not fight for Queen and Country.''
   In 1987, former National Security Adviser Robert C. McFarlane,
faced with tough questions about his role in the Iran-Contra affair,
survived a suicide attempt.
   Ten years ago: Chinese Vice Premier Deng Xiaoping returned home
from his United States tour, receiving a warm welcome from his
country's senior leaders.
   Five years ago: Soviet leader Yuri V. Andropov died at age 69,
less than 15 months after succeeding Leonid Brezhnev; he was
succeeded by Konstantin U. Chernenko.
   One year ago: A panel of historians who examined the conduct of
Austrian President Kurt Waldheim during World War II released its
report, saying that as a German officer, Waldheim had been aware of
Nazi atrocities. However, the panel left open the question of his
personal guilt.
   Today's birthdays: Former Secretary of State Dean Rusk is 80.
Actress Kathryn Grayson is 66. Television journalist Roger Mudd is
61. Singer Carole King is 47. Actress Mia Farrow is 44.
   Thought for today: ``You've either got to have a sense of humor,
or you've got to have an attitude and a scapegoat. It helps if you
have all three.'' -- Linda Ronstadt, American rock singer.
</TEXT>
