<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday, Feb. 10</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, Feb. 10, the 41st day of 1989. There are 324
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Forty years ago, on Feb. 10, 1949, the play ``Death of a
Salesman,'' Arthur Miller's tragedy about Willy Loman, an aging
salesman haunted by failure and false dreams, opened at Broadway's
Morosco Theater with Lee J. Cobb in the role of Loman and Mildred
Dunnock as his wife, Linda.
   On this date:
   In 1763, France ceded Canada to England in the Treaty of Paris,
which ended the French and Indian War.
   In 1840, Britain's Queen Victoria married Prince Albert of
Saxe-Coburg-Gotha.
   In 1846, members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day
Saints, the Mormons, began an exodus to the west from Illinois.
   In 1863, showman P.T. Barnum staged the wedding of General Tom
Thumb and Mercy Lavinia Warren _ both of them midgets _ in New York
City.
   In 1933, the first singing telegram was introduced by the Postal
Telegram Company in New York.
   In 1942, the former French liner ``Normandie'' capsized in New
York Harbor a day after it caught fire while being refitted for the
U.S. Navy.
   In 1947, peace treaties between the Allies and five of the Axis
powers were signed in Paris.
   In 1962, the Soviet Union exchanged captured American U-2 pilot
Francis Gary Powers for Rudolph Ivanovich Abel, a Soviet spy held by
the United States.
   In 1967, the 25th Amendment to the Constitution, dealing with
presidential disability and succession, went into effect.
   In 1981, eight people died when a smoky fire raced through the
upper floors of the Las Vegas Hilton Hotel.
   In 1987, Surgeon General C. Everett Koop told a House panel he
favored advertising condoms on network television because of the
national health threat posed by the incurable disease ``AIDS.''
   Ten years ago: Violence erupted in Tehran as rival factions of
Iran's armed forces clashed and thousands of civilians roamed the
streets, demonstrating for the overthrow of the government of Prime
Minister Shapour Bakhtiar.
   Five years ago: American civilians and other foreigners began
evacuating Beirut because of what were described as ``unsettled
conditions'' in Lebanon.
   One year ago: A federal appeals court in San Francisco struck
down the Army's ban on homosexuals, saying homosexuals were entitled
to the same protection against discrimination as racial minorities.
(However, the court agreed last June to reconsider its ruling.)
   Today's birthdays: Opera singer Leontyne Price is 62. Actor
Robert Wagner is 59. Singer Roberta Flack is 49. Singer-songwriter
Peter Allen is 45.
   Thought for today: ``I don't say he's a great man. Willy Loman
never made a lot of money. His name was never in the paper. He's not
the finest character that ever lived. But he's a human being, and a
terrible thing is happening to him. So attention must be paid. He's
not to be allowed to fall into his grave like an old dog. Attention,
attention must be finally paid to such a person.'' _ From Act One of
``Death of a Salesman,'' by Arthur Miller.
</TEXT>
