<DOCNO> AP890130-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   01-30 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Living Years'' (Atlantic) _ Mike + The Mechanics.
   
   No doubt there is sincerity in the lyrics of ``In the Living
Years,'' a song co-written by Mike Rutherford and B.A. Robertson not
long after their fathers died. Unfortunately, there is little
originality in its description of the communication gap between
father and son (``It's too late when we die, To admit we don't see
eye to eye''). And when the music swells for the refrain and a
children's choir joins in, it sounds uncomfortably like another
Artists for Trendy Causes benefit project.
   Aside from that overdose of FEELING, the most striking feature of
this second album by Genesis guitarist Mike Rutherford's other band
is that there is nothing very striking about it. The tunes are
catchy, the production is smooth, the overall sound is perfectly
listenable and the lyrics contain simple, easy-to-understand
messages: ``Nobody's Perfect,'' love is worth believing in, a ``Poor
Boy'' deserves a break.
   There's a life-is-beautiful-because-we're-in-love song, and a
too-bad-we-couldn't-make-love-last song. Each is pleasant to listen
to, each is easy to hum along with, each sounds vaguely as though
you've heard it before.
   Paul Carrack, best known from Squeeze, and Paul Young from Sad
Cafe share the lead vocal duties. Their voices blend together well
enough to give the band a recognizable sound, and the differences in
their styles are used to good advantage to match the lyrics.
   All the songs are well put together and could easily become hits.
Catchy, smooth, listenable, pleasant, hummable hits. Nothing wrong
with that, unless by chance you're tired of '80s music and looking
for something new.
   _ By Dan Murphy, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``C.G.P.'' (Columbia) _ Chet Atkins
   
   Chet Atkins, despite his enormous talent and legendary status
among guitarists, has made a fair number of dull albums in his long
career. ``C.G.P.'' is another one of them.
   On most of the songs, Atkins sounds content to lay back and
pleasantly pick through a selection of light, pseudo-jazz
arrangements. It's backround music, a soundtrack of your last visit
to an office waiting room.
   The Atkins-Mark Knopfler duet on ``Imagine'' says a lot about the
album. The combination has enticing potential, but the two
guitarists approach the John Lennon song in such an easygoing,
gentlemanly manner (as if each one is politely waiting for the other
to take off) that it never gets off the ground.
   More successful are ``Jethreaux,'' in which Atkins' snappy
playing proves that easy-listening doesn't have to mean
sleep-inducing, and ``Put Your Clothes On,'' featuring some lovely
interplay between Atkins and fiddler Johnny Gimble.
   Atkins also delivers a heartfelt vocal on the plaintive ``I Still
Can't Say Goodbye,'' in which the singer recalls his late father.
   The title of the album is an acronym for Certified Guitar Player,
which Atkins certainly is. But on ``C.G.P.'' the music rarely rises
above that of a P.O.R. _ Pretty Ordinary Record.
   _By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Victory Day'' (RCA) _ Tom Cochrane &amp; Red Rider
   
   ``Victory Day'' is a record filled with intelligent lyrics about
alienation and resiliency. Unfortunately, the creativity reflected
in the lyrics is missing from most of the music, which sounds like a
generic imitation of Springsteen, John Cougar Mellencamp and Bryan
Adams.
   The album is the sixth from the Canadian sextet Tom Cochrane &amp;
Red Rider. Songwriter Cochrane's way with words is apparent from the
opening cut, ``Big League,'' sung by a father whose plans for his
son are ruined by a car wreck. Also stirring is the title cut, about
a girl who tries to temper her boyfriend's dreams of grandeur by
arguing that life is about ``small moments ... all strung together.''
   Ironically, while Cochrane ventures beyond the ordinary when
choosing the subjects he sings about, most of the guitar-dominated
arrangements on ``Victory Day'' are utterly predictable. One
exception is ``Good Man (Feeling Bad),'' a simple ballad that allows
a great bass line and Cochrane's singing to carry the song.
   Most of the other cuts are uptempo, but the band sounds
restrained and a little stiff. It's evident that Tom Cochrane &amp; Red
Rider have talent _ Cochrane sings with a certain swagger, and the
band sparkles occasionally, such as on the soaring guitar break of
``Sons Beat Down.'' But next time the guys should cut loose and take
a few chances.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
