<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Miller Adv10-12   01-30 1077</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Miller, Adv 10-12,1120</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Feb 10-12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: A Work of Love</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Miller's newest album, ``Born 2B Blue,''
was a work of love for the veteran musician. It was something he
just wanted to do, rather than a job to create hits.
   The album, his 18th for Capitol Records, includes such staples of
pop and jazz as ``When Sunny Gets Blue'' and ``Willow Weep for Me.''
But there are no Steve Miller tunes on it.
   ``My own artistic sense told me I could sing that stuff pretty
good,'' the 45-year-old singer-guitarist-composer said. ``I couldn't
play it.'' But he got help from a long-time friend, pianist Ben
Sidran.
   ``It's a forward-looking album. I feel like my audience is ready
for this. I've been ready for this for a long time.''
   He'll tour the world for the album next summer. ``We need about a
$3 million budget to get it ready to take around the world. I think
we can do it. If it works we make lots of bucks and on we go for
another five-10-20 years. I'd like to be performing the rest of my
life. I'd like to drop dead on stage, or off-stage and they can
announce, `Ladies and gentlemen, Mr. Miller has just left the
building and the planet.'''
   Miller plans to open the shows solo and acoustically, doing a few
of his big rock hits. Then Sidran will join him.
   ``It'll be the Steve and Ben show for awhile,'' he said. ``Then
his band will come in. We weave our way through blues, jazz and
rock. We've got a real good jazz-rock arrangement on `Space Cowboy.'
We'll invite jazz and blues musicians in that town to solo on `God
Bless the Child' and `When Sunny Gets Blue.' It'll be a well-rounded
evening. I'd like to bring it on Broadway.''
   Sidran and Miller met in 1961 when both studied comparative
literature at the University of Wisconsin. ``He worked on my first
album, `Children of the Future,' and co-wrote `Space Cowboy' with
me,'' Miller said. ``This album has enabled us to work together on a
mature level.
   ``His band came out to play Jazz Alley in Seattle. We brought his
band over to my studio on five afternoons. I would sing. They would
work on the arrangements.'' That was August 1986.
   ``They went on tour. I kept the tapes around. Then I started
listening to them.'' Miller decided he'd like it to become his next
album. ``Ben was down in Los Angeles with the guys. We cut some
more. I asked Ben if he would introduce me to some jazz players.
   ``That's Milt Jackson playing vibes on `Born to Be Blue.' Phil
Woods plays solo on `When Sunny Gets Blue' and `Red Top.' I think
`Red Top' is going to be the most popular song on the record.''
Later, after some live dates with Sidran, Miller redid some vocals
and strings were added.
   ``Born to Be Blue'' was difficult, Miller said, because he had to
run scales and practice. ``It's a Mel Torme tune. I tried to make
things seem seamless and effortless. It was a real job. I found out
how great Mel is.''
   Miller had early musical roots. His mother was from a musical
family and one of his uncles played violin in Paul Whiteman's
orchestra and another uncle played guitat. His father, a doctor and
tape recorder fanatic, was best man at Les Paul and Mary Ford's
wedding. When Miller was 5, the couple showed him guitar licks and
harmonizing.
   ``I wanted to be Les Paul,'' Miller said.
   Miller's father and T-Bone Walker became friends. ``When I was
11, T-Bone taught me how to play guitar behind my head while doing
the splits. I started my first band when I was 12. We played
intermissions at fraternity dances at Southern Methodist. I taught
my older brother to play bass so he could drive me to the gigs.
   ``I went to college, studied in Copenhagen a year, started my
rock 'n' roll career. I was too young and too stupid to go back and
see T-Bone. I wish I had. He totally shaped the way; I am a pupil of
T-Bone Walker when I play lead guitar.''
   Miller decided not to get a doctorate in comparative literature
and instead went to Chicago.
   ``My grad work was done at the University of Blues on the south
side of Chicago,'' he said. ``I spent two years competing with Muddy
Waters, Howlin' Wolf, Junior Wells and Buddy Guy for work in
nightclubs. They tried to steal my gigs and I tried to steal theirs.
We jammed together a lot. It was a very healthy blues scene. It was
getting national attention. Paul Butterfield went East and played
with Dylan. I heard about what was going on in San Francisco; I
headed West.''
   Miller has five platinum albums and, according to Billboard
magazine, three No. 1 singles: ``The Joker,'' ``Rock 'n' Me'' and
``Abracadabra.''
   His commercial success is all rock 'n' roll. ```Fly Like an
Eagle' is rock 'n' roll. I'm going to play it in my jazz show; it'll
go over great.''
   Miller once spent three years away from the business. ``What I
did was finish 14 years of touring. We'd do 11 months a year. It's
the way we sold records. I had done the world 15 times. I had six
Top 10 singles in a row. I remember in 1979 walking off a stage from
an audience of 40,000, handing the guitar to an assistant and
saying, `I don't care if I ever do this again.' I was so tired.
Nothing was spontaneous.
   ``I was rich. I bought a farm in Oregon. In 1982 I moved to
Seattle and started back to work.''
   But Miller had a difficult time making ``Circle of Love.'' He had
just been divorced from his first wife (he has since remarried) and
was not very happy. ``It was not a great album. I just had to make a
record and get going. I received a lot of stinging criticism for
that record,'' he said.
   ``As a reaction I turned around and did `Abracadabra,' the No. 1
selling single in the world in 1983. I felt like, `I can do hit
singles and I'm not washed up.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Feb 10-12</NOTE>
