<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv02   01-30 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 02,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday Feb. 2, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Footprints From First Humans On Moon Should Last A Half Million Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The footprints left on the moon 20 years ago
by Neil Armstrong and Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin should be visible for
another half-million years, says a chemist who studies lunar erosion
rates.
   ``The moon is a quiet place, lacking an atmosphere and therefore
free of wind and rain,'' said James R. Arnold, a ``cosmochemist'' at
the University of California, San Diego.
   But even without an atmosphere, the moon's surface is slowly
eroded _ by bombardment from meteorites and cosmic rays. Arnold said
they eventually will obliterate the footprints left on the lunar
surface when Apollo 11's Armstrong and Aldrin became the first
humans on the moon in July 1969.
   Arnold and his colleagues studied moon rocks retrieved during six
Apollo missions to develop techniques to measure the rates at which
meteorites and solar and galactic cosmic rays erode lunar rocks and
soils.
   The information ``bears directly on many questions about the
evolution of our solar system, including the Earth,'' he said. His
findings were presented during the recent annual meeting of the
American Association for the Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Analysis Shows Narrowing Of Male-Female Difference In Math Skills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The intellectual gap between men and women
has almost closed, with females doing almost as well as males on
tests of mathematical and spatial skills, and men's verbal abilities
nearly matching women's.
   Marcia Linn and and Janet S. Hyde analyzed hundreds of studies of
sex differences and reasoning abilities conducted during the past
two decades and concluded ``the differences are now so small as to
be negligible,'' Linn said at the meeting of the American
Association for the Advancement of Science.
   ``The relatively poorer performance of women compared with men on
tests of spatial and mathematical ability has often been used to
explain the much greater access of men to scientific fields and
higher earning power,'' said a statement by the University of
California, Berkeley, where Linn is a professor of education. Hyde
is a University of Wisconsin psychologist.
   Spatial abilities involve reasoning about images, such as
locating a single figure embedded within a more complex geometric
design.
   Men still outdo women in one major math test _ the Scholastic
Aptitude Test taken by high school seniors _ but it is being revised
to remove any bias that may work to the disadvantage of women, Linn
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Ultrasound Microscope Expected To Improve Disease Diagnosis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Joie is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $375,000 ultrasound microscope that
bounces sound waves off cells or larger samples of body tissues
should speed and improve doctors' ability to diagnose cancer and
other diseases, a scientist says.
   Pieces of suspected tumors or other tissues removed during
surgery or biopsy normally must be fixed, or preserved, and then
stained and placed on a glass slide _ a time-consuming process.
   ``With acoustic microscopes, you essentially throw the hunk of
tissue in the microscope and look at it,'' said Dr. Joie Jones, a
radiology professor at the University of California, Irvine, College
of Medicine.
   The microscope, which operates something like a submarine's
sonar, probes samples of human tissue by bombarding them with sound
waves with frequencies 500,000 times higher than sounds perceptible
by the human ear.
   The waves are changed as they pass through samples, and the
returning waves are converted into a visual picture that can be
viewed directly, photographed, stored on a computer disk or strung
together to create movies.
   By determining the density and elasticity of a cell's membrane,
the microscope can indicate the cell's permeability, or ability to
transport chemicals in and out. The permeability changes when cells
become cancerous, so the microscope can be used to diagnose and
track cancer, Jones said.
   Such uses ``will lead to improved diagnoses of diseases and much
more rapid diagnoses without the elaborate tissue preparation that's
required today,'' he said during a recent interview.
   Jones also said that because the device doesn't destroy the cells
it examines, as X-rays can, it will let scientists watch living
cells in previously unknown detail, and even make movies of cells
dividing.
   Only two of the microscopes exist in the United States. Jones
said the second is used in secret military research at Sandia
National Laboratory in New Mexico, apparently to examine electronic
circuits and other sensitive hardware.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Feb. 2</NOTE>
