<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Autos     01-30 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Autos,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Car Exports Fall in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's exports of cars, trucks and buses declined
for the third consecutive year in 1988, the Japan Automobile
Manufacturers Association said Monday.
   The association said 1988 exports totaled 6.1 million vehicles,
down 3.2 percent from 1987.
   Asociation spokesman Akira Nakayama attributed the decline to a
12.6 percent decrease in sales to the United States, which imported
2,695,836 Japanese vehicles, or 44.1 percent of Japan's total motor
vehicle exports.
   He said the yen's rise against the U.S. dollar made the Japanese
cars more expensive and less competitive in the United States. In
addition, Japanese car makers produced 869,556 cars in the United
States last year, some in joint ventures with U.S. makers, up 18.2
percent from the previous year, Nakayama noted.
   Japan's total vehicle exports declined 1.9 percent in 1986 and
4.5 percent in 1987. Since September 1985, the yen has climbed from
240 yen to one U.S. dollar to less than 130 yen now.
   Nakayama said 1988 exports included 4,431,888 passenger cars,
down 1.7 percent; 1,626,576 trucks, down 7.7 percent, and 45,688
buses, up 29.9 percent from 1987.
   He said Japan exported 2,051,319 passenger cars to the United
States, down 7.0 percent; 644,514 trucks, down 26.8 percent, and
three buses, an increase of two.
   Japan also exported 1,705,363 vehicles to Europe, up 3.8 percent;
473,749 to Southeast Asia, up 36.4 percent; 230,275 to Africa, up
55.5 percent; 225,483 to the Middle East, up 10.7 percent; 105,385
to Central America, down 29.7 percent, and 98,121 to South America,
up 20.5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
