<FIRST>r f BC-SouthKoreaTrade     01-30 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Korea Trade,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ministry Unveils Measures To Trim Trade Surplus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea will send purchase missions
to the United States with shopping lists worth $4 billion to help
ease trade frictions with its big trading partner, Trade and
Industry Minister Hahn Seung-soo said Monday.
   The minister said he feared that the new administration of
President Bush might mount pressure on Korea to further appreciate
its won currency to correct bialteral trade imbalances favoring
Korea.
   Seoul prefers increases in imports to steep revaluation of the
won because the latter approach would tend to slow down Korean
exports while stimulating imports.
   The minister said Korea needs to take steps to expand imports
from the United States before May when Washignton is to designate
unfair trading countries under the tightened U.S. trade law.
   He said that an electronics import mission and a general purchase
mission will tour the United States in March, followed by a farm
products purchase mission in April and another import mission in May.
   The four missions intend to purchase $2.1 billion of electronics
equipment and parts, $1.4 billion of general machienry and parts and
$500 million of aircraft and parts, he said.
   Korea hopes to narrow its overall trade surplus this year,
setting a target of $5 billion, down from $8.9 billion in 1988.
</TEXT>
