<FIRST>r f PM-Baker-Environment     01-30 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Environment,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Opens Conference on Environmental Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James A. Baker III made his first public
appearance today as secretary of state, opening a conference on
environmental problems with a five-minute speech calling for steps
to reduce emissions, improve energy efficiency and reforestation.
   ``We face some very dificult problems,'' he said. ``It's also
true we now recognize them to be problems, and that's at least half
of the battle.''
   In Baker's audience at the State Department was William K.
Reilly, named by President Bush as the administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency. Baker spoke at the opening of a
2{-day conference on climate change attended by officials from
various countries and U.S. agencies.
   Touching on the international scope of climate problems, Baker
said `'this is a transnational issue. We all are in the same boat.
...The tides and winds can spread environmental damages to
continents and hemispheres far removed from the immediate
disasters.''
   ``We probably cannot afford to wait until all of the
uncertainties have been resolved,'' Baker said. ``Time will not make
the problem go away.''
</TEXT>
