<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   01-30 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Prices Higher, Corn Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for wheat were higher, while corn
was lower and soybeans mixed in early trading today on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Wheat was the market leader with prices advancing on the forecast
of colder temperatures at the end of this week in the U.S. growing
area and the signs of more life in the export market, analysts said.
   Overnight, Tunisia was seeking 175,000 tons of U.S. wheat.
   But Egypt's purchase of 100,000 tons of U.S. corn didn't keep
futures prices for that commodity from falling.
   Soybean prices were depressed by reports of scattered showers
improving the South American crop, but gains were made on technical
factors and a spill over in buying from wheat, traders said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 3} cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.42 a bushel; corn was { cent to
1\ cent lower with March at $2.70} a bushel; oats were unchanged to
3 cents lower, with March at $2.12 a bushel; and soybeans were 2
cents higher to 2{ cents lower, with March at $7.53 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat prices advanced in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, cattle were .05 cent to .63 cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in February at 73.72 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .10 cent to .45 cent higher, with March at 83.60 cents a
pound; live hogs were unchanged to .50 cent higher with February at
42.60 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .30 cent to .45
cent higher, with February at 39.05 cents a pound.
   On Friday, cattle prices surged but live hogs and frozen pork
bellies were mixed.
</TEXT>
