<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Chemicals     01-30 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Chemicals,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Nearly Doubles Per-Share Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Chemical Co. reported Monday that its
fourth-quarter and 1988 profits soared to record levels due to
strong demand and tight supplies of its chemical and other products.
   Net income for the three months ended Dec. 31 totaled $635
million, or $3.44 per share, up 80 percent from earnings of $352
million, or $1.85 a share, in 1987. Sales jumped to $4.29 billion
from $3.59 billion.
   The results included $136 million of pre-tax expenses, including
$62 million for pension plan improvments.
   For the year, Dow Chemical netted $2.39 billion, or $12.76 per
share, on sales of $16.68 billion. That compared with income of
$1.24 billion, or $6.47 a share, and $13.37 billion in sales.
   Frank Popoff, Dow president and chief executive officer, said the
company had strong gains in all sectors, and he predicted the same
for this year.
   ``The business environment remains strong as we enter 1989,'' he
said in a statement. ``Prices are firm and demand is healthy, with
most products in tight supply.''
</TEXT>
