<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1439EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Poll-Method Bjt   01-30 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poll-Method, Bjt,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Method Used in Poll on Air Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poll-Air Terror Bjt. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is based
on telephone interviews Jan. 4-12 with 1,162 adults in the
continental United States.
   The phone numbers were selected randomly by computer and
interviews were conducted with the adult who had the most recent
birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the sample.
The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that if every adult
American were asked the same questions, the results theoretically
would be within 3 points of the poll's results, 19 times out of 20.
The error margin is larger for subgroups _ 4 points for men, for
example.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:
   1. Generally, do you think airline security on international
flights is adequate, or not? Yes: 28 percent. No: 56 percent. Don't
know or no answer: 16 percent.
   2. The federal government has directed U.S. airlines to X-ray all
checked baggage on flights from Europe and the Mideast. Should
foreign airlines be required to do the same thing? Yes: 96. No: 2.
DK-NA: 2.
   3. Would you support or oppose requiring airlines to hand-search
all checked baggage on international flights, even if that means
passengers have to show up three hours before takeoff? Support: 73.
Oppose: 22. DK-NA: 5.
   4. Would you support or oppose a ban on carry-on luggage on
international flights? Support: 49. Oppose: 45. DK-NA: 7.
   5. Should the U.S. government publicly announce all terrorist
threats it receives against airlines, even if it gets such threats
on a daily basis and cannot tell if they're legitimate? Yes: 45. No:
45. DK-NA: 9.
   6. How about the airlines _ should they be required to announce
all terrorist threats they receive? Yes: 57. No: 38. DK-NA: 6.
   7. If the United States has proof that another country supported
a terrorist group that attacked U.S. citizens, should the U.S. take
military action against that country? Yes: 55. No: 30. DK-NA: 15.
   a. (If yes) Would you feel that way even if the U.S. military
action might kill innocent people in the other country? Yes: 60. No:
31. DK-NA: 10.
   8. If the United States believes that another country supported a
terrorist group that attacked U.S. citizens, but has no direct
proof, should the U.S. take military action against that country?
Yes: 9. No: 84. DK-NA: 7.
   9. If the United States strikes militarily against countries that
it believes support terrorism, do you think that will increase
terrorist attacks, decrease them, or make no difference? Increase:
31. Decrease: 34. No Difference: 27. DK-NA: 8.
   10. Do you think the U.S. government is doing all it can to
protect American citizens against terrorism, or should it be doing
more? All it can: 36. More: 57. DK-NA: 7.
   11. Do you think the U.S. government can do anything to
significantly reduce terrorist attacks that affect American
citizens, or not? Can: 61. Cannot: 26. DK-NA: 13.
   12. Which do you think poses a greater danger to air travelers _
terrorism or inadequate airplane maintenance? Terrorism: 24.
Maintenance: 64. DK-NA: 12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1510EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f Mexico-Pipeline     01-30 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>Mexico-Pipeline,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Pipeline In Mexico Ruptured, Catches Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 30-inch oil pipeline was out of service for
at least one day Monday after a break and fire that injured six
people, the national oil company said Monday.
   A spokeswoman for Petroleos Mexicanos, also known as Pemex, told
The Associated Press on Monday that the fire had been extinguished
but the pipeline was to be out of service until the break was
repaired, probably by Monday afternoon.
   The spokeswoman, who did not want to be identified by name, said
Pemex had not determined how much oil had been lost as a result of
the damage.
   In a news release Sunday, Pemex said six employees of the Aguilar
Silva construction company were injured in the accident.
   Pemex reported that the pipeline broke when two Aguilar Silva
tractors dropped a section of pipe on the functioning pipeline. The
company is constructing another 48-inch pipeline at the site in
southern Oaxaca state, Pemex said.
   Pemex said that its employees diverted the spilled oil into a
ditch and put out the fire on Sunday.
   Pemex said the accident occurred on the line between the pumping
station at Neuvo Teapa in Veracruz state and the Salina Cruz
refinery.
   The rupture occurred 90 miles from the pumping staton near the
town of Donaji in southern Oaxaca state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890130-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   01-30 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0218</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for soybeans advanced, while wheat
was mixed and corn steady at the close Monday on the Chicago Board
of Trade.
   Wheat prices moved ahead at the start of the day but pulled back
at the end of the session, although contracts for delivery after May
finished up to a nickel higher on fears of winter crop damage,
traders said.
   ``Commission house buying and prospects of colder air moving into
the Midwest send prices ahead. Then the old crop was struggling,
mainly because of no new export business with the Soviets,'' said
Dale Gustafson, a grains analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Soybean prices made gains on technical factors and a spillover in
buying from wheat, said Jerry Gidel, analyst with G.H. Miller.
   ``Corn was quiet,'' Gustafson said. ``It was a follower type
market.''
   At the close, wheat was 2} cents lower to 5 cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.37} a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to } cent higher with March at $2.70} a bushel; oats were
3\ cents to 4{ cents higher, with March at $2.15\ a bushel; and
soybeans were 4 cents 6 cents higher, with March at $7.58 a bushel.
