<FIRST>u f AM-Mexico-Economy Bjt   01-30 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Economy, Bjt,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Labor, Now Business Seeks Revisions to Inflation Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico's business sector is beginning to join
labor in grumbling about the government's successful
inflation-busting program, especially the program's wage-price
freeze.
   Business also has been critical of new taxes imposed under a
federal tax reform plan and increasingly is calling for reversal of
Mexico's free trade policy aimed at fighting inflation.
   For more than a year the government has counted on business
support of the Economic Growth and Stability Pact to counter labor's
anger over the wage freeze.
   The program was implemented after inflation reached 159.2 percent
in 1987, and it cut inflation to 51.2 percent last year _ with
prices growing at a much slower rate by the end of the year.
   The pact's wage and price freezes come up for renewal in July,
and labor has been unhappy with what it considers pro forma minimum
wage hikes of 3 and 8 percent since February 1988.
   Private sector leaders had supported the pact, but complaints
about price controls and profit squeezes surfaced last week when
Commerce Secretary Jaime Serra Puche denied the government had
agreed to lift price controls.
   ``There is no formal commitment of any nature in that sense,''
Serra Puche told a news conference last week. ``What I can assure
you is that inside of six or seven months, there simply will be a
new agreement and we will have, as the president has said, a
permanent effort to find a solution to the problems of this
economy.''
   Vicente Bortoni, director of the influential Confederation of
Industrial Chambers and a member of the pact's supervisory
committee, suggested business would agree to another pact extension
only if the government begins ``to liberate the economy'' and free
prices.
   Another industrialist complained that nationalized banks are
refusing to follow the program.
   Ignacio Munoz, president of the National Association of
Industrialists in Transformation, said last Thursday that bank loans
for new investment carry interest rates of about 80 percent, while
the banks' own borrowing costs run around 49 percent.
   High interest rates discourage new private investment, Munoz
said, while businesses have been forced to absorb a 40 percent
increase in electricity rates, January's 8 percent wage increase and
a 35 percent jump in social security contributions.
   The Business Confederation of the Mexican Republic and the
Coordinating Council of Industrial Associations joined the chorus to
protest a new 2 percent tax on fixed assets.
   The 2 percent tax, part of a tax reform promised by President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari, seeks to reduce the government's fiscal
deficit. But the Confederation and Council contended that the tax
only worsens the private sector's ability to make new investments.
   Further, more industrialists are citing a liquidity squeeze in
urging the government to impose restrictions on imports, a move that
would reverse a 2-year-old trade liberalization policy.
   Former President Miguel de la Madrid employed free trade as a key
anti-inflation tool. Through August, consumer goods imports surged
by 133 percent and capital goods imports by 57 percent, helping to
suppress prices but wiping out Mexico's trade surplus.
   Official data have yet to be published for September, when most
economists believe Mexico began running a trade deficit.
   ``If this problem persists and gets worse, the capital goods
industry in Mexico, which has already been hurt, is going to see the
crisis deepen,'' Elias Meckler, president of the Coordinating
Council, told local reporters last week.
   But Serra Puche ruled out trade barriers. Free trade has been one
of Salinas' key weapons in trying to make Mexico's manufacturers
more efficient, and success in that goal would reduce prices in
Mexico and increase exports.
   Serra Puche declined to say what changes may be in store for the
pact, but said ``the agreement is fundamental, it's been very useful
for the Mexican economy and it will continue being the standard of
the (Commerce) department.''
</TEXT>
