<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     01-30 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0379</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mostly higher in active
trading today.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 3.40 points at
2,319.46 at 3 p.m. EST.
   The broader market was higher, however, continuing to draw
strength from Friday's impressive rally. Advancing issues edged out
declines by about 4-to-3 on the NYSE, with 811 issues gaining, 602
losing and 515 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board was 141.24 million shares.
   ``The market is actually pretty amazing,'' said Bill Raftery, an
analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. ``There's no
profit-taking going on; they're hanging in there.''
   Analysts described today's advance as a continuation of Friday's
surge, when a wave of institutional buying lifted the Dow Jones
average to its highest close since the October 1987 market collapse.
   Today, the widely watched blue-chip indicator was weighed down by
a nearly $4 drop in shares of Texaco Inc., one of its components.
Texaco, the second-most actively traded issue on the Big Board, was
down 3~ at 50|.
   Investors were disappointed by news late Sunday that Texaco had
struck a truce with its biggest shareholder and long-time nemesis,
financier Carl Icahn, who said he would not try to buy the oil giant
or wrest control away from its board of directors.
   The Commerce Department reported today that Americans' personal
income rose 0.9 percent in December after a slight decrease during
November. Analysts said the report stirred some inflationary concern
in the bond market but was largely shrugged off by Wall Street.
   President Bush, in a speech, predicted ``jobs in abundance'' in
the years ahead.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.41 at 165.19.
   On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had
declined 0.09 to 321.48.
   Among other actively traded issues on the NYSE, AT&amp;T had slipped
~ to 30|, Phillips Petroleum was down [ at 20{ and Illinois Central
had tumbled 1[ to 21\.
   RJR Nabisco, the volume leader, had climbed 1~ to 97~, Union
Carbide was up { at 28{, Ford Motor had advanced 1\ to 53} and IBM
had jumped 1{ to 128].
</TEXT>
