<FIRST>r f AM-NYSEAppoint     01-30 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYSE Appoint,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former SEC Litigator Names to NYSE Enforcement Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange said Monday it has
selected a former top enforcement division lawyer for the Securities
and Exchange Commission as a vice president of enforcement for the
exchange.
   Richard J. Sheehan, who had been assistant chief litigation
counsel with the SEC's enforcement division in Washington, takes the
new job immediately, the exchange said.
   There are two vice presidents of enforcement at the NYSE and both
report to David Doherty, the NYSE's senior vice president,
enforcement.
   The announcement said that Sheehan's responsibilities will
include directing the investigation and prosecution of NYSE rules
and federal securities laws.
   With the SEC, Sheehan served as chief counsel for the SEC in the
federal courts for actions involving alleged violations of federal
securities laws.
   Sheehan, 55, had practiced law in St. Louis starting in the 1960s
and until taking the job with the SEC in 1986.
</TEXT>
