<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-RJRNabisco     01-30 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-RJR Nabisco,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco Reports Higher Profit, Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. on Monday reported increased
income and sales for the fourth quarter of 1988, despite expenses
incurred in the company's planned sale to Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp;
Co.
   For the quarter, RJR Nabisco's net income was $411 million, up 11
percent from $370 million in the final quarter of 1987. Net income
per common share came to $1.78, up 22 percent from $1.46 a year
earlier. Sales were $4.7 billion, up 7 percent from fourth quarter
1987 sales of $4.4 billion.
   The Atlanta-based cigarette and food products giant also reported
record sales and profits for the year 1988.
   The company reported 1988 net income of $1.4 billion, up 15
percent from $1.2 billion in 1987. Net income per common share was
$5.92, up 26 percent from $4.70 a year earlier, and sales were $17
billion, up 8 percent from $15.8 billion in 1987.
   RJR Nabisco's companies include R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, Nabisco
Brands, Del Monte Foods and the Planters LifeSavers Co.
   The 1988 results ``were adversely affected'' by tax provisions
for repatriation of some foreign earnings, advisory fees and
``certain other expenses ... incurred in anticipation of the
previously announced merger of the company'' with a corporate arm of
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, said a statement from RJR Nabisco's
corporate headquarters.
   After a bidding war of several months, sparked by a takeover
attempt by RJR Nabisco President F. Ross Johnson, the RJR board late
last year agreed to a $109-per-share takeover offer from KKR. The
$25 billion deal will be the biggest corporate takeover in history.
   Without the tax provisions and expenses the company cited, 1988
net income would have been $1.5 billion, up 26 percent, with
per-share net income of $6.47, up 38 percent, the statement said.
Fourth-quarter net income would have been $539 million, up 46
percent, with per-share earnings of $2.33, up 60 percent.
   The company's tobacco sales in 1988 were up 11 percent, to $7.1
billion, from $6.3 billion a year earlier. The company's food
business recorded sales of $9.9 billion, up 5 percent from $9.4
billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
