<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     01-30 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0346</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mostly higher today in
active trading, buoyed by continued momentum from last week's
impressive rally.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was weighed down most of
the day by a sharp decline in shares of Texaco Inc., one of its
components. But the broader market rose convincingly.
   ``The market is actually pretty amazing,'' said Bill Raftery, an
analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. ``There's no
profit-taking going on; they're hanging in there.''
   Analysts described today's advance as a continuation of Friday's
surge, when a wave of institutional buying lifted the Dow Jones
average to its highest close since the October 1987 market collapse.
   Today, the widely watched blue-chip indicator was held back to
some extent by the drop in Texaco shares.
   Investors were disappointed by news late Sunday that Texaco had
struck a truce with its biggest shareholder and long-time nemesis,
financier Carl Icahn, who said he would not try to buy the oil giant
or wrest control away from its board of directors.
   The Commerce Department reported today that Americans' personal
income rose 0.9 percent in December after a slight decrease during
November. Analysts said the report stirred some inflationary concern
in the bond market but was largely shrugged off by Wall Street.
   President Bush, in a speech, predicted ``jobs in abundance'' in
the years ahead.
   Analysts said the market got a bit of a boost from the robust
dollar and falling prices of oil and gold, although stocks were
fueled mostly by their own steam.
   ``Nobody cares about anything except the market itself,'' said
Michael Metz, an analyst at Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   The dollar's recent strong showing has revived foreign investors'
interest in the stock market, and they and others are poised to jump
into the action in the near future, Metz suggested.
   ``There are buyers waiting in the wings,'' he said. ``There's
plenty of money still waiting to get in.''
</TEXT>
