<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks     01-30 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Sharply Higher But Down From Peaks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices enjoyed another exceptional day on the
London Stock Exchange Monday, soaring to new heights amid heavy
demand from institutional investors.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 37 points, or 1.85 percent, at 2,042.9, after surging as much
as 66.8 points in the afternoon.
   At its minimum the index was up just 9.4 points at the opening.
   ``There are quite a lot of institutions who are still underweight
(in equities). They've got too much cash,'' one dealer said.
   The rise in prices was once again exacerbated by a shortage of
stock on the part of market makers, who sought to draw out a few
sellers in order to fill in their books, market observers said.
   But prices fell off their peaks on profit-taking, dealers said.
   ``One or two institutions have been quite happy to sell some
stock'' to take profits after the market's 13.9-percent rise since
the new year, the dealer said.
   A tentative opening on Wall Street also helped to push prices
down from their best levels.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended 27.5 points higher at
1,666.4. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 19.37 points to
1,148.75.
   Volume was heavy, with 1.06 billion shares changing hands, down
from 1.17 billion shares on Friday.
</TEXT>
