<FIRST>u f AM-RJR-FTC 1stLd-Writethru f0140 01-30 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RJR-FTC, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0140,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>KKR Says It Reaches Tentative Agreement With FTC On RJR Nabisco Takeover</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: recasts lead to move divestment higher. ADDs last graf to provide
FTC background</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. said Monday it
agreed to divest some duplicate product lines it would acquire in
its $24.53 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc. under a tentative
agreement with the staff of the Federal Trade Commission.
   The buyout firm said either RJR Nabisco or Beatrice Co., another
consumer products firm owned by KKR, would sell some of their assets
and businesses after the merger.
   The asset sales would take place within 12 months of final
approval from the FTC commissioners and would include duplicate
products such as respective brands of ketchup, oriental entrees, soy
sauce and packaged nuts, KKR said.
   Atlanta-based RJR Nabisco accepted KKR's $109-a-share offer last
November over a slighlty higher management-led bid. The holding
company, RJR Holdings Corp., has since been formed for the takeover.
   FTC spokeswoman Anna Davis said her office could neither confirm
nor deny that a tentative agreement was reached with KKR.
   The FTC reviews many propsed mergers to determine the effects on
competitiveness and often requires acquiring companies to divest
certain businesses.
</TEXT>
