<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1928EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-GeneralDynamics     01-30 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-General Dynamics,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourth Quarter Helps Defense Company Offset Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Dynamics Corp. on Monday reported strong
fourth-quarter 1988 earnings that helped the company counter losses
it incurred during a 103-day strike at its Electric Boat division in
Groton, Conn.
   Despite the fourth-quarter comeback, net earnings decreased 12.6
percent for the year. Also adversely affecting the results, the
company said, were up-front investments in its advanced tactical
fighter and advanced tactical aircraft projects in Fort Worth, Texas.
   Significant improvements in its Cessna Aircraft and Land Systems
divisions helped General Dynamics post after-tax fourth-quarter
earnings of $110.2 million, or $2.64 per share, on sales of $2.5
billion.
   The company's net income was up 15.6 percent from 1987's amount.
Net earnings for the Oct.-Dec. 1987 period were $95.3 million, or
$2.27 per share, on sales of $2.5 billion.
   For the fourth quarter of 1988, earnings included tax benefits of
$25 million, or 60 cents per share, compared with similar benefits
of $20 million, or 48 cents per share, for the period in 1987.
   General Dynamics' net earnings for all of 1988 were $379 million,
or $9.03 per share, down from $437.3 million, or $10.26 per share,
for all of 1987.
   The company's sales in 1988 were $9.6 billion, compared with $9.4
billion in 1987. Net earnings for the year included tax benefits of
$85 million, or $2.03 per share, compared with those of $80 million,
or $1.88 per share, in 1987.
   Stanley C. Pace, chairman and chief executive officer for the
defense contractor, said orders for more than 100 jet aircraft
received during the year by Cessna brighten the company's future
outlook.
   General Dynamics was recently awarded the construction contract
for the first SSN 21-class Seawolf attack submarine, giving it
lead-ship construction for 16 of the Navy's 19 classes of nuclear
submarines.
   ``This win gives us a decided head start on future construction
contracts in competing for the remaining 29 ships the Navy plans to
build,'' Pace said. A $400 million contract awarded General Dynamics
during the fourth quarter for construction of one SSN 688-class
attack submarine was General Dynamics' 33rd in the class, Pace said.
   General Dynamics' funded backlog at the end of 1988 was $18
billion and its total backlog, funded and unfunded, was $24.5
billion, representing approximately 2.6 years of sales compared with
$17 billion and $22.8 billion at the end of 1987.
</TEXT>
