<FIRST>u f AM-Mergers-WallStreet     01-30 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mergers-Wall Street,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Firms Earn Record Fees from 1988 M&amp;A Binge; Goldman No.
1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporate takeover activity hit record
$311.4 billion last year and Wall Street firms reaped an all-time
high of $1.28 billion in fees for their roles in the deals, a
financial information service said Monday.
   Data compiled by IDD Information Services showed a total of 3,637
mergers and acquisitions were completed in 1988, revising upward its
Jan. 4 estimate that showed a total of 3,310 transactions worth
$282.4 billion were completed.
   The revised figures showed a 41.6 percent jump over the 1987
level of 3,565 deals worth $219.5 billion.
   IDD said fees for merger-related work earned by investment
banking firms, an important source of business in the aftermath of
the October 1987 stock market crash, rose 39 percent last year from
the 1987 level of $801.6 million.
   Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. retained its position as top financial
adviser for the third straight year, working on 158 deals worth
$93.4 billion, IDD said.
   First Boston Corp. ranked second, advising on 153 deals worth
$78.23 billion, despite the loss of its senior executives in charge
of mergers-related work, Bruce Wasserstein and Joseph Perella, who
formed their own firm.
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ranked third, with 211 deals worth
$74.15 billion; Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. ranked fourth, with 125 deals
worth $74.06 billion; Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ranked fifth, with
158 deals worth $39.04 billion, the IDD figures showed.
   Other members of the top 10 included: Wasserstein &amp; Perella,
sixth, with 19 deals worth $35.65 billion; Lazard Freres &amp; Co.,
seventh, with 59 deals worth $34.73 billion; Salomon Brothers,
eighth, with 124 deals worth $31.83 billion; Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.,
ninth, with 1l6 deals worth $24.82 billion; and Kidder Peabody &amp;
Co., 10th, with 73 deals worth $17.75 billion.
   IDD is a leading financial information and publication service
that primarily serves the Wall Street investment banking industry.
</TEXT>
