<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     01-30 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCOJ Rallies; Other Commodities Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fear of a frosty Florida helped spark a rally of futures prices
for frozen concentrated orange juice Monday on the Cotton Exchange
in New York.
   The spot contract for delivery in March rose 515 points or $5.15
cents in active trading.
   ``Basically, there were two reasons _ a correction of oversold
conditions and weather concerns as colder weather is expected to
push into the eastern half of the United States,'' said Judy Ganes,
an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The market has been on the selling side since the first of the
year because of price cuts by processors and expectations of an
abundant Florida crop, Ms. Ganes said.
   Orange juice settled 4.75 cents to 5.15 cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $1.41.90 a pound.
   Futures prices for soybeans advanced, while wheat was widely
mixed and corn steady on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices moved ahead at the start of the day but pulled back
at the end of the session, although contracts for delivery after May
finished up to a nickel higher on fears of winter crop damage,
traders said.
   ``Commission house buying and prospects of colder air moving into
the Midwest sent prices ahead. Then the old crop was struggling,
mainly because of no new export business with the Soviets,'' said
Dale Gustafson, a grains analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Soybean prices made gains on technical factors and a spillover in
early buying in wheat, said Jerry Gidel, another Chicago analyst,
with G.H. Miller.
   Wheat settled 4\ cents lower to 5{ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.37\ a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to { cent higher with March at $2.71 a bushel; oats were 3{
cents to 4{ cents higher, with March at $2.15} a bushel; and
soybeans were 5{ cents 8{ cents higher, with March at $7.60{ a
bushel.
   Cattle prices advanced sharply and pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Higher prices on the wholesale and cash markets, plus a ``bullish
cattle-on-feed report on Thursday'' all helped to bolster cattle
futures, which climbed as much as 135 points or 1.35 cents, said Tom
Morgan, president of Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington Heights,
Ill.,
   Some of the cattle rally spilled over into the live hogs pit and
frozen pork bellies ``were mainly marking time,'' Morgan said.
   Cattle settled .50 cent to 1.35 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in February at 74.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were
.50 cent to 1.10 cents higher, with March at 84.27 cents a pound;
live hogs were .10 cent lower to .50 cent higher with February at
42.60 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were 2.00 cents lower
to .15 cent higher, with February at 39.75 cents a pound.
   Precious metals prices fell on the Commodity Exhcange in New York.
   Futures prices for gold and silver continued to tumble in early
trading after Friday's slump, but they recovered somewhat toward the
end of the session as traders decided the market had been oversold,
said Sharon Ziemian, a trader in New York for Citibank.
   Gold settled 20 cents to 80 cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in February at $395.30 a troy ounce; and silver was 5.3
cents to 7.8 cents lower, with February at $5.83.2 a troy ounce.
   Energy prices were mostly lower in futures trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   Crude oil settled 27 cents to 45 cents lower, with the contract
for delivery in March at $17.29 a barrel; and heating oil was .91
cent lower to .61 cent higher, with February at 52.59 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
