<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     01-30 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped Monday, giving up part of the
gains achieved in Friday's powerful rally in spite of bullish
economic news. Gold prices edged down after Friday's plunge.
   The dollar began to lose ground after traders who had loaded up
on the currency on Friday decided it did not seem to be following
through on the rally as they had hoped, dealers said.
   The dollar failed to rise in response to a Commerce Department
report that Americans' personal income rose 0.9 percent in December,
a figure that ``should have helped the dollar,'' said Bob Morrissey,
senior trader of the Bank of Boston in New York.
   There was no evidence that central banks had intervened to sell
dollars, as they had in an attempt to stem Friday's rally, said John
McCarthy, chief dealer of Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank in New York.
   Earlier in Tokyo, where the business day ends before London's
begins, the dollar rose to 129.73 Japanese yen, up 1.08 yen. In
London Monday the dollar traded at 129.85 yen. In New York the
dollar fell to 129.30 yen from 129.38 Friday.
   In London, the dollar rose against the pound. One British pound
cost $1.7605 Monday, less expensive for buyers than Friday's late
$1.7655. But in New York the pound rose to $1.7625 from $1.7595 late
Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday's late
rates, included: 1.8595 West German marks, down from 1.8650; 1.5808
Swiss francs, down from 1.5875; 1.1813 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1835; 6.3235 French francs, down from 6.3358; and 1,360.5 Italian
lire, down from 1,364.5.
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Friday's
late rates were: 1.8660 West German marks, up from 1.8570; 1.5884
Swiss francs, up from 1.5743; 6.3500 French francs, up from 6.2875;
2.1085 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0880; 1,365.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,352.37; and, 1.1820 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1853.
   Gold bullion prices in London were trading at $394.50 a troy
ounce, down from the closing price of $398.25 Friday.
   Gold in Zurich was trading at a late price of $394, down from a
late bid price of $398.75 a troy ounce Friday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $395.96 bid, down from
$403.99.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $395.30 a troy ounce from $396.10.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was
bid at $394.35 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EST. Friday's price was
unavailable.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.83 bid a troy ounce,
down from $6.02. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery fell to $5.832 a troy ounce from $5.883 on Friday.
</TEXT>
