<FIRST>r f BC-GoldmanSachs     01-30 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Goldman Sachs,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goldman, Sachs Cutting Back 66 Positions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. said Monday it was cutting
back 66 positions in its domestic fixed-income division because of a
slowdown in bond trading and sales.
   The investment firm said the cuts involve less than 1 percent of
its 6,600-person worldwide staff.
   ``This move reflects an industry-wide slowdown in fixed-income
market activity and does not imply any change in direction in our
basic fixed-income business strategy,'' the firm said in a statement.
   Goldman spokesman Ed Ryan said the cuts affect trading, sales and
administrative staff. He said some employees may be given other jobs.
   The cuts, which began in December and are near completion,
primarily affect Goldman's U.S. government bond and mortgage
operations. Ryan said the reductions do not include the firm's
high-yield or municipal bond areas.
   Goldman said the cuts affect about 5 percent of the domestic
fixed-income division, but employees said privately the division
workforce totals about 700, placing the layoffs at close to 10
percent.
</TEXT>
