<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   01-30 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Momentum from last week's impressive rally lifted
the stock market Monday in active trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 1.25 points to
2,324.11, its highest close since the market crash in October 1987.
   The closely watched blue-chip indicator was restrained to some
extent by a $4 drop in shares of Texaco Inc., one of its components.
But the broader market rose convincingly.
   Advancing issues edged declines by about 3-to-2 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 876 up, 570
down and 533 unchanged.
   ``The market is actually pretty amazing,'' said Bill Raftery, an
analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. ``There's no
profit-taking going on; they're hanging in there.''
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 167.83 million
shares, down sharply from 254.87 million in Friday's session _ which
saw the heaviest trading in seven months.
   Analysts described the advance as a continuation of Friday's
surge, when a wave of institutional buying lifted the Dow Jones
average over 2,300 for the first time since the October 1987
collapse.
   On Monday, the drop in Texaco shares dampened the Dow's rise.
Investors were disappointed by news late Sunday that Texaco's
management had struck a truce with its biggest shareholder and
long-time nemesis, financier Carl Icahn, who said he would not try
to buy the oil giant or wrest control away from its board of
directors.
   Texaco, the second-most actively traded issue on the Big Board,
tumbled 4\ to close at 50\.
   The Commerce Department reported that Americans' personal income
rose 0.9 percent in December after a slight decrease during
November. Analysts said the report stirred some inflationary concern
in the bond market but was largely shrugged off by Wall Street.
   Analysts said the market got a bit of a boost from the robust
dollar and falling prices of oil and gold, although stocks were
fueled mostly by their own steam.
   ``Nobody cares about anything except the market itself,'' said
Michael Metz, an analyst at Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   The dollar's recent strong showing has revived foreign investors'
interest in the stock market, and they and others are poised to jump
into the action in the near future, Metz suggested.
   ``There are buyers waiting in the wings,'' he said. ``There's
plenty of money still waiting to get in.''
   Among other actively traded issues on the NYSE, volume leader RJR
Nabisco jumped 2 to finish at 98. The investment firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. said it agreed to divest some duplicate product
lines it would acquire in its $24.53 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco
under a tentative agreement with the staff of the Federal Trade
Commission.
   Union Carbide rose | to 28|, IBM jumped 1~ to 128}, Ford Motor
climbed 1[ to 53| and Polaroid was up | at 40|.
   AT&amp;T fell 1 to 30{, Phillips Petroleum slipped [ to 20{, Illinois
Central dropped 1\ to 21[ and Southern Co. was unchanged at 23~.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 202.66 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market rose $9.60 billion, or 0.33
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was up
0.58 at 165.36.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index increased 1.41 to 340.96, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index rose 1.17 to 294.99.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
1.26 to 399.22. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 321.88, up 0.31.
