<FIRST>u f AM-AutoDealers Bjt   01-30 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Dealers, Bjt,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Import Dealer Group President Blasts Iacocca</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outgoing president of an import car
dealers organization on Monday criticized Chrysler Corp. Chairman
Lee Iacocca for backing a move to stick a 25 percent tariff on
imported vans and sport utility vehicles.
   The Treasury Department in Washington is considering a plan that
would reclassify the hot-selling vehicles as trucks, instead of
cars. That would raise the import tariff from 2.5 percent to 25
percent of the vehicle's value, and add an estimated $2,000 to
$3,000 to price tags.
   Iacocca, General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith and Ford Motor
Co. Chairman Donald Petersen signed a joint letter to Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady on Jan. 16 saying that without the change,
the domestic industry would be hurt and the Treasury would lose
millions of dollars in potential revenue.
   Robert McElwaine, who has been president of the American
International Automobile Dealers Association for 19 years, accused
Iacocca of backing the move only to benefit Chrysler.
   Boosting tariffs on the foreign vehicles could prompt customers
to buy domestically-produced alternatives.
   ``Lee Iacocca thinks Americans should feel ashamed and humiliated
because the Treasury Department didn't cave into his little scheme
that would cost consumers more than a billion dollars a year and,
not incidentially, add a half-billion to Chrysler Corp.'s already
swollen profits,'' McElwaine said during a speech.
   McElwaine and others in New Orleans for the National Automobile
Dealers Association convention said changing the tariff would be
disasterous for some importers and import dealers.
   One such company is Range Rover of North America Inc., whose
luxury sport-utility vehicle made in England is the only vehicle the
company sells in the United States. President Charles Hughes said
the Customs Service classified the vehicle as a car in 1984, when it
first was introduced in the United States.
   The price of a Range Rover, if the 25 percent fee is imposed,
would climb past $40,000.
   ``I don't think anybody can look us in the face and say a $40,000
vehicle is designed to haul goods,'' Hughes said.
   The ruling also could affect dealers such as Herb Overstreet, who
sells Nissans in Lakeland, Fla. Nissan now imports its Pathfinder
from Japan.
   ``It (the Pathfinder) is a small percentage of my business,''
Overstreet said. ``We just have not had the availability.'' He also
said he now sells all the Pathfinders he can get and would like to
have more.
   ``It (the new tariff) would just kill sales,'' he said. ``We have
our fingers crossed.''
   Nissan's Tom Mignanelli, executive vice president for operations,
said one of the company's options is to move production of the
Pathfinder to its plant in Smyrna, Tenn. That move would take about
a year, but would enable Nissan to avoid the increased tariff on the
vehicle, he said.
   ``One way or another, we will not give up an inch in
Pathfinders,'' he said.
   But the future for Nissan's Axxess minivan, to be introduced in
March as a 1990 model, isn't as guaranteed, Mignanelli said.
   ``There is the possibility that if the tax stays on, Axxess is in
jeopardy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
