<FIRST>u f AM-Economy 2ndLd-Writethru f0136 01-30 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0136,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Personal Income, Savings Rebound In 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 2nd graf pvs with other economic news;
PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `In December...; Stands for Economy Rdp.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' after-tax incomes shot up 3.8
percent last year, with some of the extra money going to raise the
nation's personal savings rate from the 40-year low it had hit just
a year before, the government said Monday.
   The Commerce Department said the gain in income, adjusted for
inflation, was the best since a 3.9 percent gain in 1986 and more
than double 1987's 1.7 percent.
   In other economic news, the stock market continued its march past
pre-crash levels Monday, while a new survey showed the cost of
employer-sponsored health-care plans increased dramatically last
year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 1.25 points to
2,324.11, its highest close since the market crash in October 1987.
   The health-care survey by A. Foster Higgins &amp; Co. in New York
found that health-care costs rose 18.6 percent per worker last year
after increases of 7.7 percent in 1986 and 7.9 percent in 1987.
   In December, personal income totaled $4.2 trillion, with much of
the $37.1 billion jump from November resulting from farm subsidy
payments. Without those outlays, the government said, December's
total income would have been up 0.8 percent.
   Last year's income gains spurred both spending and saving:
   _Consumer spending rose 2.8 percent after adjusting for
inflation, following increases of 2.7 percent in 1987 and 4.3
percent in 1986.
   In December alone, spending rose 0.9 percent, with the biggest
increase, 4.1 percent, posted for durable goods _ ``big ticket''
items expected to last three or more years.
   _The average personal savings rate rose a full percentage point,
from 3.2 percent to 4.2 percent, the highest since the 4.4 percent
set in 1985.
   The 1987 rate was the smallest since a 3.1 percent rate in 1947.
   In all, economists said the figures were a good sign for
continued economic strength in the coming year.
   ``There's a balanced picture for consumers, with a strong
increase in income, a solid increase in spending and some increase
in savings,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co.
``All three of those ... are quite desirable if the expansion is
going to keep on rolling along.''
   Added Robert G. Dederick, an economist with Northern Trust Co. in
Chicago:
   ``People continue to fill their wallets and then they continue to
empty them and this clearly should provide the impetus for a further
push in growth in the first half of 1989.''
   However, Lawrence Chimerine, head of the WEFA Group, an economic
consulting firm in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., cautioned that much of the
year's income growth came from increases in employment and could not
be expected to continue unabated. Joblessness was at a 14-year low
in 1988.
   ``Once we run out of people to put into the labor force, we'll
see much smaller growth in income,'' Chimerine said.
   Both Dederick and Chimerine said the savings rate still was too
low and that while the spending and income picture for 1988 was
generally good, high levels of spending have made it more difficult
to narrow the nation's trade deficit as consumers fail to curb their
appetite for foreign goods.
   The year ended on a strong note as personal income in December,
before adjusting for inflation, rose 0.9 percent.
   Wages and salaries, a key component of income, were up 0.6
percent to $2.53 trillion in December following a revised 0.3
percent gain a month earlier. The volatile category of farm income
soared 73.2 percent to $23.9 billion after plunging 66.8 percent in
November.
   Sinai said the year-end strength ``was impressive and suggests
that consumers will have the wherewithall to keep spending for a
number of months.''
   ``There are no impediments in sight to continued good growth in
income and consumption,'' he said. ``The consumer is supportive of
our expansion at this point, neither spending in a boom-like way nor
showing any signs of a fade in spending.''
</TEXT>
