<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     01-30 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Fall; Heating Oil Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices closed mixed in uneventful
trading Monday as investors continued looking for signals that would
spur prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled 45
cents lower at $17.29 a barrel. Other contract months also fell.
   Among refined products, the February contract for heating oil
surged 0.61 cent to close at 52.59 cents a gallon, while other
contract months were mixed.
   The February contract for unleaded gasoline fell 0.71 cent to
settle at 48.88 cents a gallon as other contract months also lost
ground.
   Traders said forecasts of cold weather and sub-freezing
temperatures in Alaska helped strengthen heating oil prices.
   ``The Alaskan pipeline is partially closed because of the storms,
shutting down 1 million barrels of exports,'' said Bob Baker, an
energy futures analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   In the crude market, investors waited for further word from the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries following last week's
meeting between technical experts from OPEC and non-OPEC countries.
   The meeting focused on possible production cuts by non-OPEC
producers in an effort to stabilize prices. The experts agreed on
the need to take further steps to support prices, but took no
definitive action to do so.
</TEXT>
