<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 1849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CableDeal     01-30 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable Deal,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Artists, United Cable Keep Talking But Expect to Miss Deal
Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of Denver-based cable companies, United
Cable Television Corp. and United Artists Communications Inc., said
Monday they cannot meet the Feb. 28 deadline for their
previously-announced merger but that are continuing their talks on a
business combination.
   Analysts said they expect the deal to proceed but possibly at a
slightly higher price than the $1.6 billion value they had placed on
the original deal.
   The proposed merger, which involves a complicated cash-and-stock
swap, would create the nation's third-largest cable concern.
   The companies, who cancelled an all-stock merger plan after the
October 1987 stock market crash, announced last March they had
agreed to a cash-and-stock merger.
   But on Monday, the companies said in a joint statement that
because of ``delys resulting from regulatory requirements,'' the
deal could be terminated by either party because the closing cannot
occur by the Feb. 28 deadline specified in the agreement.
   The companies also said they were ``discussing on what terms any
business combination between United Cable and United Artists could
go forward.''
   A spokesman for United Artists Communications said he could not
elaborate on the statement. A call was placed to United Cable but it
was not returned.
   One official familiar with the discussions but speaking on
condition that he not be identified said the delays involved
securing Securities and Exchange Commission approval for a proxy
statement outlining the terms of the deal.
   ``It's a process that seems to have taken longer than
anticipated,'' he said. He said the Feb. 28 deadline could not be
met because the companies must allow 20 business days after mailing
proxy statements before a shareholder vote can be taken on the deal.
   The proposal would allow United Cable's shareholders to convert
their shares into either $35 in cash or stock in the new company
with a separable right to sell a share of the new company's stock at
special terms. The cash portion of the deal was available on up to
49 percent of United Cable's 46.4 million fully diluted shares.
   United Artists shareholders would have the right to convert their
stock on a one-for-one basis into stock of the new concern, which
would be called United Artists Entertainment Co.
   Sharon Armbrust, a senior analyst for the media research concern
Paul Kagan Associates Inc. of Carmel, Calif., said the companies
have invested too much time and energy in the deal to let it fall
through but said it may proceed on renegotiated terms.
   ``There may be a little more money on the table for the United
Cable shareholder,'' she said.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, United Cable rose 12{
cents a share to $35.25 while United Artists Communications fell 50
cents a share to $30 in national over-the-counter trading.
   Each of the companies have about 1.2 million subscribers, and the
combination would put the new company third in terms of subscribers
behind cable industry leaders Tele-Communications Inc., based in
Englewood, Colo., and American Television and Communications Corp.,
a unit of Time Inc.
   United Artists Communications also is one of the nation's biggest
motion picture operators.
   Tele-Communications owns 65.5 percent of United Artists
Communications and 23.7 percent of United Cable, and would own about
52 percent of the new company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
