<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2024EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Boeing     01-30 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Boeing,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Rose 23.4 Percent in 4th-Qtr, 28 Percent in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. said Monday its profit rose 23.4
percent in the fourth quarter and 28 percent for the full year,
citing higher sales, lower federal tax rates and lower spending on
research and new-business expenses.
   Fourth-quarter earnings were $174 million, or $1.14 a share, up
from $141 million, or 92 cents per share, a year earlier.
   Fourth-quarter sales rose 5 percent to $4.87 billion from $4.64
billion in 1987.
   For the year, Boeing earned $614 million, or $4.02 a share, up
from $480 million, or $3.10 a share, a year earlier.
   Sales for the year totaled $16.96 billion, 9.4 percent higher
than $15.50 billion in 1987.
   Boeing said the factors that helped boost earnings were partially
offset by ``significant performance problems'' on some military
programs, increased cost-share expenses on government contracts, and
increased costs of research, development and building up production
rates at Boeing's deHavilland Canadian subsidiary.
   Boeing set industry records in 1988 for new commercial jets
ordered: 636 planes worth about $30.1 billion. The previous records
were 461 planes ordered in 1978, and new orders valued at $20.2
billion in 1987.
   The backlog of firm orders totaled $53.6 billion at Dec. 31,
compared with $33.2 billion at the end of 1987.
   The company delivered a total of 337 commercial airplanes,
compared with 299 in 1987. Boeing plans to deliver a total of 401
planes in 1989, including 57 747s.
</TEXT>
