<FIRST>r f AM-PCStandard     01-30 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PC Standard,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>PC Makers Say New Standard Computers Out By End of 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of rivals to International Business
Machines Corp. predicted Monday that new personal computers based on
the so-called EISA standard would be on sale by the end of 1989.
   The group's Extended Industry Standard Architecture is intended
to challenge IBM's Personal System-2 by offering some of the same
features as IBM's computers while sticking closer to the old PC
standard.
   Members of the group include Compaq Computer Corp., Tandy Corp.,
Zenith Electronics Corp. and Japan's NEC Corp.
   The group said all key aspects of the EISA specification have
been agreed upon and sent to more than 100 manufacturers and
developers. It said enegineering samples of key chips would be
available from Intel Corp. in the April-June period, and production
shipments would be available in the second half of the year.
</TEXT>
