<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Chemicals     01-30 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Chemicals,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Fourth-Quarter Earnings Soar 80 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong sales of basic chemicals and
plastics as well as industrial and consumer goods helped Dow
Chemical Co.'s fourth-quarter earnings soar nearly 80 percent, the
company said Monday.
   Dow reported earnings of $635 million, or $3.44 a share, in the
three months ended Dec. 31, up from $352 million, or $1.85 a share,
in the fourth quarter of 1987.
   Sales for the quarter were $4.3 billion, up from $3.6 billion in
the year-earlier period.
   Frank Popoff, president and chief executive officer, said the
gains came from strong domestic and overseas performances in each of
Dow's four business segments.
   For all of 1988, Dow reported net income of $2.41 billion, or
$12.76 a share, up 93 percent from $1.25 billion, or $6.47 a share,
in 1987.
   Sales rose to $16.68 billion from $13.38 billion in 1987.
   In addition to basic chemicals and basic plastics, Dow makes
industrial specialities, such as Styrofoam insulation and
polycarbonate materials for uses such as auto parts.
   The company also produces consumer specialties such as plastic
wrap, glass cleaner and pharmaceuticals. Pharmaceutical products
include Nicorette gum to aid in quitting smoking, and Seldane, a
non-sedating antihistamine.
   Popoff said all four business segments set income records for the
year, though detailed figures on the segments, or on Dow's
performance domestically compared with other markets, will not be
available for several days.
</TEXT>
