<DOCNO> AP890130-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-30-89 2305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HollyFarms-Tyson     01-30 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms-Tyson,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Order Against Tyson In Bid For Holly Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge issued a restraining order
against Tyson Foods Inc. on Monday, saying the company may have
violated federal securities law to gain an undue advantage over
ConAgra Inc. in their billion-dollar fight to acquire rival poultry
processor Holly Farms Corp.
   Tyson, which has offered to buy Holly Farms for $1.15 billion,
was ordered to refrain from making false, misleading, inaccurate or
incomplete statements involving Holly Farms.
   Senior Judge Richard Robinson issued the order in U.S. District
Court here at the request of Omaha-based ConAgra. Holly Farms has
agreed to be acquired by ConAgra in a $1 billion stock swap, but
invited both of its suitors to submit further bids.
   Kirk Blecha, a Tyson attorney, said the decision was being
reviewed by company lawyers.
   ``There does appear that there was a serious breach in Tyson's
obligation under federal securities law which resulted in Tyson
attaining an unfair advantage in its efforts to acquire Holly
Farms,'' Robinson said.
   He said his temporary restraining order would extend until Feb.
9, the date for a hearing on whether to make it permanent.
   ConAgra alleged that Tyson officials issued false statements in
interviews and press releases Jan. 19 and 20.
   The statements indicated Holly Farms' board had recommended
accepting Tyson's offer of $63.50 per share, ConAgra officials said.
   At the time, ConAgra said, the only tender offer before
shareholders was $60 per share.
   ConAgra said the information caused heavy trading in Holly Farms'
stock and that Holly shareholders were induced to sell their stock
prematurely. The number of shares of Holly stock tendered to Tyson
increased from nearly 1.3 million to 5 million.
   ConAgra said Holly shareholders were mistakenly tendering their
shares at $60 a share, thinking Tyson's tender offer was $63.50 per
share.
   The statements were aimed at preventing ConAgra's merger with
Memphis, Tenn.-based Holly Farms, ConAgra charged.
   Tyson, based in Springdale, Ark., said information in press
releases it issued was correct at the time it was issued, and that
at one point in its negotiations with Holly Farms, the Holly Farms
board had accepted its $63.50-per-share offer.
   The Holly Farms board later issued a statement that it would not
accept Tyson's offer of $63.50 per share.
   Tyson said ConAgra was trying to prevent Tyson from disclosing
any information about its offer to Holly.
   Robinson said his order requires only that Tyson exercise
``circumspection'' in making statements to inform shareholders and
investors.
   Tyson is the nation's largest poultry processor, while ConAgra
ranks second and Holly Farms is third.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
